<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More public Hillary Clinton agrees to appear at satire show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Continuing to venture out of the White House cocoon
that has shielded her for the past seven years, Hillary Rodham Clinton has
agreed to take the stage at the nation's longest-running political gridiron
show.
<P>
	   The first lady, fresh from her star turn on the "Late Show with David
Letterman" and set to formally enter New York's Senate race next month, accepted
an invitation to be part of the 100th annual Legislative Correspondents
Association show on June 10 in Albany. Through political satire performances,
reporters and LCA alumni poke fun at politicians and government officials.
</P>
<P>
	   "We'll have to get the home office in Chappaqua working overtime on this,"
Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign committee, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton, who had never lived or worked in New York before, recently
moved into a house in Chappaqua in Westchester County just north of New York
City to establish New York residency for her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
	   The first lady's expected opponent for the Senate race, New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, has also been invited to appear at the LCA show. There was no
immediate response Friday from the mayor on whether he planned to attend.
</P>
<P>
	   As a featured guest, Republican Giuliani did a lengthy monologue at the
LCA's 1991 show.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent weeks, as she draws closer to formally entering the Senate race,
the notoriously media-shy Mrs. Clinton has begun conducting regular
question-and-answer sessions with reporters during campaign stops. She mixes
easily with people who happen to show up at her events. The first lady is also
planning a series of in-depth interviews in the days leading up to her early
February campaign kickoff.
</P>
<P>
	   That is a far cry from her early forays onto the New York political stage
last year when she rarely left the security of her Secret Service detail and
contact with the public generally involved little more than some handshaking
along a rope line. Questioning by reporters was rare.
</P>
<P>
	   That is in sharp contrast to Giuliani, who holds a "media availability"
almost daily.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent polls have shown the mayor leading the first lady among New York
voters and some of her aides have been advising a more open approach to
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
	   In agreeing to appear at the LCA show, Mrs. Clinton is accepting what has
become almost a rite of passage in New York politics for major candidates. In
1998, then-U.S. Rep. Charles Schumer took a turn. Five months later, Democrat
Schumer defeated Republican incumbent Alfonse D'Amato in that year's U.S. Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
	   Traditionally, once the reporters have finished skewering the politicians
with songs and skits, the governor and two guests, one Republican and one
Democrat, are invited to offer responses - generally humorous speeches or more
elaborate skits.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfson said Friday that he wasn't yet sure what Mrs. Clinton would do.
</P>
<P>
	   The black-tie, $175-a-person dinner and show raises money for charity and to
support LCA operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Initially, the Hillary Clinton campaign team appeared to have rejected the
LCA's invitation.
</P>
<P>
	   In a Jan. 10 letter to LCA President David Hepp, co-host of the "Inside
Albany" television show, Mrs. Clinton's scheduling director, Paul Rivera, had
written that "Mrs. Clinton's official schedule will not permit her to accept the
invitation."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about the rejection, Wolfson had said Thursday that he believed there
had been a mistake. By this morning, Hepp had a new letter in hand from Rivera
stating that the first letter "was sent in error."
</P>
<P>
	   "Please be assured that we plan to participate in the show," Rivera wrote in
the second letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 0012 </TRAILER>
