<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snow's arrival means ski time, if it's not too cold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LATHAM, N.Y. (AP) - Mike Lilleberg stood before the long rack of skis at
Ski Market, fingering the multicolored runners with a determined look.
<P>
	   "I've skied in Tahoe and Montana and I was planning on buying skis anyway,"
he said, "but the snow was a good motivator."
</P>
<P>
	   Like dozens of other customers, Lilleberg made a late Friday run to the ski
store envisioning newly frosted slopes. With up to ten inches of snow having
fallen in Albany in two days, he knew the time had come.
</P>
<P>
	   With the new snow falling on top of the manufactured snow that ski resorts
have been producing for a month, mountains in eastern New York and neighboring
states seemed a skiers paradise. But there could be one problem: high winds
accompanied the first snow of the season. That meant some would-be skiers were
reluctant to hit the slopes and resort operators worried they might have to
close down trails because of the intense cold.
</P>
<P>
	   A Whiteface Mountain employee said temperatures early Friday night reached
17 degrees below zero at the summit and four at the base. The ski resort was
considering closing lifts to the summit if the wind continued.
</P>
<P>
	   Employees at ski shops across eastern New York said business picked up
steadily through the week as the first big storm of the season approached and
finally coated the landscape picture-perfect white.
</P>
<P>
	   "We cut the staff back by 40 percent last week," Ruth Strothers, assistant
manager at the Ski Market said, laughing. "Now we're too busy."
</P>
<P>
	   Customers milled through the Ski Market in the Albany suburb of Latham,
sticking their hands into bin after bin of big leather gloves and ski masks,
eyeing racks of designer sunglasses and goggles and staring up at walls covered
with brightly-colored parkas and jackets.
</P>
<P>
	   Others ran in from the windy parking lot to pick up skis they dropped off
for repairs, pausing to chat about conditions before running back to their cars.
</P>
<P>
	   Winds of 15 to 20 mph were expected in Buffalo this afternoon on top of a
high of around 30 degrees, according to the National Weather Service. Slopes
around Syracuse are expected to be only slightly friendlier, with winds of 10 to
15 mph on top of a high of between 20 and 25 degrees.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Albany area, the wind chill Friday night made for brutally cold
weather. Winds were expected to decrease this afternoon, but the high was still
expected to hang on to the underside of 20 degrees.
</P>
<P>
	   That was bad news for Christine Jevons and her son Aaron, who were shopping
for snow boarding supplies at the Ski Market.
</P>
<P>
	   "I told him it's going to be bitter, bitter cold," Mrs. Jevons said, adding
she wasn't about to accompany her son on the slopes of Massachusetts' Brodie
Mountain today.
</P>
<P>
	   Aaron added, "If I wasn't skiing, then I wouldn't like this weather."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 0012 </TRAILER>
