<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late night host David Letterman undergoes quintuple bypass  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - While trading quips with a guest during a taping of his
late night show, David Letterman mentioned he was about to undergo heart tests -
joking that at worst, doctors would have to "open daddy's rib cage."
<P>
	   His prediction to fellow talk show host Regis Philbin became reality Friday
when doctors performed emergency quintuple bypass surgery on the 18-year veteran
of wisecracks and after-dark celebrity interviews.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors say Letterman is recovering from the surgery, but they are unsure
when the late-night television stalwart will return to his interviewing chair.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's very good," said operating surgeon Dr. O. Wayne Isom, when
asked of Letterman's outlook during an interview on CNN.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman spokesman Steven Rubenstein said CBS will telecast reruns of the
"Late Show with David Letterman" while the host recovers.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're thrilled that Dave's surgery went well," said his network in a
statement. "He is a valued member of the CBS family, and we love him. We are
concerned first and foremost about his health, but we can't wait until he's back
behind his desk where he belongs."
</P>
<P>
	   The decision to operate was made after Letterman, 52, underwent an angiogram
because of high cholesterol and a history of heart disease in his family. The
test, during which a flexible tube is inserted into an artery and dye is
injected, revealed one artery was seriously constricted.
</P>
<P>
	   Isom performed the successful surgery on Letterman at Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center. The doctor said it went smoothly and predicted a rapid recovery.
</P>
<P>
	   "Dave has the heart muscle of a 20-year-old," Isom said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman's personal physician, Dr. Louis J. Aronne, and his cardiologist,
Dr. Martin Post, said it was too early to determine how long recovery would
take.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Amarkanth Saxena, a cardiothoracic surgeon at St. Joseph's Medical
Center in Paterson, N.J., said if there are no complicating factors Letterman
should be hospitalized for three or four days, then recuperating at home for six
to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Saxena, who is not involved in Letterman's case but has performed bypass
surgery many times, said he would advise such a patient to control risk factors
like high blood pressure and cholesterol in the future, in part by avoiding
fried foods and red meat.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman also may need medication to control his cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
	   Like everything else, Letterman has made a long-running joke of his health,
starting years ago when he discovered he had high cholesterol. For a month he
went on an oat-bran diet, complaining nightly about the taste and consistency of
the stuff. Comically, it played. Health-wise it didn't. At the end of the
experiment Dave said he hadn't improved much.
</P>
<P>
	   During Thursday night's taping of the program - which aired Friday - he
joked about it again with Philbin, who asked about Letterman's cholesterol
level.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's borderline ... 680," Letterman quipped. Doctors usually recommend
people keep their cholesterol levels under 200.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman was born in Indianapolis on April 12, 1947. He broke into network
television on CBS in 1978 as a guest on Mary Tyler Moore's variety show, "Mary."
</P>
<P>
	   From there, it was "The Tonight Show" starring Johnny Carson, long regarded
as THE place for aspiring standup comedians to catch their big breaks. Letterman
also guest hosted "Tonight" numerous times.
</P>
<P>
	   After a brief stint as the host of daytime's "The David Letterman Show," his
after-dark career took off with "Late Night with David Letterman." It premiered
in 1982 in the time slot following "Tonight."
</P>
<P>
	   During his 11-year run on NBC, Letterman won five Emmy awards, but moved to
CBS in 1993 shortly after Carson retired and NBC gave the coveted "Tonight Show"
host position to rival Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
	   "I and everyone at The Tonight Show wish Dave a speedy recovery," Leno said.
</P>
<P>
	   The slightly flashier, slightly softer "Late Show with David Letterman" has
brought the longtime host three more Emmy awards.
</P>
<P>
	   Mujibur Rahman, who runs a shop near The Ed Sullivan Theater where "Late
Show" tapes, and who has frequently appeared on the show as a straight-man for
the host, said he watched television all day in hopes of catching an update
about his friend.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm praying for him and his good health. I hope nothing will happen," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Greg James, a 27-year-old fan from Portland, Ore., who apparently shares
Letterman's sense of dark comedy, blamed the entertainer's condition on the
stress of hosting first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on the show earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   "I guess Hillary did it to him," James said. "Too much pressure."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 0115 </TRAILER>
