<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Crackdown Tries To Tame Athens  </HEADLINE>
   By BRIAN MURPHY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Suddenly, there's something missing from downtown
Athens. Cars and motorbikes aren't jammed onto sidewalks. Double-parked vehicles
don't linger for hours. Traffic is actually moving in one direction on one-way
streets.
</P>
<P>
	   What's left are the sounds of police scratching out tickets and motorists
gnashing their teeth over an abrupt halt to Athens' notorious traffic
free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What's this?'' complained motorist Takis Choropoulou as he plucked a
parking ticket from his car, which was left perched over a curb. ``Since when
are there parking rules?''
</P>
<P>
	   The change came after traffic enforcement authorities decided this week to
assign hundreds of police to roam central Athens in search of scofflaws. Since
Monday, more than 5,000 parking tickets have been issued in a new no-tolerance
zone covering areas near the Acropolis and parts of the city's central business
district.
</P>
<P>
	   Police promise to keep up the pressure. Foot patrols are nudging along
double-parked vehicles and intercepting drivers zipping up one-way streets as a
shortcut. Even the thousands of motorbike drivers who weave through central
Athens are feeling the squeeze. Many sidewalks have been declared off limits to
scooter parking.
</P>
<P>
	   The blitz is part of a larger attempt to tame Athens' unruly reputation. The
mayor, Dimitris Avramopoulos, has promoted ideas such as pedestrian zones and
saving the limited green space in the urban maze. A long-delayed subway
extension is expected to go into service later this month with hopes of easing
the monumental gridlock in a metropolitan area that holds nearly half of
Greece's 10.2 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   But order is not always easily imposed on Greeks -- especially when it comes
to their cars.
</P>
<P>
	   For decades, there has been a tacit understanding between motorists and
officials in Athens. Drivers could generally set their own traffic rules and
wedge their vehicles almost anywhere without a serious risk of being fined.
Enforcement was held in check in an apparent acknowledgment that motorists had
no other options. Parking lots are very scarce, public transportation is
traditionally weak and the rampant growth of greater Athens since the 1950s has
put nearly 2 million vehicles onto a road network designed for a fraction that
number.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is anarchy,'' said Giorgos Kanellaides, a professor of highway
planning at the Athens Polytechnic University.
</P>
<P>
	   Some drivers believe the chaos is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's its Greek way,'' said Manolis Psaropoulos, a delivery man for an
electrical supply company. ``The situation forces us to drive and park like
madmen. Where is the parking? Why does it sometimes take hours just to get
somewhere in the city?''
</P>
<P>
	   Since the 1970s, Athens has imposed an odd-even number system that limits
daytime circulation in the city center depending on the last digit of license
plates. But officials have so far resisted trends in other European cities to
strictly curb private vehicle access to the center.
</P>
<P>
	   Some urban planners say blocking most traffic from the center may be the
only solution, particularly when Athens begins to spruce up to host the 2004
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a little while we will have so many cars that we will not know where to
put them,'' said Andonis Statopoulos, an associate professor of traffic
engineering at the Polytechnic University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0120 </TRAILER>
