<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mighty Ducks 3, Blues 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Marty McInnis got the go-ahead goal and Paul Kariya
scored his first power-play goal in nine games as the Anaheim Mighty Ducks ended
the St. Louis Blues' eight-game unbeaten streak with a 3-1 victory Friday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Guy Hebert, who played for the Blues until the Ducks made him their first
pick in the 1993 expansion draft, made 36 saves, and Ladislav Kohn ended a
12-game goal-scoring drought to help Anaheim snap a seven-game winless streak
and hand the Blues their third loss in 17 games (10-3-4).
</P>
<P>
	   Stephane Richer played his first game with the Blues after being obtained on
Thursday from the Tampa Bay Lightning. The 15-year veteran right wing, playing
for his fourth NHL team, assisted on Pierre Turgeon's second-period goal.
</P>
<P>
	   McInnis opened the scoring 4 1-2 minutes into the second period with his
eighth goal. Antti Aalto, playing for the first time in 16 games since spraining
his left elbow on Dec. 4, sent the puck behind the net while taking a hard check
against the right boards. McInnis then converted Mike Leclerc's cross-ice pass,
beating Jamie McLennan to the stick side.
</P>
<P>
	   Kariya made it 2-0 at 10:15 of the period, scoring his 19th goal just 14
seconds into a two-man advantage. Teemu Selanne carried the puck around the left
circle and set up Kariya with a little backhanded flip through the crease.
</P>
<P>
	   It could have been worse for the Blues, but McLennan slowed the Ducks'
momentum with sprawling saves against Leclerc and Jeff Nielsen during the next
minute.
</P>
<P>
	   Hebert stopped the first 25 shots by the Blues, who took 14 in each of the
first two periods after recording only 16 in Thursday night's 3-2 victory at Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   But Turgeon narrowed the gap to 2-1 at 14:52 of the second with his 22nd
goal and 100th since joining the Blues in a trade from Montreal in October 1996.
He stuffed a rebound under Hebert after the Ducks' goalie stopped Richer's wrist
shot from the top of the left circle.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohn restored Anaheim's two-goal margin at 2:08 of the third period with his
third goal, helping the Ducks beat St. Louis at home for the first time in seven
tries (1-5-1). Kohn beat McLennan high to the glove side with a 15-foot wrist
shot after Matt Cullen set him up with a slick drop-pass between his legs.
</P>
<P>
	   Al MacInnins, last season's Norris Trophy winner as the NHL's top
defenseman, left the game with a bruised chest after getting slammed into the
boards by Leclerc behind the St. Louis net early in the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0122 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Roundup  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE ASSEO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court is adding two explosive cases to an
already high-profile term, agreeing to decide whether states can ban a procedure
opponents call ``partial birth abortion'' and whether the Boy Scouts can exclude
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices announced Friday they will hear arguments in the two cases this
spring; decisions are expected by July.
</P>
<P>
	   The abortion case could yield the court's most important ruling on the issue
since it reaffirmed women's constitutional right to abortion in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices will review a Nebraska law that made it a crime for doctors to
perform the controversial procedure. A federal appeals court struck down the law
as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A constitutional crisis is calling out for a remedy,'' said
abortion-rights advocate Janet Benshoof of the Center for Reproductive Law &AMP;
Policy. ``What's at issue is whether a woman's interest in her health can be
trumped by a state legislature's moral and political statement about a fetus.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Nebraska Gov. Mike Johanns said, ``I feel strongly that states should
have the right to legislate in the area of partial-birth abortion. It's a
barbaric procedure that I hope is brought to an end.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although the current controversy involves a specific procedure,
abortion-rights activists contend far more may be at stake. They say the court's
decision could broadly safeguard -- or dramatically erode -- abortion rights,
depending on what state legislatures are allowed to consider when passing laws
to regulate abortions.
</P>
<P>
	   The procedure involves partially extracting a fetus, legs first, through the
birth canal, cutting the skull and draining its contents.
</P>
<P>
	   Thirty states have enacted bans on the procedure, but most have been blocked
in court. A month after the Nebraska law was invalidated along with laws in Iowa
and Arkansas, nearly identical abortion laws in Illinois and Wisconsin were
upheld by another federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress passed a federal ban on partial-birth abortions, but President
Clinton vetoed it.
</P>
<P>
	   The Boy Scout case involves an assistant scoutmaster in New Jersey whose
leadership role was revoked when the organization learned he was gay.
</P>
<P>
	   James Dale sued, and the New Jersey Supreme Court ruled last summer that the
Boy Scouts' denial of membership to homosexual boys and leaders violated a state
law banning discrimination in public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
	   The Scouts' lawyers contend that law violated the organization's rights of
free speech and free association under the Constitution's First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Scouting adheres to a moral belief ... that homosexual conduct is not
moral,'' the Scouts' lawyer, George A. Davidson, said Friday. An openly gay
person would not be a proper role model for the Scouts, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   But Dale's lawyer, Evan Wolfson of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education
Fund, said opposition to homosexuality is not one of the Scouts' main purposes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As gay people we know how important the First Amendment is,'' Wolfson
said. ``Their First Amendment rights are not being interfered with.''
</P>
<P>
	   Entering another high-profile area Friday, the Supreme Court agreed to
review an appeal in which five Branch Davidians challenged their sentences for
using firearms during a gun battle that began the 1993 standoff at the cult's
compound near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices said they will hear the Davidians' argument that they could not
be given longer sentences for using machine guns, rather than some other kind of
firearms, because a jury never decided what type of weapons were used.
</P>
<P>
	   Even before Friday, the court had a number of major cases on its calendar.
This week, the justices further trimmed the federal government's power over
states, ruling that state employees cannot sue in federal court over age bias.
</P>
<P>
	   They also broadened police officers' authority to stop and question people
who run at the sight of an officer, and ruled that Congress can protect
motorists' privacy by barring states from selling the personal information on
drivers' licenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Still to come by summer are rulings on:
</P>
<P>
	   --State laws that give grandparents broad rights to seek court-ordered
visitation with their grandchildren against the parents' wishes.
</P>
<P>
	   --Whether a federal law, in effect, overturned the 1966 Miranda ruling that
requires police to warn criminal suspects of their right to remain silent and to
get a lawyer's help.
</P>
<P>
	   --Limits on financial contributions to political candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   --A federal law that lets rape victims sue their attackers in federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   --The Food and Drug Administration's decision to regulate tobacco as an
addictive drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0122 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain, Forbes Spar Over Taxes  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush is accusing Sen. John McCain, his
chief rival for the Republican presidential nomination, of ``Washington
double-accounting'' with his tax plan.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the Texas governor aired a new ad in response to
intensifying criticism of his own big tax-reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Facing accusations from McCain and fellow contender Steve Forbes, Bush said
simply, ``They're both wrong.''
</P>
<P>
	   The charges and countercharges came as the six GOP presidential hopefuls
prepared for an afternoon debate today sponsored by The Des Moines Register.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain had a new tax ad, too. Speaking directly into the camera for a spot
airing in New Hampshire, he said: ``There's one big difference between me and
the others -- I won't take every last dime of the surplus and spend it on tax
cuts that mostly benefit the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Forbes claimed that Bush, as governor, broke a 1994
anti-tax pledge by supporting failed legislation that included business and
sales tax increases.
</P>
<P>
	   Not guilty, Bush said in his Iowa ad. ``In Texas, you're only as good as
your word.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Forbes camp dismissed that.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Once again, Governor Bush has ducked the issue,'' said Bill Dal Col,
Forbes' campaign manager. ``It's simple -- he just has to come clean.''
</P>
<P>
	   On the attack himself, Bush said in Glenwood, Iowa, that McCain was
targeting the same special-interest tax benefits to pay for both his tax cuts
and an education proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It sounds like he's going to fund his education reform with ethanol and
he's going to fund his tax cut plan with ethanol,'' Bush said of the Arizona
senator's plan. ``It sounds like Washington double-accounting to me.''
</P>
<P>
	   The education program in question concerns vouchers that could be used to
help certain students attend private schools. And the McCain camp was quick to
respond.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain includes the needed money, said spokesman Howard Opinsky. Bush knows
it and ``is doing a Texas two-step on vouchers and taxes. He said he is for
vouchers, but he never funded his plan in Texas,'' Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain himself was in New Hampshire on Friday speaking to College Convention
2000.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The major reason I'm running for president of the United States is right
here in this room,'' McCain told the group, which included college and high
school students from as far away as Alabama. ``I want to get young people back
into the political process and part of the government.''
</P>
<P>
	   Iowans hold their first-in-the-nation presidential caucuses on Jan. 24.
Eight days later, New Hampshire voters go to the polls in the first primary.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stump, Bush is touting a plan that would cut income taxes by $483
billion over five years. Earlier this week, McCain announced a proposal to cut
taxes by $237 billion over the same period, while setting aside $729 billion for
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush argues that McCain's plan leaves too much surplus tax revenue in
Washington, where Congress will be sure to spend it. McCain argues that Bush
doesn't preserve enough to buoy Social Security in the face of the baby boom
generation's retirement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'll use the bulk of the surplus to secure Social Security far into the
future to keep our promise to the greatest generation,'' McCain says in his new
TV ad. ``I'll begin to pay down the national debt so we don't threaten the
future of our children.''
</P>
<P>
	   Arriving in Des Moines, Bush replied: ``If I can paraphrase his plan, his
plan is the best to maintain the status quo in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush started his day with a speech in a corrugated tin community center in
Red Oak, Iowa. He made a special appeal for votes in this agricultural state,
arguing that one way to help farmers is to open more markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said that might not only raise farm prices but also counteract the move
from family farms to ones owned by conglomerates. ``If you're able to sell your
product overseas, to me it almost makes the conglomeration you're worried about
moot,'' the governor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0135 </TRAILER>
