<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban Mothers Seek Elian's Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Rows upon rows of Cuban mothers -- hundreds visibly pregnant,
others carrying small children -- marched along a seaside boulevard in Havana on
Friday as Fidel Castro's government appealed to emotion in demanding the return
of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez. Cuban authorities estimated that 100,000 women
participated in what it called the "March of the Combatant Mothers." Elian, the
boy at the center of the international dispute, was found clinging to an inner
tube Nov. 25 off the coast of Florida after his mother, stepfather and others
died in a failed attempt to reach U.S. shores. He has been staying with
relatives in Miami who do not want to send him back to Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Possible Mob Victims' Remains Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- Acting on a remarkably precise tip early Friday,
investigators digging in a Boston field unearthed the skeletal remains of two
men and a woman believed to be victims of mobsters. The bodies are believed to
be victims of reputed mobsters Stephen "The Rifleman" Flemmi and fugitive James
"Whitey" Bulger. Authorities believe the woman is Deborah Hussey, Flemmi's
26-year-old stepdaughter, who allegedly was about to expose an affair with him
when she disappeared in 1984, The Boston Globe reported Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Welcomes Medicare Advance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is greeting with cautious optimism a
pledge by drug makers to cooperate on a new Medicare prescription benefit for
older Americans, saying the companies must follow it up with action. "I take
their offer in a positive way, and I just hope they'll come and sit down with
us," Clinton said Friday. But he said his worries about high drug prices, which
have raised industry fears of price controls, remain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court To Rule on Late-Term Abortion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court reclaimed center stage in the legal and
moral war over abortion Friday by agreeing to decide whether states may ban a
surgical procedure opponents call "partial-birth abortion." The justices said
they will review a Nebraska law that made it a crime for doctors to perform such
abortions. A federal appeals court has blocked enforcement of that law, calling
it unconstitutional. Nearly identical laws have been enacted by 30 states, but
courts have blocked enforcement of most of them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Supports Anti-Drug Efforts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton said his drug adviser's effort to
insert anti-drug messages in prime-time television programs was not an attempt
to rob networks of creative freedom. "There was no attempt to regulate content
or tell people what they had to put into it," he said Friday. "Of course, I
wouldn't support that." Fallout over the policy extended to California, where
the bosses of several studios said they were unaware that networks were offered
financial incentives if certain programs preached against drugs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuador Braces for Indian Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Bracing for massive protests in Ecuador's major
cities, the government on Friday deployed 35,000 soldiers and police to deal
with Indians demanding the ouster of President Jamil Mahuad and the closure of
Congress and the courts. Leaders of the indigenous organization that represents
4 million Indians in this Andean nation of 12 million said they expect 40,000
Indians to march into Quito on Saturday to seize control of Congress. Mahuad has
been the target of increasing calls from across the political spectrum to resign
because of his failure to stop Ecuador's economic decline.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Letterman Resting After Heart Surgery
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- "Late Show" host David Letterman underwent emergency
quintuple bypass surgery Friday after a test found one of his arteries was
seriously blocked. "He's fine," spokesman Steven Rubenstein said. Letterman, 52,
had an angiogram because of what he said was high cholesterol and a history of
heart disease in his family. The test, during which a flexible tube is inserted
into an artery and dye is injected, revealed the problem. Dr. O. Wayne Isom, who
performed the procedure at New York Presbyterian Hospital, predicted a rapid
recovery.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends at High of 11,722.98
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average rose 140.55 to a new
closing high of 11,722.98, the third record this week. On the NYSE, gainers led
losers 1,621-1,411. The Nasdaq rose 107.06 to 4,064.27.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
SuperSonics Defeat Spurs 91-85
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Gary Payton scored 25 points and Vin Baker added 23 as the
Seattle SuperSonics won their fourth straight game by beating the San Antonio
Spurs 91-85 Friday night. The Spurs, led by Tim Duncan's 32 points and 16
rebounds, lost for the second night in a row. They were beaten on Thursday night
in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</P>
</TEXT>
