<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright's Mexico Trip a Mystery  </HEADLINE>
   By LISA J. ADAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OAXACA CITY, Mexico (AP) -- When U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
arrives in this quaint tourist capital famous for its colonial architecture and
Indian ruins, there will be no billion-dollar aid proposal to discuss as there
was in Colombia, nor any important canal handover to review as in Panama.
</P>
<P>
	   But on this, the third stop in her three-day Latin American visit, Albright
does have an opportunity to tie up loose ends in the Clinton administration's
relationship with its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright and Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green, who will meet Sunday,
had a close working relationship when the two of them were at the United Nations
several years ago. But there was a ``clear distancing'' between them when
Albright didn't attend last year's meeting, said Rafael Fernandez de Castro, a
Mexican-U.S. relations specialist at Mexico City's private Autonomous Technical
Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They have gotten together very little,'' Fernandez said. Albright has not
directed much attention to Mexican issues, nor Green to U.S. issues, he said.
``So it is very interesting to see in this difficult climate the two are getting
together.''
</P>
<P>
	   But what they'll talk about is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mexican Foreign Relations secretariat said it had no statement to
release, while a U.S. Embassy spokesman referred inquiries to the State
Department's Internet Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   A synopsis of Albright's trip on the site cryptically stated that her
meetings would focus on ``ongoing discussions and review of this crucial
bilateral relationship.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``You have a high official stopping in an important country for the U.S. and
it's not very clear what the purpose is,'' said John Bailey, a Mexican
specialist and government professor at Georgetown University in Washington.
``Usually there's some kind of leadup to it with some announcements and some
expectations created, so this is either peculiar or careless ... or both.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mexico's government news agency Notimex reported that Albright would review
``the most important themes in the bilateral relationship, such as drug
trafficking, immigration and commerce.''
</P>
<P>
	   Albright's trip comes after opposition politicians stymied Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo's planned White House visit in December, which was to involve
discussions on trade, drug trafficking and immigration. Six months ago, Albright
was absent from a meeting of the Binational Commission on U.S.-Mexico relations
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   Now with both countries on the verge of presidential elections, Bailey said
their governments are dealing with other issues. ``So I would be surprised if
there was something really important that got talked about'' by their top
diplomats, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Panama, where Albright stops off today for several hours, officials see
the visit as an attempt by the top U.S. diplomat to make amends for skipping a
ceremony in December for the handover of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright canceled plans to attend the Dec. 14 event here because of Middle
East peace talks in Washington. President Clinton had earlier said he could not
attend the ceremony marking the end of a 96-year U.S. presence.
</P>
<P>
	   Many in Panama believe U.S. officials avoided the ceremony because of
conservative opposition to the transfer of the canal to Panamanian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Since she did not come for political reasons, she is coming now to repair
the damage,'' said former Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter.
</P>
<P>
	   During today's six hour visit, Albright will visit the canal's Miraflores
Locks and hold talks over dinner with President Mireya Moscoso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0046 </DOCNO>
