<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political cartoonist sues for $10 million over botched surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Ranan Lurie's cartoonist career began sixty years ago,
taking him from his homeland in Israel onto the pages of The New York Times and
more than 1,000 other newspapers.
<P>
	   But the world's most widely published political cartoonist claims a botched
surgical procedure on his hand has left him crippled and cut his cartoon output
in half. Because of the damage to his hand, Lurie filed a $10 million lawsuit
against the doctor on Thursday in Manhattan State Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   Lurie, 67, said the operation on his right hand left his pinkie finger
curved inward, making drawing awkward and painful.
</P>
<P>
	   His work appeared in The New York Times when he was 21, while he was cited
by the Guinness Book of World Records as the world's most widely syndicated
political cartoonist. In 1993, he appeared in 1,018 newspapers in 79 countries.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the lawsuit, Lurie injured a ligament his right pinkie while in
an airport in Seoul, South Korea, in 1997. He consulted Dr. Richard G. Eaton
after a friend, New York Yankees pitcher David Cone, recommended the doctor.
</P>
<P>
	   The cartoonist checked into the C.V. Starr Hand Surgery Center at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital on Aug. 29, 1997, where Eaton performed surgery on the
swollen hand.
</P>
<P>
	   Following the hour-long operation, done under a local anesthetic, Lurie
said, "I was left on my own. I didn't get any therapy afterward. The finger
stiffened so that it formed an inward circle, a very sharp crescent."
</P>
<P>
	   When he returned to Eaton, Lurie said, "He didn't know what to do. He
recommended to me that it be amputated and I almost fainted. He tried to
convince me that it would be a good thing."
</P>
<P>
	   Lurie said other physicians opposed amputating the finger, and Dr. Andrew
Weiland eventually operated a second time, relatively successfully.
</P>
<P>
	   "The end result is that the finger can move," said Lurie. "It's obviously
damaged, but I'm limited in what I can do. I used to do eight to 10 cartoons a
week; now I can hardly do four. I used to paint my cartoons; now I use a
computer."
</P>
<P>
	   In the lawsuit, Lurie said Eaton was "negligent" and the surgery was
"inappropriate."
</P>
<P>
	   "(Lurie's) livelihood is entirely dependent upon his use of his right hand,
which he has used during his entire professional career to draw political
cartoons and caricatures," court papers say.
</P>
<P>
	   Lurie said that apart from his right hand, "My health is A-1."
</P>
<P>
	   Annie Ting, the manager of the hand surgery center, said only Eaton could
comment on Lurie's lawsuit and he is out of town until Jan. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 0225 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0047 </DOCNO>
