<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Researchers Form Own Company  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    EXTON, Pa. (AP) -- The inevitable layoffs began six years ago when a
European company bought Sterling Winthrop's prescription drug business, and
among those to go were the team developing pleconaril.
</P>
<P>
	   This was not because the new owner, the French firm Sanofi Pharmaceuticals,
thought the drug worthless. Pleconaril was already in early-stage human testing,
and while no sure thing, all the indications looked good. But the company's
expertise was in heart disease and other areas, and it had no interest in
developing drugs for infections.
</P>
<P>
	   Several other drug companies would like to have taken over pleconaril. But
eventually, Sanofi decided to turn the drug over to the Sterling scientists who
had been working on it for years.
</P>
<P>
	   "We fought very hard," said Mark A. McKinlay, a virologist who directed
pleconaril work at Sterling. "No one will give it more of their energy than we
will. They gave us a chance. The rest is history."
</P>
<P>
	   Ten former Sterling scientists formed the research core of ViroPharma, which
paid Sanofi $1 million for U.S. and Canadian rights to the drug. More payments
will follow if the drug wins final approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Proving a drug safe and effective is hugely expensive, and so far,
ViroPharma has spent more than $50 million, most of it raised from venture
capital firms and stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
	   Sanofi is likely to benefit from ViroPharma's research, since it still has
the right to sell pleconaril outside of North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0255 </TRAILER>
