<DOCNO> APW20000115.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tom Donahoe Resigns From Steelers  </HEADLINE>
    By ALAN ROBINSON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Finally, after two seasons of offseason friction and
on-field failures, the Pittsburgh Steelers decided Tom Donahoe or Bill Cowher
had to go.
</P>
<P>
	   Tom Donahoe went.
</P>
<P>
	   In a remarkable development that caught even team employees by surprise,
Donahoe resigned under pressure as director of football operations Friday after
the Steelers decided he and Cowher could no longer work together.
</P>
<P>
	   The Steelers promised change following their worst season in 11 years, but
this is a transition virtually nobody predicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Cowher keeps his job despite a 13-19 record the last two seasons and 15
losses in 21 games. But Donahoe, one of the NFL's most respected talent
evaluators, is out.
</P>
<P>
	   The ouster -- the Steelers called it a resignation, but it essentially was a
firing -- would be a major development in any NFL city. But it was a stunning
one for a stable organization that has had two coaches in 31 years and never had
a general manager until Donahoe took the job, except in title, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   "We were aware there was tension and, to some extent it's natural and it's
healthy," said team vice president Art Rooney II, a lawyer named for the
Steelers' founder. "But when it gets to the point where communications don't
exist ... and the organization can function, that's when tension crosses the
line into something that doesn't work anymore."
</P>
<P>
	   Cowher and Donahoe each offered to resign following a 6-10 season, and team
president Dan Rooney initially weighed alternatives under which both would stay.
</P>
<P>
	   But after opting against bringing in a middle man or restructuring the front
office, the Steelers accepted Donahoe's resignation, only two days after
announcing Cowher would remain as coach.
</P>
<P>
	   "We looked at shuffling some things around and bringing somebody else in to
serve as a go-between, but we came to the conclusion that was putting a Band-Aid
on something we felt wouldn't work," said Art Rooney II, who is Dan Rooney's son
and heir apparent. "So we felt we had to go in this direction."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if the Steelers were forced to choose between the two, Art Rooney II
said, "In some ways, you could say we looked at it that way."
</P>
<P>
	   Further explaining the move, Dan Rooney said, "I'm not saying we're going to
the Super Bowl, but I confident Bill Cowher can take us there."
</P>
<P>
	   Donahoe, a longtime high school coach who moved into the front office in
1986, drafted or traded for most of the players who led the Steelers to three
AFC title game appearances in four years from 1994-97.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahoe drafted players such as Chad Brown, Levon Kirkland, Leon Searcy and
Joel Steed and swiped star running back Jerome Bettis for a fourth-round draft
pick in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of all, Donahoe fit in well with a franchise that has the leanest front
office in the NFL. In a league where power, big money and constant TV exposure
can easily inflate egos, he wouldn't allow his biography to be published in the
media guide. He had a temper, but he never showed it publicly as Cowher so
readily does on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
	   Even Dan Rooney understands that Donahoe, who signed a 10-year contract only
two years ago, won't be out of a job long.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has opportunities in the NFL," said Dan Rooney, who has known Donahoe
since his high school days and once hired him as a training camp ballboy.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahoe, a lifelong Pittsburgh resident, turned down a big-money offer from
the Seattle Seahawks two years ago and was given a big pay raise and the new
contract. But his relationship with Cowher got only worse and so did the
Steelers' record, as their inability to retain star free agents led to their
first successive losing records since 1985-86.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahoe did not attend a hastily called news conference Friday night, but
issued a short statement: "Change is often necessary. In this particular
instance, the change involves me, which I believe will be positive not only for
the organization, but for myself as well."
</P>
<P>
	   Dan Rooney said the Steelers' front office structure won't change and a
successor to Donahoe will be chosen as soon as possible. Cowher will not gain
any additional say in talent matters.
</P>
<P>
	   The Steelers do not have an obvious successor in place. Tom Modrak, who
worked for them for 20 years, left in 1998 to run the Philadelphia Eagles'
football operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Until Donahoe's successor is hired, front office staffers Dan Ferens and
Mark Hart will oversee plans for the free agent signing period that begins Feb.
11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By RONALD BLUM AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- If general managers could eliminate one day from the
calendar, it would be this one: the day players file for salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
	   Ninety players filed Friday, and the Colorado Rockies and New York Mets took
another step in their makeovers. In another deal, Cincinnati and Milwaukee
swapped outfielders in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
	   Trying to cut their huge payroll a bit, the Mets sent right-hander Masato
Yoshii to the Rockies for left-hander Bobby M. Jones and minor league
right-hander Lariel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
	   While getting rid of Yoshii's $3 million salary, the Mets doubled their
Bobby Joneses; they already have Bobby J. Jones, a 29-year-old right-hander. The
two faced each other last May 11, becoming the first starting pitchers to share
the same name in a major league game since April 16, 1899, when Cincinnati's
John B. Taylor met Chicago's John W. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
	   Yoshii, a 34-year-old right-hander, went 12-8 with a 4.40 ERA in 29 starts
and two relief appearances last season. Bobby M. Jones was 6-10 with a 6.33 ERA
in 20 starts and 10 relief appearances for the Rockies last season.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yoshii fits into the plan of what we want to do," said Rockies general
manager Dan O'Dowd, whose team heads to spring training with seven potential
starters. "We want a staff that throws strikes and doesn't defeat itself."
</P>
<P>
	   Cincinnati acquired Alex Ochoa from Milwaukee for Mark Sweeney and a player
to be named. Sweeney spent most of last season with Triple-A Indianapolis, while
Ochoa hit .300 with eight home runs and 40 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Alex gives us depth in the outfield," Reds general manager Jim Bowden said.
"Our bench is strong from the left side ... but since we lost Jeffrey Hammonds
in the Dante Bichette deal we needed a right-handed bat."
</P>
<P>
	   Unless they settle in the next few days, the players who filed for
arbitration Friday will swap figures with their teams Tuesday, as will first
baseman David Segui, who became a free agent after the season and then accepted
Toronto's arbitration offer.
</P>
<P>
	   Teams, especially the small-market clubs, dislike arbitration because they
have little control over what salaries they pay, forced to give their players
larger raises in many instances because of other settlements or arbitrators
decisions.
</P>
<P>
	   Arizona closer Matt Mantei agreed after the filing to a one-year deal worth
$2,831,000, nearly four times his $725,000 salary last year. And Montreal
right-hander Anthony Telford agreed to a $2 million, two-year deal that contains
a team option for 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   Four players who had been eligible for arbitration, all right-handed
pitchers, agreed to one-year contracts before the filing: Oakland's Jason
Isringhausen ($825,000), Baltimore's Al Reyes ($620,00), Seattle's Frankie
Rodriguez ($580,000) and Tampa Bay's Jim Mecir ($350,000).
</P>
<P>
	   Among free agents, reliever Ricky Bottalico agreed to a $1.5 million,
one-year contract with the Kansas City Royals, right-hander Mike Morgan agreed
on a minor league contract with the Diamondbacks, infielder Dave Hollins agreed
to a minor league deal with the Devil Rays and infielder Jeff Huson got a minor
league contract from the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
	   Bottalico became a free agent Dec. 20 after the St. Louis Cardinals failed
to offer him a contract by the deadline. He was 3-7 with 20 saves last season,
but walked 49 in 73 1-3 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
