<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   The streaking New Jersey Devils and Philadelphia Flyers apparently got
caught looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   The Devils lost for the first time in 10 games, and the Flyers had a
six-game winning streak snapped Friday night, as the top two teams in the
Atlantic Division enter tonight's showdown in New Jersey on a down note.
</P>
<P>
	   Adam Oates scored on a breakaway with 22.6 seconds left in overtime as the
Washington Capitals beat the Devils 3-2, snapping New Jersey's NHL-best
nine-game unbeaten streak.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's frustrating to lose the game, we had the lead, and to lose it is
disappointing," said Devils defenseman Sheldon Souray, whose giveaway led to the
game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
	   In Atlanta, Norm Maracle, returning from an exile to the bench, stopped 26
shots and Dean Sylvester scored the only goal early in the third period as the
Thrashers beat Philadelphia 1-0.
</P>
<P>
	   Philadelphia lost for the first time since Dec. 22 at New Jersey, going
6-0-1 the next seven games and winning four times on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   "They (the Thrashers) worked hard and once they got their goal, they were
fired up," Flyers coach Roger Neilson said. "We had a lot of good chances,
really, but we just couldn't pull the trigger."
</P>
<P>
	   In other games, it was Florida 5, Carolina 1; Montreal 2, Buffalo 1; Toronto
3 Edmonton 2; and Anaheim 3, St. Louis 1.
</P>
<P>
	   At New Jersey, Oates' game-winner was set up when Souray broke his stick
while trying to keep the puck in the Capitals zone, allowing Oates to block his
weak pass and break in alone on Devils goalie Chris Terreri.
</P>
<P>
	   "As soon as I saw him go to his backhand, I took off hoping it would
bounce," Oates said. "Four-on-four you gamble a little bit and I just took off."
</P>
<P>
	   That left it to Terreri to save the Devils' nine-game unbeaten (7-0-2).
Oates skated patiently toward him and flipped the puck over his left shoulder
for his seventh goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
	   Maracle was benched for five games after a 6-0 loss at Nashville on Dec. 30.
He spent the time working with goalie coach Bob Mason, improving the angle on
shooters and not flopping to the ice quite so often.
</P>
<P>
	   "This was huge for me," Maracle said. "I've been struggling the last couple
of weeks. ... Now, my confidence is back up and hopefully it will continue."
</P>
<P>
	   The Thrashers posted one of their biggest victories before a raucous crowd
of 18,571 -- the largest in team history.
</P>
<P>
	   Pavel Bure and Scott Mellanby scored power-play goals to lead host Florida
to its fifth win in six games.
</P>
<P>
	   The first-place Panthers opened up a 14-point lead over second-place
Carolina in the Southeast Division and snapped a seven-game winless streak
against the Hurricanes (0-3-4).
</P>
<P>
	   Rookies Jason Ward and Francis Bouillon each scored their second career
goals and Jose Theodore made 14 saves to lead visiting Montreal.
</P>
<P>
	   Stu Barnes scored and Martin Biron stopped 25 shots for Buffalo, which is
2-6-1 since Christmas.
</P>
<P>
	   Mats Sundin scored at 2:59 of overtime as Toronto rallied from two goals
down to win at Edmonton. Garry Valk and Igor Korolev scored in the third period
for the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
	   Todd Marchant and Ryan Smyth scored in the second period for the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
	   Marty McInnis got the go-ahead goal and Paul Kariya scored his first
power-play goal in nine games as host Anaheim ended St. Louis' eight-game
unbeaten streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Guy Hebert, who played for the Blues until the Ducks made him their first
pick in the 1993 expansion draft, made 36 saves, and Ladislav Kohn ended a
12-game goal-scoring drought to help Anaheim snap a seven-game winless streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0302 </TRAILER>
