<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watch Out for the Tsunami  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK-
AP Sports Writer-
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBA commissioner David Stern came up with the image first as
he tried to express what he sees for the changing sports landscape.
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunities for employment in sports will explode in the digital age,''
Stern said. ``It will be a tsunami of opportunities. Send us your resumes. My
address is 645 Fifth Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue did not supply his address, but endorsed
Stern's stand and even employed the NBA boss' word.
</P>
<P>
	``David called it a tsunami of new opportunity,'' he said. ``It is an economy
driven by new technology.''
</P>
<P>
	And it has the NFL and NBA hanging out help wanted signs for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
	Appearing at the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/Push Wall Street Project,
Tagliabue and Stern participated on a panel that discussed minority jobs in
sports. It is a continuing issue, one that ex-Georgetown coach John Thompson
spoke out about on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern is about the universities in the country that educate our kids,''
he said. ``If these colleges are not sensitive enough that if you are going to
allow young people in intercollegiate activities, and after they finish you are
not willing to hire them on a consistent basis, it is ridiculous to wonder why
they don't have any interest in getting an education.''
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue sees only an upside to the developing sports environment.
</P>
<P>
	``Sports in the 21st century mirrors three trends in society -- population
growth, increased minority population and an America whose economic engine is
driven by technology,'' the NFL boss said.
</P>
<P>
	``The social, cultural, political implications are huge. Sports is no longer
the mom and pop business it was 50 years ago. We are at $3.5 billion revenue
league-wide and in five years it will be $5.5 billion through increases in
television revenue.
</P>
<P>
	``The challenges I see is the demand for new skills, high levels of
specialization in a nation that is becoming increasingly diverse. We seek
specialists, not generalists, coming from other sectors into sports. There is a
need for capologists. What's a capologist? It's a bright person who knows how to
deal with complex financial issues.''
</P>
<P>
	Included on the Operation/Push panel were athletes who succeeded first in
sports and then in the business world.
</P>
<P>
	Ex-stars like Drew Pearson and Isiah Thomas have flourished in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
	Pearson, the former Dallas Cowboys wide receiver, runs a marketing company that
employs 100 people. Thomas, who starred for the Detroit Pistons, helped launch
the NBA's Toronto franchise and now operates the CBA, basketball's main minor
league.
</P>
<P>
	Pearson is a licensee for sports apparel.
</P>
<P>
	``It is tougher than ever to maintain a level of success,'' he said. ``It's
tough to gain access in the sports licensing industry. In the last year, I've
been in more fights than Mike Tyson and he's supposed to be fighting.
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough road to hoe. We have access to capital. What we need is access
to opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said the reason he bought into the CBA was to bring franchises back into
local communities. He said a number of NBA players have invested in teams. Chris
Webber, Jalen Rose, Voshon Lenard, Derrick Coleman and Hall of Famer Dave Bing
have owner interest in the Detroit franchise. All of them are natives of that
city.
</P>
<P>
	``Sports inspires the world and it inspires America,'' Thomas said. ``It holds
a meaningful role in our lives. It's the only place you can truly see inclusion
and diversity at work.''
</P>
<P>
	Not always, though.
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said that in his executive role, he attends many meetings. Usually,
though, he finds that he is the only minority in the room. ``In corporate
America, you notice that you don't encounter someone who looks like me,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Signs Appeals Reform Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By JACKIE HALLIFAX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The electric chair has ended its days as Florida's
sole means of execution after a decade that sometimes saw macabre spectacles in
the state's death chamber.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Jeb Bush signed a bill Friday giving inmates a choice between the
electric chair and lethal injection. The new law makes lethal injection the
method of choice if inmates decline a preference.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also approved new regulations designed to limit inmates' appeals and
cut the time they spend on death row by half.
</P>
<P>
	   The Legislature approved the changes last week in a bid to stop the U.S.
Supreme Court from reviewing a death row inmate's lawsuit claiming the electric
chair is cruel and unusual punishment -- and therefore unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is scheduled to be argued in February, but Attorney General Bob
Butterworth has asked the court to dismiss it in light of the change. The
inmate's attorney wants the case to continue.
</P>
<P>
	   Executions in the state have been on hold since October, when the U.S.
Supreme Court agreed to review the claim.
</P>
<P>
	   Florida had been one of only four states, along with Georgia, Alabama and
Nebraska, that used the electric chair as its sole means of execution.
</P>
<P>
	   Its old electric chair, dubbed ``Old Sparky'' after flames shot from its
headgear during executions in 1990 and 1997, was replaced before the July
execution in which blood streamed down the face of Allen Lee ``Tiny'' Davis.
</P>
<P>
	   The other law changed Friday limits death row inmates appealing on legal
technicalities to two appeals in state courts in most cases and requires second
appeals be filed within six months of the first. Previously, attorneys for
convicted killers had a year to file a second appeal after the first was
rejected.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents argued the change could lead to the execution of innocent people.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters said it will stop frivolous cases and bring legitimate claims to
the attention of judges more quickly. They hope the change will cut the time
between a death sentence and an execution to five years.
</P>
<P>
	   The 44 people who have been executed in Florida over the last two decades
have lived on death row an average of more than 10 years. One, Gary Alvord, has
lived with a death sentence for a quarter of a century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 0310 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phills' Son: Dad's With the Angels  </HEADLINE>
    By PAUL NOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTE (AP) -- The most moving eulogy for Charlotte Hornets guard Bobby
Phills was made by his wife, Kendall. The most courageous one came from his
teammate and close friend, David Wesley.
</P>
<P>
	   Phills' life was celebrated Friday at a memorial service, where his family
was joined by members of the NBA's Hornets and New York Knicks, friends and
former teammates. His funeral is scheduled for Sunday in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
	   Wesley, who police say was racing his teammate Wednesday before Phills lost
control of his sports car and collided with an oncoming car, needed a moment to
compose himself before he addressed the family.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't really know what I want to say, but he was my partner in crime," he
began. "We had some fun."
</P>
<P>
	   Making no references to the accident, Wesley remembered Phills as a fierce
competitor on the basketball court and on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
	   "He always had to win and even when he wasn't winning he talked enough trash
to make you think he was winning," he said, drawing laughter from the mourners.
</P>
<P>
	   Negating the despair that has gripped the community for days, Kendall Phills
set the tone for the service as she got up to speak near the open casket. She
carried their young son, Bobby Phills III, to the podium.
</P>
<P>
	   With a little gentle prodding from his mother, 3-year-old Bobby told several
hundred mourners: "Daddy is in heaven with the angels." He then ran off and
hugged his 1-year-old sister, Kerstie.
</P>
<P>
	   With few dry eyes left in the Central Church of God, Kendall Phills spoke
glowingly of her love for her husband. They met in high school when she was just
14.
</P>
<P>
	   She described Bobby Phills as "intelligent, competitive, funny and
compassionate."
</P>
<P>
	   "He adored our beautiful children and he loved his parents," Kendall Phills
said, finally breaking down into tears. "It's truly been a blessing for me to
have Bobby as my husband, friend and eternal soul mate. While we will meet
again, I will always love you, Bobby."
</P>
<P>
	   Phills, 30, was in a bronze casket surrounded by about a dozen flower
arrangements and two poster-size photographs of him while he played for the
Hornets. One of the arrangements was in the shape of a basketball hoop and ball.
</P>
<P>
	   An entourage of Knicks players came to the service led by veteran center
Patrick Ewing. Several of Phills' former teammates also attended the service.
</P>
<P>
	   Hornets coach Paul Silas also was unable to control his emotions when he was
asked to say a few words.
</P>
<P>
	   "The thing I think I'll miss the most is his big smile, an infectious
smile," Silas said. "He would brighten up the room when he entered. And he was
smart and perceptive on and off the court."
</P>
<P>
	   Silas said Phills took it in stride when he was asked to give up his
starting job this season.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I asked him to go to the bench he said, 'Coach, I'll do whatever I
need to do to help this team."'
</P>
<P>
	   Hornets vice president Bob Bass nearly lost his composure when he started to
talk about his former player.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bad thing I feel," he said, his voice shaking, "was that I never told
Bobby that I love him. God, it's tough to lose a guy like that."
</P>
<P>
	   The emotional service was the start of what promises to be a difficult
period for Phills' former teammates. The Hornets were to fly to New York today
to play the Knicks. After the game, the team was to take a charter back to
Charlotte, then fly to Baton Rouge on Sunday for Phills' funeral and burial.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, on Monday, the Hornets will host the Toronto Raptors at the Charlotte
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
	   The funeral will be held on the campus of Southern University, where Phills
earned a bachelor's degree in animal science.
</P>
<P>
	   A moment of silence as well as a video tribute to Phills had been planned
for Friday night's game. That will be done at Monday's home game. His teammates
plan to wear a patch bearing Phills' No. 13 on their jerseys for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the Hornets will retire his jersey number at their Feb. 9 home
game against Cleveland, the team with which Phills spent his first six NBA
seasons. Phills will be the first Charlotte player to have his jersey retired in
the club's 11-year history.
</P>
<P>
	   No makeup dates have been set for the Hornets' two postponements. Wednesday
night's game against Chicago also was postponed after the accident.
</P>
<P>
	   Wesley and Phills left a practice at the Charlotte Coliseum late Wednesday
morning, got into their Porsche coupes -- Phills a black one and Wesley a white
one -- and began racing on a winding, heavily traveled thoroughfare, according
to police.
</P>
<P>
	   Less than a mile from the coliseum, while the two were traveling at what
police said were speeds in excess of 75 mph, Phills lost control of his car in a
45-mph zone and slid into oncoming traffic. His car was struck in the driver's
side door by an oncoming sedan. Phills was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
	   Charlotte-Mecklenburg County police spokesman Keith Bridges said if any
charges are filed in the case, they would come at the end of the crash
investigation, probably sometime next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
