<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family of police shooting victim files complaint  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The family of a man killed by police says Commissioner
Howard Safir twisted the truth to justify a shooting that should never have
happened.
<P>
	   "He specifically first demonized my brother," said Glen Busch, whose
brother, Gary, was wielding a hammer when officers shot him to death last
summer. "This starts from the top and works its way down."
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Busch's family filed a complaint with the Civilian Complaint Review
Board Friday alleging that Busch was fleeing from cops, not attacking them, when
he was struck by 12 bullets.
</P>
<P>
	   "He didn't attack anybody ... and never had," said Busch's mother, Doris
Busch Boskey. "They knew that he wasn't a threat, they knew he posed no danger.
... He was trying to get away. Why would anyone go toward six or more police
officers?"
</P>
<P>
	   Deputy police chief Thomas Fahey said in a statement that the matter had
been fully investigated and that both the police department and the Brooklyn
district attorney found the officers involved in the shooting acted properly. He
declined through a spokesman to respond specifically to the allegations about
Safir's statements.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, a Brooklyn grand jury decided the shooting was justified
because it was reasonable for the patrolmen to believe Busch was a threat to
them.
</P>
<P>
	   Busch's death on Aug. 30, 1999, prompted street protests in Borough Park,
Brooklyn, the predominantly Orthodox Jewish neighborhood where he lived, and
raised questions about how police deal with emotionally disturbed people.
</P>
<P>
	   Police came to Busch's home after receiving reports that he was threatening
people with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
	   The department said that when officers ordered Busch, 31, out of his
basement apartment, he flew into a rage and charged up the stairs swinging an
11-inch hammer. One officer tried - but failed - to stop him with pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
	   His family's CCRB complaint charged the officers involved in the shooting
with excessive force and abuse of authority.
</P>
<P>
	   It asked the board to investigate whether the officers followed department
guidelines on dealing with the emotionally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
	   If their actions were within NYPD rules, then the rules must be changed,
said New York Civil Liberties Union executive director Norman Siegel,
representing the family. Siegel said the use of pepper spray on the already
agitated Busch only provoked him further.
</P>
<P>
	   "It just ... creates a crisis situation when in most of these instances, if
you just wait it out, you can deal with the person," Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
	   He added that even though the grand jury had found the officers did not act
criminally, the board could still determine that the shooting was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
	   The day after the shooting, Safir said the four officers who fired the shots
that hit Busch had used deadly force only after he refused to drop his hammer
and stop attacking two other officers. The commissioner, who cited seven
non-police witnesses, said Busch was pummeling a fallen sergeant when he was
shot.
</P>
<P>
	   The family disputes that account, and accused Safir and his subordinates of
distorting the truth in public statements after Busch's death.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was an immediate cover-up, there were stories, they had to justify
this shooting which should never have happened," Mrs. Boskey said.
</P>
<P>
	   The family's complaint asks the CCRB to investigate Safir's actions and find
out what basis he had for saying there were seven independent witnesses
confirming that police acted appropriately. Investigators were reportedly unable
to find any of the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   The complaint also asks whether the officers involved truthfully answered
questions about the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Boskey, who said she had spoken to many witnesses and seen photos of
the scene, said her son was trying to get away from police when he was shot. She
described his hammer as a religious item inscribed with Hebrew writing.
</P>
<P>
	   He was trying to get away from police and find an open space to recover from
the pepper spray when he was shot, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was afraid," Mrs. Boskey said. "They had guns drawn."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 0314 </TRAILER>
