<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 03:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winter arrives in New York City area with an icy jolt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - After a relatively toasty December and early January,
New Yorkers struggled to get through icy temperatures hovering in the teens and
winds that made it feel at times like 25 degrees below zero.
<P>
	   "It's been warm and now all of a sudden it is so cold," said Aida Rios, 31,
of the Bronx, as she waited for a subway Friday to get to work. "I was forced to
be outside in this weather. I felt like I was in a freezer."
</P>
<P>
	   "Even the money is cold," Charles Masur, 28, said at an ATM machine in White
Plains. "You can't wear enough to be warm when the wind's like this."
</P>
<P>
	   Some school districts in the northern suburbs opened up to two hours late.
And in Sullivan County, Monticello schools were closed.
</P>
<P>
	   New York City was on a cold weather alert.
</P>
<P>
	   "Up to last night we were averaging 11 degrees above normal for the month,"
meteorologist Scott Reynolds of the National Weather Service said Friday. "Today
we'll take a little bite out of that, I suspect."
</P>
<P>
	   Shelters and soup kitchens braced for the worst overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coalition for the Homeless was giving hot meals and blankets to hundreds
of people on the streets and urging them to go to shelters.
</P>
<P>
	   "When it gets this cold it's a matter of life and death," said Patrick
Markee, senior policy analyst for the coalition. "On nights like this we see
literally hundreds of men pouring into shelters," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that on Thursday night, some men waited hours to get into a shelter,
and he feared the same thing might happen Friday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Added Hossein Saadat, executive director of St. John's Bread and Life soup
kitchen in Brooklyn: "When it's cold like this people tend to stay longer than
usual. The challenge is finding space for so many people. We don't have the
heart to tell them to leave, so we just have to manage."
</P>
<P>
	   David Billig, a spokesman for the Emergency Medical Service, said the
service had received several calls Thursday and Friday about cases of
hypothermia, frostnip and frostbite.
</P>
<P>
	   He said people who live or have to work in the street, such as EMTs,
paramedics, firefighters, police officers and work crews, are most in danger.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you don't need to be outside, stay inside," he said, and for those who
have to go out, he stressed the importance of layered clothing with a waterproof
outer layer. He said people should avoid smoking and alcohol, and should be sure
to wear gloves and a hat.
</P>
<P>
	   Back in White Plains, Jan Pferd of Goteborg, Sweden, said the weather
reminded him of home. But "that doesn't mean I like it. I think the wind will
bowl me over."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
