<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Heavy rain and snow was falling from parts of northern California to the
Pacific Northwest today while cold air was keeping conditions frigid from New
England through most of the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
	   The cold was expected to remain in the East -- as well as the southern
Plains -- with below-zero readings in New England.
</P>
<P>
	   Clear and dry conditions were forecast to span from the Mid-Atlantic states
south to the Gulf Coast and west into Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Great Lakes, an approaching warm front is expected to bring snow
across Michigan, Pennsylvania and western New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Snow showers were also forecast to work their way east from North Dakota and
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's midsection was largely expected to have mostly clear to partly
cloudy conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   Heavy rain was forecast along the Pacific coast from central California
north to Washington state, with localized flooding possible in northern
California and southern Oregon. Snow is expected to begin at higher elevations
in the Cascades and Sierras before moving into western Montana and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
	   An approaching system is expected to bring wind gusts of up to 50 mph in
higher elevations of the northern Rockies and Pacific coastal ranges.
</P>
<P>
	   Extremes on Friday in the continental United States ranged from a high of 86
degrees in El Cajon, Calif. to a low of minus-16 degrees at International Falls,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
	   Forecast highs for Saturday ranged from the single digits and teens in New
England; teens and 20s in the northern Plains; 20s and 30s over the mid-Atlantic
and central Appalachians; 30s in the Rockies; 30s and 40s in the Great Lakes
region, Ohio Valley and central Plains; 40s and 50s in the Southeast and much of
the West; 60s and 70s along the Gulf Coast; and 70s and 80s in Southwest
deserts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
