<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Civil Rights Funding  </HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Invoking the memory of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.,
President Clinton said today his budget request for 2001 will include a
substantial increase in money for civil rights enforcement.
</P>
<P>
	   The president said in his weekly radio address that ``there are still too
many barriers and examples of too many Americans facing discrimination in their
daily lives,'' even though the country is doing better in treating all citizens
equally.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, speaking on King's 71st birthday and two days before the nation's
official celebration, also said he will also ask Congress for swift passage of
legislation that would expand federal hate crime laws to include crimes
committed because of the victim's sexual orientation, gender or disability.
</P>
<P>
	   Seated near Clinton during the address was 100-year-old Charlotte Filmore, a
black woman who once worked at the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   The president said she is a living testament to civil rights progress in
America.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whan she worked at the White House she had to use the side door,'' Clinton
said. ``Today she came through the front door all the way to the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
	   Arriving today at the White House, Mrs. Filmore, who was born on October 2,
1899, said: ``I``m so glad I lived to see this day.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he will seek $695 million for civil rights enforcement, a 13
percent increase from last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Civil Rights Division of the Justice Department would receive $98
million, an increase of 86 percent above its spending levels in 1993, the first
year of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The proposed funding will permit the Justice Department to expand
significantly investigations and prosecutions of criminal civil rights cases --
including hate crimes and police misconduct -- as well as fair housing and
lending cases,'' the White House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he also will seek $322 million for the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, 14 percent more than last year's budget.
</P>
<P>
	   Other substantial increases are being sought for the civil rights
enforcement offices at the Labor Department, the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, the Agriculture Department, and the Education Department, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton described his proposals and requests as ``new steps to fulfill Dr.
King's dream'' as one of the 20th century's greatest champions of justice.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Dr. King challenged us to dig deep in our hearts ...and live to to our own
creed,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
