<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Says GOP Focus Is on Education  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Citing a year of past success, Sen. Olympia Snowe,
R-Maine, said today that education was the No. 1 priority for Republicans in
2000.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Who would dispute that education is the great equalizer in our society
that can give every citizen in our nation -- regardless of race, gender, income
or geographic background -- the same opportunity to succeed?'' Snowe said in the
GOP's weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
	   If the federal government would fully meet its obligation to fund special
education programs, it would free billions for states and local governments to
put toward other education needs, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, 5.6 million children were enrolled in special education programs,
most with learning disabilities, language impairments or emotional problems,
according to the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We must continue to provide the resources and the flexibility necessary
for schools to be their best and students to do their best,'' Snowe said.
</P>
<P>
	   She added that student loans should be more accessible and affordable, and
said Congress plans to the review the nation's education programs this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Turning from young Americans to seniors, Snowe said Republicans are
dedicated to preserving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As part of last year's budget, we ensured that not one red cent of Social
Security surplus funds will be touched for the first time in 40 years,'' she
said. ``I'm pleased the president now agrees with our approach.''
</P>
<P>
	   On a final note, Snowe sounded the familiar Republican theme of fighting for
tax reform, particularly ending the ``marriage penalty'' that affects two-earner
couples.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You've worked hard to make our economy what it is today,'' she said. ``You
deserve to keep more of that hard-earned money to spend as you see fit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
