<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Brace for First Primary  </HEADLINE>
   By RON FOURNIER AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- The Republican campaign took a turn toward civility
in last week's runup to the first presidential voting, while Democrats Al Gore
and Bill Bradley decided that combat suited them better.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The voters will have a clear choice on election day,'' pledged Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
	   The candidates looked ahead to a week of television ads, mass mailings,
phone banks and carpools designed to get supporters to the Iowa caucuses a week
from Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary served as an important distraction, with many
candidates splitting time between the two opening-bell states.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No time to waste!'' Bradley said midway through a week in which the
dynamics shifted in the Democratic race in Iowa, taxes dominated the GOP debate
and a front-runner twice shifted his ad strategies under pressure.
</P>
<P>
	   George W. Bush seemed caught off guard during a GOP debate in Michigan, when
McCain seized on an unexpected pledge not to run negative ads. ``I'll shake
hands with you, George,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   The moment seemed impromptu, but in fact McCain had reason to believe Bush
was about to go negative: A woman had contacted his campaign to complain that a
Bush camera team had interviewed her about McCain's tax plan. She said she was
coached to criticize the package.
</P>
<P>
	   His campaign caught in the act, the Texas governor said he knew nothing
about the operation and pledged anew not to run negative ads. Bush advisers said
their ad team had stockpiled scores of interviews for potential ads, but there
were no plans to cut a negative spot.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet one member of the Bush camp confirmed that the woman who came forward
had been ``helped along'' by producers seeking an articulate criticism of
McCain's cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, the national GOP front-runner, is in a dead heat with McCain in New
Hampshire. McCain has bypassed Iowa, where complicated caucuses demand
resource-draining organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush also pulled his punch with Steve Forbes, the conservative millionaire
who is airing ads accusing Bush of breaking his no-tax pledge as governor.
</P>
<P>
	   After days of internal debate, Bush produced a response ad that said Forbes'
charge was ``wrong'' and set the record straight by talking about two Texas tax
cuts he supported. Left on the shelf was the script of an ad that would have had
Bush saying, ``My opponent has chosen to run a negative campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, meanwhile, appeared to outlast questions about his work on behalf of
contributors in the Senate. A week earlier, the matter had threatened to
overwhelm his campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, Gore and Bradley dredged up old Senate votes and
pounced with breathless accusations. The vice president said Bradley abandoned
flood victims in Iowa. The former New Jersey senator said Gore flip-flopped in
votes on smoking and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley had promised not to sling ``darts'' in his not-politics-as-usual
campaign, but aides say he had no choice after the vice president lashed out at
Bradley in the final months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's team now is crying cry foul. ``It's a shame that Senator Bradley has
had to resort to negative campaigning,'' said the vice president's combative
spokesman, Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
	   The rhetoric intensified as Bradley struggled to close a stubborn 20-point
gap in Iowa polls and his advisers began to worry Gore actually was gaining
strength.
</P>
<P>
	   It was a different picture in New Hampshire, where the race remained close.
Gore's team sensed what one adviser called ``glacial movement'' in his favor
after weeks of advantage-Bradley in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Barely heard above the din, three Republicans hoped Iowa's social
conservatives would lift them into the top tier. Debates that served as bookends
to the week gave Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah a chance to
shine.
</P>
<P>
	   In their final week in Iowa, Bush plans to hammer home the fact that he has
the largest tax-cut proposal, and he is expected to continue to find fault with
McCain's package. He already accused McCain's bean counters of using
``Washington double-accounting.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's advisers discussed ways to portray their boss as the most
presidential of the presidential candidates, hoping to capitalize on lingering
questions about Bush's experience and intellectual heft.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Democratic candidates braced for another week of jousting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a competition, after all,'' said Bradley, a sharp-elbowed former
basketball star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
