<HEADLINE> Banks Were Aided Along With Farmers  </HEADLINE>
    By PHILIP BRASHER AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices for wheat and corn are as low as ever in Garden
County, Neb., but things at the Nebraska State Bank are looking up. Only half as
many farmers need federal guarantees to qualify for credit this year, and almost
every borrower now is up to date on payments.
</P>
<P>
	   The reason? The $8.7 billion farm-economy bailout Congress passed in
October, said Mike Jorgensen, the bank's president. More than $2 million of the
emergency aid went to Garden County's 400 farms. "I think the government
payments have made a lot of difference," Jorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, analysts say, the unprecedented infusion of government farm aid over
the past two years has been a boon for banks as well as the growers who borrow
from them. With the bailout, direct government payments to farmers last year
reached a record $22.7 billion, triple the federal outlay just three years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Only one farming-dependent bank has failed in each of the past three years,
compared to close to 300 that went under during the last major slump in
commodity prices in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   The delinquency rate on federally guaranteed farm loans, which go to banks'
riskiest borrowers, is another sign of relative stability. It is virtually
unchanged from 1997 at about 4.5 percent, according to the Agriculture
Department. Overall, the delinquency rate for loans by farm banks was well under
3 percent for the year ended June 30, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
	   "The government is putting in a lot of money. That is the really big story,
I think," said Steve Koenig, a farm credit analyst for USDA's Economist Research
Service.
</P>
<P>
	   Other factors are helping the banks, too: Land values are relatively stable;
the mid-1990s were boom years for U.S. agriculture, so farmers were in
relatively good financial shape when grain prices collapsed in 1998; and federal
loan guarantees are widely available.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA guaranteed almost $2.6 billion worth of farm loans last year and,
thanks to last fall's bailout package, has the money to do more than $4 billion
this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Banks also are demanding more records from farmers than they used to -- back
in the 1980s, for example, they might not have required a farmer's income tax
returns to verify earnings. And banks more frequently are requiring farmers to
buy crop insurance or to get futures and options contracts on their crops, which
protect them from price declines.
</P>
<P>
	   Farmers rely extensively on credit, both to pay for land and to cover yearly
operating expenses until crops are harvested.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly, we're not looking at a financial or economic meltdown like we had
in that period in the '80s," said John Blanchfield, an agricultural credit
expert for the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
	   "The 1990s for the most part were highly profitable years for farmers.
Through the '90s there was tremendous wealth built up, and that huge cushion of
wealth has helped tremendously these last couple of years."
</P>
<P>
	   The overall financial position of farmers is relatively sound, according to
USDA statistics.
</P>
<P>
	   Average farm equity, adjusted for inflation, was up 1 percent last year from
1998 and has risen 50 percent since the mid-1980s. Farm debt is down 12 percent
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Virtually no other bank in the country is as dependent on farming as
Jorgensen's, located in Oshkosh, in the western Nebraska panhandle. Almost 94
percent of the $17 million in loans it had outstanding in 1998 were
agricultural.
</P>
<P>
	   But almost no one in the area has quit farming recently, although Congress
will have to come through with more aid in 2000 to ensure they are okay,
Jorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Farmers are better managers than they used to be, he said. Almost every
producer bought federally subsidized crop insurance in 1999 -- only half did a
few years ago -- and many are using futures contracts even though the bank
doesn't require it.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not trying to allude that the farm economy is good. It certainly
isn't," Jorgensen said. "But the borrowers we have seem like they are more
heads-up on it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
