<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Golden Touch of John Wells  </HEADLINE>
    By BOB THOMAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For a man who bears the ultimate responsibility for
three hours of successful network TV drama each week, 66 hours per season, John
Wells seems remarkably cool.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet Wells -- who is co-executive producer of two smash-hit television
series, "ER" and "West Wing," and one promising newcomer, "Third Watch" --
confesses to some wee-hour trepidation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I do fine all day long, then I wake up out of a dead sleep, usually about
2:35, and realize ... I can't possibly get it done. I'm up for two hours, then I
go back to bed."
</P>
<P>
	   Wells' three NBC series total a staggering 24 to 30 script pages a
production day, compared to five for the average feature film. That's a heavy
load for the casts and crews and Wells says one of his key roles is to make the
working environment comfortable for them.
</P>
<P>
	   "The amount that you're working in TV is so great that it becomes your
family -- not a replacement, but an adjunct," he says. "A typical shooting day
is 12 hours, five days a week. It's not unusual to have 14-hour days.
</P>
<P>
	   "It needs to be a good place to work, where you're supported, and people
care about your concerns. We spend a lot of time trying to do that."
</P>
<P>
	   So what else does an executive producer do? Is TV the same as feature
movies, where the executive producers can number eight or more and include the
star's wife, agent and hairdresser?
</P>
<P>
	   Wells, 43, laughed loudly at the question.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's a good object lesson," he remarked, "because all three shows are
very different jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   "On 'Third Watch,' I'm very involved in the writing of the show and the
editing and producing. Because it's shot in New York, the production is handled
by Brooke Kennedy and my co-executive producer, Chris Chulack, a wonderful
director who supervises the visual end of the show.
</P>
<P>
	   "On 'West Wing,' I get notes of the scripts, but (series creator and
co-executive producer) Aaron Sorkin really runs the writing staff. Tommy
Schlamme (also co-executive producer) runs the visual look of the show. I'm far
more involved in producing, along with my brother Lew.
</P>
<P>
	   "Because 'ER' has been on so long, we have a great staff. I'm much more
involved in the long-range planning and casting, giving notes on the script and
the cut."
</P>
<P>
	   "ER," of course, is a TV phenomenon: five and a half seasons as the top
rated series. Yet it was turned down by all the networks.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Wells said, the health care system was in decline. "There was
tremendous dissatisfaction with physicians; you were most likely to see a doctor
portrayed as a villain in a movie. There was a lot of belief that you couldn't
attract an audience with doctors as heroes."
</P>
<P>
	   NBC finally agreed to sponsor a pilot, largely, Wells believes, because
Michael Crichton and Steven Spielberg were involved; they had just scored big
with "Jurassic Park." Network bosses hated the pilot, but agreed to schedule it
after it tested well with sample audiences.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House saga "West Wing," which has drawn rave reviews and solid
ratings in its first season, was also a hard sell, Wells said, "because there's
a general belief in films and television that there's not a mass audience for
politics." After 16 months and a change of network administrations, NBC agreed
to put "West Wing" on the fall schedule.
</P>
<P>
	   NBC also lacked enthusiasm for "Third Watch," a drama about New York City
firefighters. It was considered "a rescue show" and was scheduled in the highly
competitive Sunday night at 8 time slot. Since Jan. 10, "Third Watch" has
appeared in a more favorable position, Monday at 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Wells confessed that he fell in love with the theater in the eighth grade of
his Alexandria, Va., school. He trained as a director and designer at
Carnegie-Mellon University, then graduated in film producing at the University
of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
	   "We were required to take a writing course at USC, and I fell in love with
it," he said. "But I didn't make a dime from it for six years." He discovered he
was more adept at managing large groups of people. Now he finds himself
overseeing 700-750 employees each week -- "like a medium-size manufacturing
company."
</P>
<P>
	   The three shows have elements in common -- the most visible being
fast-paced, steady-cam action, whether it's emergency personnel racing along
with patients on gurneys, presidential aides hurrying down corridors, or
firefighters racing to a fire. All of the series also have large casts with
interlocking story lines.
</P>
<P>
	   Wells added another quality:
</P>
<P>
	   "What I'm interested in with drama is something that illuminates the human
condition in a way that we can better ourselves. We can watch someone else make
mistakes that we think we ourselves would be able to make.
</P>
<P>
	   "We try to find those small moments of heroism and moral dilemmas; they're
close to the same kinds of choices we all have to make day in and day out. Let's
experience those emotions and try them on a little bit, and hopefully we can use
a little bit of that in our own lives."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
