<HEADLINE> sfhfc  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP)- The investment group proposing the state's only
minority-owned bank has begun lining up branch offices in Hartford, Bloomfield
and Bridgeport.
<P>
	   The group Friday reached tentative agreement to buy three branches being
divested in the merger of Fleet Bank and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
	   Sale of the branches is dependent on The Community Bank being granted
charters and other approvals by state and federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
	   The bank's holding company, Urban Financial Group Inc., would be based in
Bridgeport, and is headed by New York investor Peter F. Hurst.
</P>
<P>
	   "We see opportunities in urban markets that the bigger players may have
overlooked," Hurst said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial terms of the deal with FleetBoston Corp. were not disclosed, but
Hurst said his group has raised enough capital to get a charter and to buy the
three branches.
</P>
<P>
	   The Community Bank would be the first minority-owned bank in the state in a
decade. It would start out as a residential and commercial real estate lender,
as well as a lender to small businesses, Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
	   "One of our goals is to bridge the great digital divide" that separates city
and suburban households, Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
	   Before The Community Bank opens for business, it must apply for and receive
a state charter and federal deposit insurance and the holding company must
receive a federal charter.
</P>
<P>
	   Hurst, an investment banker and lawyer, said he and his partners plan to
open the bank in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Community Bank would become the only minority-owned bank in Connecticut,
according to the state Department of Banking.
</P>
<P>
	   Caribbean First Bank of Hartford was once granted a temporary charter by
state regulators. But insufficient capital forced the bank to surrender its
charter in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The Connecticut Savings &AMP; Loan Association in Hartford was the last
minority-owned bank to possess a full-fledged charter. It was one of 20
Connecticut banks that failed in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
