<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal feted on 80th birthday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Cardinal John O'Connor's birthday party Saturday has
turned into a major fund-raiser for the New York Archdiocese - as well as an
expected gathering for some of his possible successors.
<P>
	   The dinner at the Waldorf-Astoria in honor of the cardinal's 80th birthday
raised $4 million for Catholic charities, including support for parochial
schools in the archdiocese and funding for a seminary position named for the
cardinal.
</P>
<P>
	   Included among the 1,500 people invited were several men whose names have
been mentioned as O'Connor's possible successors: Archbishop Justin Rigali of
St. Louis; Archbishop Edwin O'Brien, who heads the archdiocese for the U.S.
Military; and Bishop Henry Mansell of Buffalo, a former top aide to O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
	   The dinner was scheduled to feature tributes to the cardinal, a speech by
O'Connor, and a video about his legacy.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor, who grew up in Philadelphia, was a military chaplain who served
briefly as the bishop of Scranton, Pa., before being named to head the New York
Archdiocese in 1984. He succeeded Cardinal Terence Cooke.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor is the oldest active bishop in the United States and is regarded as
one of the most powerful Catholics in America. The pope is expected to replace
him now that he has turned 80, the age at which cardinals lose their power to
vote for a new pope.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor also had a brain tumor removed in September and has missed a number
of public appearances, including Masses, since then. He stumbled twice in
November when mounting the steps to the pulpit, and has taken to sitting in a
chair near the high altar to avoid the stairs.
</P>
<P>
	   The guest list for his birthday dinner reads like a Who's Who of Catholics
in America. In addition to Rigali, O'Brien and Mansell, the attendees were
expected to include Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark; Cardinal Anthony
Bevilacqua of Philadelphia; Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston; Cardinal Adam Maida
of Detroit; Cardinal James Hickey of Washington; Cardinal Francis George of
Chicago; Archbishop Daniel Buechlein of Indianapolis; Archbishop Harry Flynn of
St. Paul-Minneapolis; and the Papal Nuncio in Washington D.C., Gabriel Montalvo.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Mayor Ed Koch, a close friend of the cardinal's, and Gov. George
Pataki, were also expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the clergy are also expected to attend Sunday morning Mass at St.
Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
	   The dinner is being chaired by three Wall Street investment bankers: Ted
Forstmann, senior partner of Forstmann Little &AMP; Co., and a well-known advocate
of school vouchers; David Komansky, CEO of Merrill Lynch; and Les Quick of Quick
&AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
	   Tickets were $1,000 a head but many guests made additional contributions.
The seminary position being funded by some of the proceeds is the John Cardinal
O'Connor Distinguished Chair in Hebrew Studies at St. Joseph's Seminary in
Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
	   It is designed to educate priests about the shared scriptural heritage of
Jews and Christians. Fostering better relations between Catholics and Jews has
been one of the cardinal's priorities.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor is also known for being a stalwart defender of the pope's hard line
on abortion and homosexuality. During his 16 years in New York, he has chastised
politicians who support abortion and ousted gay worshippers from parish
churches. But he's also sided with striking unions and gone into AIDS wards
anonymously to wash the hair of patients too sick to know who he was.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York Archdiocese serves 2.4 million Catholics in Manhattan, the
Bronx, Staten Island, Westchester, Rockland and five upstate counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
