<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dark past brings down South Beach's 'dangerous darling'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Until last month, Chris Paciello confidently reigned
over a South Beach nightclub regime catering to the see-and-be-seen set.
<P>
	   Madonna, Donald Trump, Jennifer Lopez - all hung out at Paciello's clubs,
lounging in black leather booths, sipping Dom Perignon and schmoozing with the
beefy, dark-haired owner.
</P>
<P>
	   But authorities claim a truer picture of Paciello emerged years earlier in a
more mundane setting: the middle-class home of Staten Island housewife Judith
Shemtov. It was there, they say, that Shemtov took a bullet in the head - part
of an evil past that has finally caught up to Paciello.
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 1, the Brooklyn native surrendered in Miami on murder and robbery
charges after he was named in a New York indictment accusing him of being a
former member of the violent "Beach Avenue Crew."
</P>
<P>
	   The goon squad, authorities say, provided muscle and money for the Bonanno
organized crime family by going on a crime spree that left a half dozen bodies
in its wake. They claim Paciello, whose legal name is Christian Ludwigsen, was
known as "the Binger" because he liked to binge on crime.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal case could force Paciello, 28, to forfeit his multimillion
dollar enterprise and put him behind bars for life.
</P>
<P>
	   The mercurial rise and fall of the man a Miami alternative weekly, New
Times, calls "the dangerous darling of the SoBe nightlife set" has both
enthralled and stunned his supporters and associates.
</P>
<P>
	   Gerry Kelly, owner of the new nightclub Level, learned from authorities last
week that Paciello once discussed responding to the competition by having him
"whacked."
</P>
<P>
	   "This is definitely a 'Jekyll and Hyde' situation," said Kelly, Paciello's
onetime marketing director. He recalled Paciello as a kind boss who began each
day with a two-hour workout.
</P>
<P>
	   "I never, ever even heard him raise his voice," he said. "I thought he was
my friend. ... It's scary as hell."
</P>
<P>
	   Ingrid Casares - Paciello's partner in the trendy dance club Liquid and
close friend of Madonna - and other South Beach glitterati have rallied behind
Paciello. Insisting Paciello is a legitimate entrepreneur and community leader,
several wealthy backers have put up personal property to secure a $15 million
bail bond.
</P>
<P>
	   Paciello's attorney, Roy Black, has sought to portray the graduate of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt High School in Bensonhurst as a "young man who's
turned his life around." He notes that Paciello - despite growing up with known
criminals and having several previous arrests - has never been convicted of a
felony.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unfortunately, the way our society works is when someone becomes successful
or a high-profile person, they become a target," Black told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   South Florida friends say Paciello's success sprung from a shy charm and
knack for drawing black-clad beautiful people to his nightspots dotting South
Beach's Art Deco District.
</P>
<P>
	   Before his arrest, Paciello himself responded to mob rumors, saying, "It
doesn't make me a gangster because I hung out on the corner with people while I
was growing up." He has said he began using his mother's maiden name, Paciello,
because his parents broke up - not to escape his past.
</P>
<P>
	   But prosecutors call the portrait a sham. They say Paciello led a double
life after he went south, switching his allegiance to the Colombo crime family
and settling scores with assaults and death threats.
</P>
<P>
	   In one incident noted in gossip columns, Paciello allegedly decked a former
football player at a South Beach club in a fight over a super model. A lawsuit
by a former Mr. Universe accuses him of breaking the plaintiff's face with a
beer bottle.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a character trait of Mr. Ludwigsen to resort to violent activity,"
said Assistant U.S. Attorney James Walden.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities allege Paciello first gravitated to the mob in the late 1980s
after moving to Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
	   Accomplice witnesses have told investigators that as part of the Bonanno
holdup crew, Paciello was both mastermind and lookout for the 1992 robbery of a
branch bank in a Staten Island mall. Armed bandits smashed out windows with a
sledgehammer before making off with $300,000.
</P>
<P>
	   On Feb. 18, 1993, the crew struck again, this time ringing the doorbell at
the home of Staten Island home of Shemtov, 46, on a tip that her businessman
husband had $200,000 stashed in a safe. Within minutes, a gunman had shot and
killed her; Paciello allegedly drove the getaway car as they fled, empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
	   Paciello made enough money to reinvent himself in South Beach by opening a
club called Risk in 1994, investigators say. The name was apt: Risk was
destroyed by fire in what authorities now suspect was an arson-insurance scam
which helped Paciello raise enough money to start Liquid.
</P>
<P>
	   Teaming with Casares - a member of a rich Cuban family which credits him
with helping her kick a drug habit - Paciello also opened the celebrity hangout
Bar Room and a restaurant, Joia, held fundraisers and bought a pricey
beach-front home. As his profile rose, so did stories linking him romantically
to the likes of Niki Taylor and Daisy Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
	   But authorities say Paciello also had another acquaintance - an undercover
agent posing as a corrupt narcotics officer. The agent was making secret
recordings of their phone calls, evidence that prosecutors say exposes the
defendant as a career thug.
</P>
<P>
	   "We got to get him beat up," Paciello allegedly said of Kelly. "I got to get
him whacked." Later, he warned that he would have to "come out of retirement.
I've become a big (sissy) down here. A big sucker."
</P>
<P>
	   About the same time, Paciello was observed introducing the undercover agent
to Alphonse Persico, then the acting boss of the Colombo crime family,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
	   The meeting has raised suspicions Paciello was laundering mob money through
his clubs. Prosecutors also allege that he allowed Liquid to become a haven for
dealers peddling the designer drug Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
	   The combination of Paciello's violent background and newfound fame would
make him "a commodity to the Colombos," said Jerry Capeci, a crime expert
tracking the Mafia on his Ganglandnews.com. Web site. "He's willing to break
heads to make money and he's an entree to celebrities with lots of cash."
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorneys have denied their client has any mob ties. And they
complain that the recorded conversations were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's unfair to suggest that Chris Ludwigsen was plotting to kill anybody,
because that's nonsense," said attorney Howard Srebnick.
</P>
<P>
	   Paciello is expected to be released from a Brooklyn jail by the end of the
month. But he will remain under house arrest until his trial in the fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the party goes on at Paciello's Bar Room. Madonna and Gwyneth
Paltrow were spotted dancing on tabletops there at 4 a.m. New Year's Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
