<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warrants not always pursued in NY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   AMSTERDAM, N.Y. (AP) - Police Chief Thomas Brownell sometimes wishes the
long arm of the law was a little bit longer.
<P>
	   He sees the problem regularly in this small Mohawk Valley city: An officer
makes a traffic stop or an arrest; a routine check uncovers an outstanding
warrant from the New York City area; police downstate decline to bring the
offender back.
</P>
<P>
	   "Basically that means we've got the jerk living here," Brownell said. "We
don't want New York City's garbage, whether it comes by barge or ... bus."
</P>
<P>
	   Brownell is voicing frustration felt by a number of other upstate New York
police officers. While fugitives wanted on felony warrants are routinely
retrieved, the officers complain New York City authorities often will not pick
up people wanted on less serious misdemeanor warrants - charges like marijuana
possession or disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
	   The problem is considered a big enough public nuisance that the Schenectady
County sheriff has offered to have his own deputies drive offenders back to New
York City. And a state assemblyman from that area has just submitted a bill that
would set up a state funding stream to defray the cost of transporting those
fugitives.
</P>
<P>
	   "It kind of turns justice around on its head if you can go 150 miles up the
Thruway and not pay for breaking the law," Republican Assemblyman James Tedisco
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The warrant issue is tied up with the larger problem of criminals from New
York City migrating upstate. Even as crime rates have dropped in New York City,
some upstate areas have been grappling with relocated criminals.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, police in Schenectady estimate that more than half the drug
suspects they arrest give New York City addresses. Albany Det. James Miller said
most of the 13 homicides there last year involved either a suspect or a victim
from New York City - many of them involved in the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a safer climate for your low-level drug dealer to come up to Albany
and ply their trade," Miller said.
</P>
<P>
	   At least some of those offenders are leaving behind pending legal cases in
New York City. Law enforcement officials in Schenectady, Albany and Ulster
counties have reported stopping or arresting people with outstanding warrants
from downstate. If New York City refuses to retrieve them, they are released
back into those communities even if they end up serving local jail time.
</P>
<P>
	   "We kind of recontaminate the community," Schenectady County Sheriff Harry
Buffardi complained.
</P>
<P>
	   New York City Police Lt. Dennis Cirillo said his department does travel
across the state to execute warrants but he said each case is judged on its own
merits.
</P>
<P>
	   "We look at the severity of the crime, the distance from the city coupled in
with the cost to the taxpayers," Cirillo said.
</P>
<P>
	   Of course, the NYPD is one of the busiest police agencies anywhere. There
were 375,000 arrest cases in the New York City Criminal Court last year and the
city preliminarily reported 667 homicides for 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Montgomery County District Attorney James Conboy noted that even far smaller
jurisdictions like his do not retrieve all fugitives. He noted that when a
person wanted locally for felony DWI was apprehended in the Midwest, local
officials decided not to saddle county taxpayers with the costs to bring the
offender back.
</P>
<P>
	   Tedisco, noting the costs to localities, has just proposed a bill that would
require the state to pay half the cost of ferrying absconders back to the town
or city where a warrant was issued. Municipalities could opt to pay the other
half.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, as a Republican in a chamber dominated by Democrats, Tedisco could
have an uphill fight. He has distributed copies of the bill to the Pataki
administration and hopes to hold hearings this year to build support.
</P>
<P>
	   Buffardi, meanwhile, has offered to have his department ferry offenders back
downstate. Problem is, he would need more money for the unbudgeted expense.
</P>
<P>
	   But as some police officers noted, even if more warrants were enforced, it
wouldn't totally stem the flow of criminals to upstate cities.
</P>
<P>
	   Schenectady Lt. Mike Hamilton noted: "In all likelihood they would come back
and commit the crimes anyway. It would just be a few days later."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1350 </TRAILER>
