<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Revelations Stun Kohl's Party  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Revelations of campaign money irregularities by a state
branch of Germany's Christian Democrats deepened the party's finance scandal and
prompted calls Saturday for nullification of its victory in last year's state
elections.
</P>
<P>
	   A Christian Democratic leader in Hesse stunned the nation late Friday by
disclosing that party leaders had channeled millions to their organization from
foreign accounts and declared the money improperly. The amounts involved were
the biggest yet in the ever-expanding finance scandal touched off by former
chancellor Helmut Kohl that has dominated German politics for weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   National party leaders expressed dismay. ``Money laundering like the
Mafia,'' said Saturday's front-page headline in the daily Bild.
</P>
<P>
	   In Friday's revelation, a former Cabinet minister under Kohl who used to
chair the Hesse Christian Democrats said the state branch transferred $6.8
million to its coffers from abroad between 1989 and 1996. To hide the money's
origin, the party listed it as stemming from bequests, said the former minister,
Manfred Kanther.
</P>
<P>
	   National party leaders, including Kohl, were not informed about the
transfers, and neither was Hesse Gov. Roland Koch until now, said Casimir of
Sayn-Wittgenstein, the state party's then-treasurer. His remarks were reported
Saturday by the news magazine Der Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
	   As recently as Monday, Koch, a Christian Democrat, had insisted the state
organization's books were in order.
</P>
<P>
	   The governing Social Democrats charged that the allegedly illegal campaign
funds tainted the Hesse state elections they narrowly lost last year. They urged
a fresh ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To prevent much greater damage to democracy, there is only one way out:
The voters must decide anew,'' said Hans Eichel, who was voted out as governor
and now is German finance minister.
</P>
<P>
	   The Christian Democrats rejected the demand. Koch has refused to resign over
the affair.
</P>
<P>
	   The revelations on top of the finance scandal in the national party have the
Christian Democrats reeling as they try to focus on a state election next month
in Schleswig-Holstein.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All this is very hard to take,'' party general secretary Angela Merkel
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The scandal erupted last month when Kohl admitted accepting up to $1 million
in cash donations and failing to declare them in apparent contempt of the law.
He has refused to name the donors despite repeated appeals from his party to
help clear up the scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   Parliament is investigating whether payoffs influenced decisions by Kohl's
government, a suggestion Kohl vehemently denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
