<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bada-bing! New Jerseyans love how mob hit portrays their state  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) - The cast of "The Sopranos" is here. Lorraine
Bracco, Steven Van Zandt, Michael Imperioli - and about 400 people from New
Jersey.
<P>
	   "How many times does a state become a star of a television series?" the
show's creator, David Chase, asked at a screening this week of HBO's wildly
successful mob hit.
</P>
<P>
	   It's true. "The Sopranos," which begins its second, 13-episode season on
Sunday, is set here. And unlike most television shows, it's filmed here. The
story of suburban mobster Tony Soprano and his two "families" has racked up 10
million viewers in its first season, plus four Emmy awards and raves by critics
who call it one of the best television series ever made.
</P>
<P>
	   And New Jerseyans say the series has shone a national spotlight on the
state.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's practically the world's most expensive home movie," said Steve
Gorelick, assistant director of the New Jersey Motion Picture and Television
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents have called Gorelick asking to have their homes used for the show.
The show has been shot in about 20 cities from Asbury Park to Paramus. Gritty,
industrial landscapes serve as a backdrop for mob activities, while suburban
tract homes and soccer fields in the same area show Tony Soprano's family side.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's like, Uh! That was the diner in Fort Lee, and that was in Lodi and
that was in Newark," Newark Mayor Sharpe James said.
</P>
<P>
	   The meat market where Tony and his buddies talk business is in Kearny. The
nursing home where Livia Soprano, Tony's mother, lives is in West Orange. Bada
Bing!, the exotic dancing club that Tony runs, is in Lodi. And Pleasantdale
Chateau, the site of Thursday's screening, was set to serve as a the site of a
Soprano meeting in Italy.
</P>
<P>
	   "The scenes are certainly New Jersey. I don't know about the lifestyle they
project," said John Kosko, borough administrator of North Caldwell, where the
exteriors of the Soprano home are filmed.
</P>
<P>
	   Paramus resident Clara Nagy doesn't have a problem with the show's criminal
element.
</P>
<P>
	   "Do you know how much mob there is in New Jersey?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
	   And Paterson Police Chief Lawrence Spagnola, who worked on narcotics and
organized crime task forces in the 1970s, says, "I've seen a few families like
that. They're out there."
</P>
<P>
	   But New Jerseyans say they relate more to the characters' nuclear family
lives in the settings they call home.
</P>
<P>
	   "It shows the problems they're having with their kids," Clifton Police Chief
Frank Logioco said. "I think the characters are absolutely perfect."
</P>
<P>
	   Those attending the screening applauded the most for Van Zandt, a longtime
Jersey celebrity for his membership in Bruce Springsteen's E Street Band and
then in Southside Johnny and the Asbury Jukes.
</P>
<P>
	   The crowd also clapped more on screen for Nancy Marchand's Livia, a
manipulative mother who, when she felt neglected and cast aside, fought back by
putting out a hit on her son.
</P>
<P>
	   "Dysfunctional as it is," Chief Spagnola said, "it's just an average
family."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1400 </TRAILER>
