<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Vote Too Close To Call  </HEADLINE>
   By BILL CORMIER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Sunday's presidential election in Chile is so close
that not even pollsters will hazard a guess who will win: socialist Ricardo
Lagos or his rightist rival, Joaquin Lavin.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 8 million Chileans are eligible to cast ballots in a run-off vote for a
new leader in this country, where the economy is emerging from its deepest
recession in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic considerations will be uppermost in voters' minds as they choose
between Lavin, the strongest conservative candidate in years, and Lagos,
representing the Concertacion, a center-left coalition that has governed Chile
since a dictatorship ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   The two men battled to a virtual draw in an initial ballot on Dec. 12. Lagos
received 47.9 percent of the vote and Lavin received 47.5 percent. A simple
majority was needed to win outright.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This election is going to be just as close as the first round,'' Lavin
said in an interview published Saturday in El Mercurio, Chile's leading
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   The two most recent polls were divided, each giving the rival candidates a
lead of less than 1 percentage point -- less than the 3 percent margin of error.
</P>
<P>
	   The winner will be inaugurated March 11 for a six-year term, succeeding
Eduardo Frei, a Christian Democrat who was constitutionally barred from
re-election.
</P>
<P>
	   For months, the candidates sought to outdo each other with similar-sounding
promises to fight rising street crime, aid strapped farmers, and create hundreds
of thousands of jobs. To some, that made it hard to distinguish between the two.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It makes no difference to me, they're both the same,'' said fish seller
Eduardo Fuenzalida.
</P>
<P>
	   While Lagos, 61, was far head in polls early in the race, Lavin,
representing the opposition Alliance for Chile, gained momentum as the campaign
proceeded.
</P>
<P>
	   Almost boyish looking at 46, Lavin is a successful two-term mayor of Las
Condes, Santiago's swankiest suburb. He is acclaimed for putting more police on
that suburb's streets and ending traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
	   The outcome could be swayed by how well either candidate has done in
alluring support from roughly 800,000 voters who did not vote the first time
around.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Lavin has attracted a huge mass of voters who are not ideologically
motivated,'' said Eugenio Guzman, a Chilean sociologist who observed that Lavin
focused more on the economy and unemployment early on.
</P>
<P>
	   But Lagos, who has a Ph.D. in economics from Duke University, has attracted
attention by promising unemployment insurance in a country seeking to improve
its social safety net.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The first measure in my government will be to create unemployment
insurance, take my word for it,'' said Lagos, a former opponent of Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's 1973-1990 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment has improved to 9.6 percent after climbing as high as 11
percent, and the economy has begun to grow again after a two-year slump.
</P>
<P>
	   Lagos remains a hero for Pinochet foes. After leftist guerrillas made an
attempt on Pinochet's life in 1986, Lagos was one of several leftists arrested
by state security services in a crackdown. Although he had nothing to do with
that attempt, Lagos spent several days in jail, coming out to work full time for
the restoration of democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet has been detained in Britain since October 1998 on a warrant from a
Spanish judge who wants the general to stand trial for alleged human rights
abuses during his iron rule.
</P>
<P>
	   A move to extradite Pinochet to Spain won court approval. But after months
of legal wrangling, British Home Secretary Jack Straw said Tuesday that a panel
of doctors concluded Pinochet is too ill to face trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Straw said he was reconsidering the extradition, which could open the door
for Pinochet to return home to Chile within weeks. Both Lavin and Lagos have
said they would allow Pinochet to be tried at home if he returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
