<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Facts Concerning Chile Election  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Key facts about Chile, which holds a presidential run-off election Sunday,
Jan. 16:
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   ELECTION SUNDAY: More than 8 million voters are registered to take part in
the presidential election. Winner to succeed President Eduardo Frei, 59, for a
six-year term.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   CANDIDATES:
</P>
<P>
	   --Ricardo Lagos, 61, a moderate socialist. Backed by the center-left
coalition that has governed Chile since civilian rule was restored in 1990,
ending Gen. Augusto Pinochet's 17-year dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   --Joaquin Lavin, 46, a conservative economist supported by a unified
right-wing opposition.
</P>
<P>
	   Both candidates battled to a virtual draw in a first round vote Dec. 12,
forcing the run-off, as no candidate received a majority of the vote. Lagos
received 47.9 percent, Lavin 47.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   COUNTRY: Located on South America's western seaboard, Chile runs 2,700 miles
south from Peru, and is also bordered by Bolivia and Argentina. A long and
narrow country, Chile has average width of 110 miles. Population: 14.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   POLITICS: A republic, Chile enjoyed one of the longest-lasting democracies
in Latin America until 1973, when a bloody military coup led by Gen. Augusto
Pinochet toppled Marxist President Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet's authoritarian rule lasted until 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   In October 1998, he was arrested in Britain on a warrant by a Spanish judge
who wants to extradite and try him on torture charges stemming from human rights
abuses during his regime. In the final week of the campaign, Britain said he is
too ill to stand trial, which could lead to his return to Chile.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   ECONOMY: Chile pioneered liberal, free markets policies in Latin America
with remarkable success in the mid-80s. For over a decade, growth averaged 7
percent annually. But as the Asian financial turmoil spread throughout Latin
America, the economy suffered its worst recession in 16 years. Unemployment has
reached a record 11 percent, but signs of recovery have appeared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1417 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0099 </DOCNO>
