<HEADLINE> Notes From the Campaign Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIVE, Iowa (AP) -- Flanked by pine trees, and with a parking lot full of
semitrailer trucks as a backdrop, Republican presidential hopeful Gary Bauer
chided the Clinton administration Saturday for not protecting its borders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're doing a lousy job in exporting more Iowa farm products out of this
country, and we're doing a terrible job in importing a lot of trouble, whether
it's illegal aliens or the drugs pouring across the border from Mexico,'' Bauer
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservative activist stepped out of a maroon Dodge Voyager and met with
reporters at the Flying J truck stop at the junction of Interstates 35 and 80.
Bauer said he wanted to use ``this great crossroads here in Iowa'' as a backdrop
to emphasize that he differs from his GOP counterparts on trade.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I particularly believe the front-runners in my party right now on major
issues are embracing policies that are identical to Bill Clinton,'' Bauer said.
``George Bush, John McCain and Orrin Hatch will all give China
most-favored-nation status again. I'm incredulous at that. I don't know an
adjective to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most-favored-nation'' status is normal trade relations, the country's
relationship with almost every country. Officials in Washington use the term to
``permanent normal trade status'' when referring to China.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Globe endorsed Vice President Al Gore and Sen.
John McCain in New Hampshire's Democratic and Republican presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   In editorials published Saturday, New England's largest newspaper described
Gore as ``the most competent among the Democrats to lead the country in a
complicated world.'' Among the Republicans, McCain's ``forays into the
unconventional are sensible as well as bold.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Two members of the Texas Board of Education said
Saturday that George W. Bush is distorting his record on education and endorsed
Steve Forbes for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert Offut, who has served on the education board for seven years, and
Donna Ballard, a former board member and activist, said the education system in
Texas has deteriorated during Bush's four years as Texas' governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush says in campaign ads that he supports local control of schools, Ballard
said, but as governor Bush broke his promise to restore local control. Ballard
said authority has been stripped from state and local elected boards while Bush
has been governor, with power given to an existing state agency or newly
appointed boards.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Texas leads the nation in improving schools,'' said Bush spokesman Eric
Woolson. ``It's documented, and it's clear for all to see.''
</P>
<P>
	   Any signs of improvement in the system resulted from making tests easier,
Ballard charged.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush ``has not been forthcoming on the issues,'' Forbes said as he predicted
a ``good showing'' in the Jan. 24 Iowa Caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Ballard and Offut said they supported Bush when he ran for governor.
Their transportation to Iowa was paid by the Forbes campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has picked up the
endorsements of 94 Republican National Committee members and state GOP chairmen
and -women.
</P>
<P>
	   They represent a majority of the 165 members of the committee, holding its
winter meeting in San Jose. The 94 amount to 85 percent of GOP officials
eligible under state by-laws to endorse candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You are the heart and soul of the Republican Party, chosen by GOP
volunteers, the good folks who do the hard work of putting up signs, handing out
fliers and getting people to the polls,'' Bush campaign manager Joe Allbaugh
said in thanking the group.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, Bush said: ``I am honored and humbled by the support of so
many grass-roots Republican leaders from every corner of our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
