<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Holiday Was Long, Tough Battle  </HEADLINE>
   By JUSTIN BACHMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. had been dead just four days
when Rep. John Conyers, moved by riots that shook several cities, introduced
legislation to make the slain civil rights leader's birthday a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   For the next 15 years, the Michigan Democrat filed his bill at the start of
each Congress, only to see it go nowhere amid apathy, widely held pessimism
about its future and outright hostility from lawmakers who considered King a
communist.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Many people said they thought this was a good idea, but they didn't see
how it was going to happen,'' Conyers said last week in a telephone interview
from his Detroit office.
</P>
<P>
	   It did finally happen, with the first federal observance of Martin Luther
King Jr. Day in 1986. On Monday, two days after what would have been King's 71st
birthday, every state will observe some form of civil rights celebration.
</P>
<P>
	   For decades, King's family focused on getting the holiday observed around
the country. Now the family and others hope it evolves into a day off in which
Americans do something more than sleep late or go shopping. They are encouraging
Americans to spend the day volunteering or helping the less fortunate. The theme
for 2000 is ``Remember! Celebrate! Act! A Day On, Not A Day Off!''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The King holiday bill is really being honored in a way that makes me quite
proud. The celebrations are very appropriate,'' Conyers said.
</P>
<P>
	   A key to getting the holiday passed was the public support of entertainers
such as Stevie Wonder, Dizzy Gillespie, Harry Bellafonte and Bob Dylan, Conyers
said. Wonder's 1980 tribute to King, ``Happy Birthday,'' became an anthem for
the campaign and planted the idea of a national King holiday in the American
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the popular culture, the idea was advanced,'' said Mary Frances Berry,
head of the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights and a University of Pennsylvania
history and law professor. ``Without the popular culture, it never would have
gone anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
	   But some opponents claimed King, who was assassinated in 1968, was a social
menace who flirted with communists and did more than that with women. His
objection to the Vietnam War enraged millions.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents also argued that it would cost a fortune to give workers another
day off. And some people simply saw no good use for another winter holiday, said
Stanford University history professor Clayborne Carson, director of the MLK
Papers Project there.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The notion of another three-day holiday in the middle of winter was not
good,'' Carson said. ``They said, 'What are people going to do?' In places where
you can ski, that might not have been a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
	   Aside from the rancorous political debate over whether King deserved such
recognition, many were taken by the audacity of proposing a new national holiday
for an individual.
</P>
<P>
	   Only George Washington, Abraham Lincoln and Christopher Columbus received
such distinction, and national holidays themselves are rare and strange
creations, said David Garrow, an Emory University history and political science
professor who won the Pulitzer Prize for his 1987 King biography.
</P>
<P>
	   The last new federal holiday was Veterans Day, adopted in 1938. Many in
Congress were displeased in the 1970s when the Washington and Lincoln
observances were lumped into one as Presidents Day.
</P>
<P>
	   But as Conyers persisted, support was slowly growing in churches, state
legislatures, even in other countries. Finally, President Reagan conceded the
growing pressure in 1983 and said he would sign the bill if it reached him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'll never forget that day in the debates in the Senate,'' Conyers said.
``They made us look like pikers. They bragged about King, they told us how
patriotic he was, what a super American he was, how much he had done for the
country. When they finally decided to come over, man, they ran to the front of
the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
	   Martin Luther King Jr. Day is now entrenched. Last summer, New Hampshire
changed its Civil Rights Day to honor King specifically and a bill is pending in
the Utah Legislature, which convenes on the third Monday of January, to rename
the state's Human Rights Day in King's honor.
</P>
<P>
	   But observances still tend to be spotty. While every state gives its workers
either a paid or ``floating'' holiday they can use on King day, several Southern
states combine their observance with honors for Confederate generals Robert E.
Lee or Stonewall Jackson.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial markets, federal offices and most banks and schools are closed,
but only 23 percent of businesses offer the day as a paid holiday, according to
a survey of 413 companies by the Bureau of National Affairs, Inc., which sells
data and research to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1986, only 14 percent of companies surveyed observed the holiday, survey
director Mike Reidy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1439 </TRAILER>
