<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prize-Winning AP Photographer Dies  </HEADLINE>
   By BRIGITTE GREENBERG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Henry Burroughs, an award-winning photographer who
chronicled three decades of news for The Associated Press, including the
presidencies of Harry Truman, John F. Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson, died late
Friday. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs died at his home in West River, Md., from complications of
pneumonia. His wife of 28 years, Margaret, was at his side.
</P>
<P>
	   Known as ``Hank,'' Burroughs joined the wire service on May 16, 1944, and
quickly gained a reputation as a journalist who could capture a great picture
without getting in the way of the story. Colleagues called him the ``dean of the
Washington photographers.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was such a marvelous representative of the AP and the photography
profession itself,'' former AP Photo Editor Hal Buell said. ``He was really a
great example of what every fine news photographer should be.''
</P>
<P>
	   Retired UPI photographer Maurice Johnson said Burroughs took great care with
his subjects.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are a few of us who believe we are capable of getting a story,
photos, without being obtrusive and obnoxious. He always worked hard on stories,
but he was very aware of the people he was photographing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Daugherty, director of the AP's state photo center, said that from the
time he first arrived in Washington in 1967, he hoped to emulate Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think he probably taught me and taught a lot of others to be a first
rate photojournalist while being a gentleman,'' Daugherty said.
</P>
<P>
	   Walter R. Mears, who has reported on Washington and national politics for
the AP for more than 35 years, said the bespectacled Burroughs brought intellect
to the job.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was both a fine photographer and a scholarly, gentleman. Those traits
don't always go together,'' Mears said.
</P>
<P>
	   Born Henry Dashiell Burroughs Jr. on Aug. 1, 1918 in Washington, D.C., he
took to photography from his earliest years and spent six years as a fashion and
advertising photographer at The Washington Post before joining the AP.
</P>
<P>
	   At the wire service, he covered every president from Franklin D. Roosevelt
to Gerald Ford. His most memorable images include a photo of Richard Nixon
standing at the window of the Oval Office just as his presidency was about to
collapse and a photo of Kennedy just moments before his assassination.
</P>
<P>
	   The day Kennedy was shot in 1963, Burroughs was in the motorcade. He made
sure the world got pictures from the chaotic scene near the book depository and
of the mob outside the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs took a rare photograph of Roosevelt in his wheelchair, an image
that went unpublished because pictures of the president's handicap were
forbidden by the White House at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs won awards for a picture of President Johnson in deep thought
prior to a press conference on Vietnam and for a photo of Sen. Thomas Eagleton
and his wife leaving a cabin in the hills of South Dakota after informing
Democratic presidential candidate George McGovern, who had chosen Eagleton as
his running mate, that he had once undergone treatment for mental illness.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs served as president of the White House News Photographers
Association in 1957 and was chairman of the Senate Standing Committee for still
photographers. In 1964, he received the first AP Managing Editors Award for
photographic excellence.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1973, he was named ``Photographer of the Year'' by the White House News
Photographers Association. He was a member of the National Press Club for more
than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs once said that he felt lucky to have had ``a front-row ticket to
history.'' He was first assigned to the White House in 1949, and of all the
presidents he covered, Truman was his favorite.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He loved photographers and we loved him,'' Burroughs once said. ``Any time
you walked in the Oval Office with Truman he would make some remark about us or
to us with his guest. And he'd put everybody at ease. We were part of his
party.''
</P>
<P>
	   Colleagues said Burroughs had a special talent for capturing lighter,
informal moments. Among his indelible images was a January 1961 photo of Jackie
Kennedy patting her husband's chin just moments after he was sworn in as
president and a 1957 photo of Richard and Pat Nixon throwing coins over their
shoulders at the Trevi fountain in Rome.
</P>
<P>
	   In his career, Burroughs drew many overseas assignments, beginning in
war-ravaged Paris and Berlin after World War II. He was arrested and detained by
a Soviet Army officer for taking photos of Red troops marching in East Berlin.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs retired from the AP in 1975, after 31 years with the news service.
</P>
<P>
	   Burroughs was predeceased by first wife Elizabeth Anderson, second wife Anne
Simpson Moore, and his brother, David.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by his wife, Margaret Wohlgemuth of Annapolis, Md.; one
stepson, Lyford Moore, of Mount Laurel, NJ.; stepdaughter Patricia Romero of
Boise, Idaho; two sisters, Jane Dollins of Alexandria, Va.; and Rosemary Schulte
of Towson, Md.
</P>
<P>
	   Services were scheduled for Tuesday at noonat Our Lady of Sorrows Church in
West River, Md.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1446 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
