<HEADLINE> Technicality Frees Convicted Killers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Authorities were forced to free 11 convicted mob killers
from life prison terms Saturday after courts missed a crucial deadline in the
convicts' cases.
</P>
<P>
	   Italy's clogged court system mandates three trials before a conviction
becomes final. Courts first convicted the 11 defendants in 1998 in a mob
supertrial in Milan. But they let the 1 1-2-year maximum between trials go by at
midnight Friday without opening the second trial.
</P>
<P>
	   The 11 were among 80 people arrested in 1994 in a crackdown on mobs
trafficking guns and drugs in northern Italy. Some of the released prisoners,
including a man implicated in 59 killings, will go immediately to witness
protection programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These are dangerous people and the danger is that they will return to
committing crimes,'' warned Marco Maria Alma, a deputy prosecutor in the
mobsters' trial.
</P>
<P>
	   A total of 53 prisoners had convictions thrown out Saturday because the
trial deadline expired. In addition to the 11 killers, a second group will be
released from convictions for less serious crimes. Two dozen others will remain
behind bars on unrelated charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Court officials blamed Italy's complicated legal system for the prisoners'
releases. They said they were overwhelmed by a case involving scores of
defendants and scores of charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Italy's labyrinthine legal system makes for years-long trials, averaging 600
days for the longest of the three mandated trial phases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1457 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
