<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Hampers Libya Rescue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Bad weather on Saturday hampered the search for five
people missing in the crash of a Swiss-owned plane off the coast of Libya that
killed 17 others, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nineteen people survived Thursday's crash, including the two Libyan pilots,
when the plane made an emergency landing in the Mediterranean sea.
</P>
<P>
	   All 38 passengers on board worked for the Libyan owned Sirte Oil Co. and
were traveling from the Libyan capital, Tripoli, to a refinery in Marsa el-Brega
on the Mediterranean coast. The plane had a three-person crew.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's chairman, Ahmed Aoun, said the search for the missing five --
three Libyans, a Briton and a Filipino -- would continue ``both at sea and along
the coast for as long as possible.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unfortunately, the bad weather conditions have meant we cannot search at
sea today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We never say never, but the chances of finding anyone alive are getting
slimmer and slimmer and before too long it will be virtually nil. It is
extremely sad and we have sent our sincerest condolences to relatives,'' Aoun
said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he was confident that the cause of the crash would be pinpointed
quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The pilots survived and we know where the plane wreckage is, so we hope to
get all technical details as rapidly as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The wreckage is resting in 165 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot had reported that both engines cut out in quick succession as the
plane came in to land. The weather was good at the time of the crash, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Libyan General Civil Aviation Authority has said it would lead the
investigation, helped by two British experts and Swiss investigator Hans-Peter
Graf.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides the pilots, the survivors include eight other Libyans, seven Britons
and two Indians.
</P>
<P>
	   About 2,000 Britons work in Libya's oil industry, with many based in Marsa
el-Brega, 280 miles east of Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
	   The 17 bodies recovered were those of five Britons, three Libyans, two
Canadians, two Croats, two Filipinos, one Tunisian, one Pakistani and one
Indian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
