<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Letterman cracking jokes day after bypass surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Television funnyman David Letterman was cracking jokes
in his hospital room Saturday as he began his recovery from emergency quintuple
bypass surgery.
<P>
	   "I feel fantastic," Letterman, 52, said the morning after his operation,
according to a statement. "In addition to re-routing the arteries, they also
installed an E-Z Pass."
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors performed the surgery on Friday, after an angiogram showed that one
of Letterman's arteries was severely constricted. He had the test because of
high cholesterol and a history of heart disease in his family.
</P>
<P>
	   The wisecracking host came through the procedure well, his surgeon said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Dave's doing great," said Dr. O. Wayne Isom, chairman of cardiothoracic
surgery at the Weill Cornell Center of New York-Presbyterian Hospital. "He's
making jokes and feels terrific. He's on his way to a full recovery."
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman's personal physician, Dr. Louis J. Aronne, and his cardiologist,
Dr. Martin Post, have said it is too soon to say how long the comedian will need
to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman, hospitalized at New York-Presbyterian Hospital, received flowers
from President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who appeared on his show
Wednesday to discuss her likely Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Friends and fans near the midtown Manhattan theater where he tapes "Late
Show with David Letterman" for CBS - and often brings his cameras into shops and
bars - were hoping for his good health.
</P>
<P>
	   "We love him," said Sirajul Islam, who manages a souvenir shop next door to
the theater and often appears with Letterman on the "Late Show." "It's a very
sad weekend for us, the whole neighborhood. ... I was not even sleeping last
night, watching television reporting about his condition, almost all night."
</P>
<P>
	   Most said they were shocked by the sudden surgery, although Letterman has
often joked on the air about his health, starting years ago when he discovered
he had high cholesterol. For a month he went on an oat-bran diet and complained
about it to his audience nightly.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was pretty surprised because I knew he had just gone in for ... a
checkup," said Christopher Fortier, 24, of Southington, Conn., who was browsing
and watching "Late Show" reruns in the CBS store near Letterman's studio. "He's
probably getting a kick out of it, the fact that everybody's paying so much
attention. I guess it'll show him how important he is to a lot of people."
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman's spokesman, Howard Rubenstein, said the comedian's doctors and
family would not release any further details Saturday about his condition "and
ask that Dave's privacy be respected while he recuperates."
</P>
<P>
	   Letterman joked about his arteries with guest Regis Philbin during the
program that was taped on Thursday and aired Friday, joking that after his
tests, doctors might have to "open daddy's rib cage."
</P>
<P>
	   In bypass surgery, doctors rerout the flow of blood to the heart to bypass
blockages.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS plans to telecast reruns of the "Late Show" while Letterman recovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1506 </TRAILER>
