<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two of 3 Tenors Wow Rome Opera  </HEADLINE>
   By JEFF ISRAELY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME (AP) -- In a special 100-year anniversary performance of Giacomo
Puccini's ``Tosca,'' two of the famed ``three tenors'' wowed a Rome opera house
crowd -- and one didn't even sing a word.
</P>
<P>
	   Placido Domingo took the baton Friday night to lead the Rome orchestra as
Luciano Pavarotti sang the lead tenor role in the Puccini classic. It was the
first time the 58-year-old Spaniard, who donned reading glasses, has directed
his Italian singing partner.
</P>
<P>
	   After the final act, shouts of ``bravi'' and 10 minutes of rousing applause
greeted the two bearded performers and the rest of the cast, including Ines
Salazar, the 28-year-old Venezuelan soprano who shined in the title role.
Florentine filmmaker and theater producer Franco Zeffirelli, who directed the
performance, joined the cast on stage afterward for a champagne toast.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Placido Domingo led with flexibility and his usual charge of human
sympathy,'' Milan's daily Corriere della Sera wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   The one-time-only performance gave a boost to the Rome opera, which has long
lived in the shadows of Milan's La Scala and has been plagued by labor strife
and public criticism from its in-house conductor, Giuseppe Sinopoli.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Tosca,'' which highlights Puccini's precise orchestration and evocative
lyrical style, made its debut Jan. 4, 1900, in the same opera house where it was
performed Friday. The opera, set in Rome in 1800, ends with the broken Floria
Tosca hurling herself off the Castel Sant' Angelo as the sun rises over St.
Peter's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
	   '''Tosca' is Rome,'' Zeffirelli said before Friday's performance.
</P>
<P>
	   The performance was Pavarotti's first in Rome since 1992. In that
performance as in this one, the 63-year-old superstar sang the part of Tosca's
lover, Mario Cavaradossi.
</P>
<P>
	   With Spain's Jose Carreras rounding out the trio, the ``three tenors'' have
packed opera houses and sports arenas over the past decade. An American tour is
set for this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1509 </TRAILER>
