<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharpton demands unoccupied city-owned buildings be made into  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The Rev. Al Sharpton and about 150 supporters marched up
125th St. to an abandoned Harlem building on Saturday, calling for the city to
convert city-owned abandoned buildings into shelters for the homeless.
<P>
	   Sharpton said the protest was in honor of Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday
and was inspired by King's message of nonviolent action and civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
	   "We came here today, on Martin Luther King's birthday, to show that the city
has property it could use to house the homeless, but it lacks the moral
imperative to do so," Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Protesters braved below-freezing temperatures, walking briskly from
Sharpton's National Action Network headquarters on 124th St. and Madison Avenue
to the abandoned building at 370 St. Nicholas Ave.
</P>
<P>
	   After Sharpton briefly addressed the crowd, four protesters climbed up a
side fire escape into the building, chaining themselves inside and leading the
crowd in chants against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and police. The protesters hung a
banner out of the burnt-out building's windows proclaiming the site the Martin
Luther King Jr. House.
</P>
<P>
	   One chained protester screamed out to the crowd, "Why is this building
locked up? There are people freezing outside," as police broke the lock off the
metal grille over the front door of the building. Once inside, police cut the
chains holding the protesters and arrested the four for trespassing.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a beautiful example of Mr. King's message of nonviolent action and
civil disobedience," Sharpton said afterwards.
</P>
<P>
	   The protest came amid controversy over Giuliani's policies regarding the
homeless. After a brick-wielding homeless man seriously injured a Queens woman
in November, police began arresting homeless people who refused orders to move
from city sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
	   The city also moved to put children in foster care if their parents sought
city shelter but refused to accept work assignments. Two judges blocked the city
from instituting the foster care rule.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for the mayor declined to comment on the issue on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Sharpton, who is to meet Hillary Rodham Clinton for the first time on
Monday, said he will ask the first lady serious questions about her stance on
homeless policies, healthcare, education and the justice system before deciding
whether to throw his support behind her likely run for the New York Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton will likely face Giuliani in the fight for the Senate seat
being vacated when Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan retires in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
