<DOCNO> APW20000115.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMBINES previous  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) - George W. Bush said Saturday that John McCain's
campaign tax proposal would impose a $40 billion increase on working Americans
by taxing their employer benefits, but the Arizona senator said his tax cut
would more than offset it.
<P>
	   Bush and McCain argued about taxes in televised campaign debate, the last
Republican confrontation before the Iowa caucuses begin the 2000 voting a week
from Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, the front-runner, told McCain, who is debating but not campaigning for
the caucuses, that his tax plan would impose taxes on employer benefits for
workers, such as continuing education, transportation and child care.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's a $40 billion tax increase," Bush told McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   He asked what the senator would tell a single mother who is working and
going to school and would have to pay taxes on the benefit.
</P>
<P>
	   "The first thing I would say to that woman is, 'I've got a tax cut for you,
and Gov. Bush doesn't,"' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the Bush tax cut, $483 billion over five years, wouldn't deal with
the future financing of Social Security, either, which is vital to workers, too.
</P>
<P>
	   "Gov. Bush's plan has not one penny for Social Security, not one penny for
Medicare and not one penny to pay down the national debt," McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said for Bush to run a campaign ad saying he will protect Social Security
is "all hat and no cattle."
</P>
<P>
	   "That's cute," Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're always cute when they're true," McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Bush's tax plan would give 36 percent of the benefits to the richest
1 percent of Americans. "Let's not do the Texas two-step here," McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   Steve Forbes, Bush's closest challenger in Iowa because of McCain's bypass
strategy, said he's spent more time in the state than any other candidate, and
his family has covered 12,000 miles seeking support.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can depend on me," he said. "I will change Washington with your help."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain began with a mistake, thanking the moderator, but calling him Randy.
Editor Dennis Ryerson of The Des Moines Register moderated the 90-minute debate.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator, challenging Bush in the New Hampshire primary but not in the
Iowa caucuses, said, "A lot of you don't know me.
</P>
<P>
	   "I hope there will be a hardy band of Americans and Iowans who will go out
and say, 'Hey, this guy McCain, he's qualified to be president of the United
States.' And I am."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, running as a Republican reformer, later threw in a slap at a federal
subsidy popular with Iowa farmers, saying that he'd end the ethanol program
along with special tax breaks and loopholes because they do not serve the
interest of the American people. Ethanol is a fuel derived from corn.
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe that we ought to increase demand for Iowa products," Bush said.
"That is what ethanol does, John, it increases the demand for Iowa products."
</P>
<P>
	   When they weren't disputing their own rival ideas, all six Republicans, Sen.
Orrin Hatch, conservative activist Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes, Forbes, Bush and
McCain took turns denouncing President Clinton and his administration for its
policies and for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush slipped in a slap at Vice President Al Gore and Bill Bradley, the
Democratic candidates, saying they sound as though they want the federal
government to make all the decisions about American health care. The
Republicans, to a man, oppose that.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republicans took turns questioning each other, and Keyes asked Bush
about a Texas town in which the city council voted to have all business
conducted in Spanish. He called that an assault on "linguistic unity" and said
Bush hadn't done anything about it.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush began his answer in Spanish: "That's not true."
</P>
<P>
	   He said he had expressed concern about the episode, had told the Texas
attorney general to look into it. "English is our nation's language," Bush said.
"That's why I'm for programs to make sure our children learn English." The
candidates 5th graf a0567
</P>
<P>
	   The candidates debate next in Manchester, N.H., on Jan. 26, six days before
the first of the presidential primaries, in New Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has overtaken Bush in the polls there, running statistically eve with
the Texan in the latest surveys.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Arizona senator isn't competing in Iowa, appearing in the debates
but without campaigning actively. So Forbes is No. 2, and far behind - Bush
holds polling leads ranging up to nearly 30 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, Forbes and McCain have clashed on taxes in person and in a barrage of
television ads. Bush promised tax cuts "so help me God" in an earlier New
Hampshire debate, but McCain argues that the governor's $483, five-year cut
would spend more than the budget surplus and would not adequately protect the
future financing of Social Security. Forbes scoffs at both as proposals that
would preserve a system he wants erased in favor of a flat tax.
</P>
<P>
	   The self-financed candidate, heir to a magazine fortune, is broadcasting ads
attacking Bush for allegedly breaking a 1994 anti-tax pledge in Texas by
including increases in some sales and business taxes in a plan to cut property
taxes, a net tax reduction.
</P>
<P>
	   On Saturday, Bob Dole, the 1996 GOP presidential nominee, was featured in a
Des Moines Register ad saying he feared that the kind of negative ads that
wounded him in the last campaign "may be happening again."
</P>
<P>
	   The ad didn't name Forbes, but the target was obvious. In 1996, Forbes waged
a blistering attack campaign on Dole, inflicting campaign damage that lasted
into the final campaign against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   "I emerged the Republican nominee, battered, bruised and broke, and a much
easier target for the negative Clinton-Gore fall campaign," Dole said in his
open letter ad.
</P>
<P>
	   Dole's wife, dropout candidate Elizabeth Dole, has endorsed Bush. Dole
himself has not publicly endorsed a candidate for the 2000 nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The key to the caucuses will be the ability of the rival campaigns to turn
out voters to register their preferences on a winter's Monday night, at 7 p.m.
There are no day-long voting hours as in a primary; to participate, Republicans
have to be at their caucus sites.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a matter of building up strong support and then convincing people
to show up in a living room or a gymnasium on caucus time," Bush said, stopping
by a campaign headquarters on Saturday. "It's a moment in time. It's a different
dynamic than a primary."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
