<HEADLINE> Clinton To Seek Funding for Veterans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans a $1.5 billion increase in
spending for the nation's veterans, much of it aimed at improving health care
services, a senior congressional Democrat said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., said the administration's proposed veterans
spending in fiscal 2001 represents ``the largest VA (Veterans Affairs) increase
requested by any administration.''
</P>
<P>
	   Administration officials declined comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Evans, the senior Democrat on the House Veterans Affairs Committee, said the
administration will request $46 billion for veterans' benefits and services.
That includes a request for a $1.5 billion increase in spending authority, much
of it targeted at expanding health care services, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
	   Specifically, he said, the Clinton budget request includes more than $1.3
billion in increases for veterans medical care, boosting total spending in that
area to $20.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans control both the House and Senate, and it was not immediately
clear what reception the proposed spending increases would receive from GOP
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   Evans called the proposed increase ``significant and needed'' and said he
was especially pleased it includes the full cost of long-term and emergency care
benefits enacted by Congress last year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This budget recommends the funding needed by (the Department of Veterans
Affairs) to make veterans' emergency care and long-term care benefits more than
just words on paper,'' Evans said in a statement. ``The lack of emergency care
has been a serious problem confronted by too many veterans for too long.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our veterans should never be forced to choose between emergency care and
bankruptcy,'' he said. ``That has been the choice too many veterans have been
forced to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
