<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Wants Dead Wife's Heart Back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- A man suing a hospital over the death of his wife
during childbirth learned that doctors removed her heart during an autopsy --
and never returned it, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
	   James Carey filed a motion Friday demanding that Nesbitt Memorial Hospital
return the heart because he might seek to exhume his wife's body ``to make it
whole.''
</P>
<P>
	   Theresa Lynn Carey, 34, died in 1997 during surgery to stop massive blood
loss following the birth of twins. The twins survived.
</P>
<P>
	   Her husband claims doctors waited too long to react to his wife's massive
blood loss. The suit also names the hospital and its parent organization,
Wyoming Valley Health Care System.
</P>
<P>
	   Carey had approved an autopsy to determine the cause of death. But he claims
the real motive for the autopsy was to deflect blame from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   The doctor who performed the autopsy initially ruled that Mrs. Carey died of
cardiac arrest brought on by the hemorrhaging, the motion said. But after
examining the heart, the doctor changed the ruling to cardiac arrest brought on
by coronary artery disease.
</P>
<P>
	   Wyoming Valley Health Care System officials issued a statement defending the
removal of the heart.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Detailed testing can require multiple samples from the same piece of
tissue. This is part of the scientific, medical and legal process to determine
the facts in a case,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Carey was not aware that the heart had been removed until November, when a
lawyer for the health care system said it was still being held at the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
