<HEADLINE> French Producer Alain Poire Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Alain Poire, the producer of some of France's best-loved films,
has died, his son said Saturday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
	   Poire died from cancer at his home in Neuilly-sur-Seine outside Paris on
Friday night, Jean-Marie Poire said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A pillar of French cinema has disappeared, as well as a loyal man with a
good heart,'' President Jacques Chirac said in a statement. ``Cinema is losing
... a passionate producer to whom we owe first-rate films which can be placed
among the greatest successes of French cinema.''
</P>
<P>
	   Born in 1917 in Paris, the elder Poire studied law and worked in a news and
publicity agency before becoming a theater director in 1938.
</P>
<P>
	   During his long career, he produced 250 films and worked with some of
France's best-known directors -- Gerard Oury, Georges Lautner, Francis Veber and
Yves Robert among them.
</P>
<P>
	   His films included some popular successes like ``Fantomas,'' ``The Tall
Blond Man With One Black Shoe'' and ``A Taxi For Tobrouk.'' He received a Cesar
film award in 1985 for his life's work and was named to France's Legion of
Honor.
</P>
<P>
	   Poire is survived by his wife and two sons. He will be buried in
Neuilly-sur-Seine on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
