<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman sentenced to at least 60 years in drunk-driving wreck  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MANTEO, N.C. (AP) - A waitress who killed four New Jersey teen-agers in
a wreck caused by her drunken driving was sentenced Saturday to at least 60
years in prison.
<P>
	   The presiding judge said he sentenced Melissa Marvin, 30, of Kill Devil
Hills, to consecutive sentences because each life she took was important.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't know how I could have said to one parent your child's life didn't
matter," said Superior Court Judge Jerry Tillett, who heard testimony from
victims' relatives and the defendant for about two hours.
</P>
<P>
	   Marvin was sentenced to 24 to 29 months for one count of assault with a
deadly weapon and 174 to 218 months each for four counts of second-degree
murder.
</P>
<P>
	   During the morning session of court, Marvin tearfully pleaded with the
judge.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm so sorry for everything that happened," she said, speaking in court for
the first time and looking at the families of the victims. "I never intended to
hurt anyone. There's not a malicious bone in my body."
</P>
<P>
	   Marvin's attorney refused comment after the sentencing, but said in court he
would file an appeal. Meanwhile, his client remains locked up in jail.
</P>
<P>
	   Killed in the April 6 wreck were Megan Blong, Amanda Geiger and Angie
McGrady, all of Burlington County, N.J., and Shana Lawler, who had moved from
New Jersey to the Outer Banks. All were 17.
</P>
<P>
	   Testimony earlier this week showed Marvin had at least five drinks before
getting behind the wheel and that her blood-alcohol level was nearly three times
the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Blong, father of Megan Blong, told the judge the wreck was "totally
avoidable" and urged the judge to impose a long prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
	   Erin Lawler, sister of Shana Lawler, told the judge: "How I wish more than
anything I could hug my sister one more time."
</P>
<P>
	   "My entire life, I did my utmost to be her big sister and protect her," she
said. "There wasn't anything I could do to protect her on April 6."
</P>
<P>
	   The defendant's mother said her daughter had "remorse and compassion for
those lives that were taken in this crash" and begged for mercy.
</P>
<P>
	   A Dare County jury deliberated about 4 1/2 hours Friday night before finding
Marvin guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury verdicts prompted crying from many in the courtroom but no reaction
from Marvin, who had sobbed frequently during witness testimony. Marvin also was
stoic when the sentence was read by the judge.
</P>
<P>
	   In closing arguments, prosecutor Amber Davis said witnesses reported seeing
Marvin with a foot on her dashboard shortly before the wreck.
</P>
<P>
	   After the accident, Marvin refused to submit to an alcohol breath test, so
police obtained a search warrant to draw blood. The blood sample, taken more
than four hours after the wreck, showed a blood-alcohol level of .21, nearly
three times North Carolina's legal limit of .08.
</P>
<P>
	   Marvin had been arrested for driving while impaired twice before the April
accident. Both times, she was permitted to plead guilty to a lesser charge of
careless and reckless driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1548 </TRAILER>
