<DOCNO> APW20000115.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Contenders Prepare for Vote  </HEADLINE>
   By ANGELA CHARLTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- With little more than two months until Russia's presidential
election, Communists and other Russian groups sketched out strategies Saturday
for their race against heavily favored acting President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
	   In Moscow, Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said he has a ``good
chance'' of winning the election. Zyuganov, who came in second in 1996
presidential elections, called his supporters together for a meeting to prepare
for the March 26 election.
</P>
<P>
	   The Communists have failed to expand their support in recent years beyond
their aging, nostalgic electorate, and have lost several allies in parliament.
Saturday's closed-door meeting was apparently aimed at finding ways to reverse
the trend, and Zyuganov called for cooperation among hard-line groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in Moscow, the reform-oriented Yabloko party formally nominated
lawmaker Grigory Yavlinsky as its candidate. Yavlinsky, who had already said he
would run, promised to push for an open economy and an end to the war in
Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   In Siberia, supporters of Aman Tuleyev, the pro-Communist governor of the
coal-rich but economically depressed Kemerovo region, began collecting
signatures to put his name on the presidential ballot, ITAR-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Other candidates include Konstantin Titov, the centrist governor of the
Samara region, and ultranationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky. Once nominated,
candidates must collect 500,000 signatures by Feb. 13 to be registered for the
election.
</P>
<P>
	   All the candidates will be hard pressed to beat Putin, who assumed power
after Boris Yeltsin resigned Dec. 31 and called early elections. Putin's
popularity is already sky-high, and the short campaign works in his favor by
giving him access to government coffers while leaving his opponents short on
time to raise money and make plans.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls show that Putin has enough backing to win the election in the first
round, but failure to make progress in defeating rebels in Chechnya or economic
troubles could erode that support over the next two months. The Chechnya war has
been largely popular among Russians, and Yavlinsky is the only presidential
candidate to speak out against it.
</P>
<P>
	   A nationwide group of teachers and other educators endorsed Putin's
presidential bid at a meeting Saturday. In recent days, Putin has promised pay
raises for teachers, doctors and other state-funded workers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want him to win, but we will help him only if we are sure that his
interest in education and his intention to support the teacher morally and
materially will not die down after he has taken the oath,'' the educators' group
said in a statement, according to ITAR-Tass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
