<HEADLINE> Mechanical Woes Blamed in Bus Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Investigators have found mechanical defects in
some of the four university-chartered buses involved in a deadly crash on a
foggy interstate two months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Details about the defects and the exact number of buses affected were not
released because the investigation is ongoing, said state police Cpl. Chriss
Grube.
</P>
<P>
	   Grube said Friday that crash investigators had not determined whether the
defects contributed to the Nov. 21 chain-reaction wreck, which left left two
people dead and more than 100 Penn State Univeristy students injured.
</P>
<P>
	   The primary cause was that the buses were traveling too fast for the foggy
conditions on Interstate 80 that day, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The four buses were among six bringing 280 Penn State students back from a
New York City shopping trip.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials from Penn State and Blue and White Lines Inc., the company which
owned the buses, declined to comment on the findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
