<HEADLINE> EU Raises Greek Drachma Target Rate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The European Union on Saturday boosted the rate at
which the Greek drachma would join the single European currency by nearly 3.5
percent, a move that could bring Greece one step closer to adopting the euro.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision by EU deputy finance ministers in Brussels adjusts the
drachma's target rate in the EU's exchange rate mechanism to 340.75 to the euro
from 353.109. Currencies in the mechanism are allowed to fluctuate only within
narrow bands of each other.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision does not directly affect the drachma's market value.
</P>
<P>
	   Greece was not allowed to join the first wave of 11 nations to use the euro
because of its high inflation and budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
	   The news provided a boost for Premier Costas Simitis' government, which
imposed years of financial austerity on Greeks in an effort to become a member
of the euro club. Some analysts speculate that the EU could approve Greece's
euro bid in June.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a historic event," Finance Minister Yannos Papantoniou told a news
conference. "It reflects the strength gained by the Greek economy."
</P>
<P>
	   Papantoniou said the new rate would "help Greece achieve a very low
inflation rate" and create a "positive climate" for the Athens Stock Exchange,
which attracted hundreds of thousands of small investors last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Finance officials in Brussels also welcomed the news. "This decision
contributes to the process of convergence that the Greek government has
initiated in the last year," said Pedro Solbes, EU Commissioner for economic and
monetary affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
