<HEADLINE> Car Crashes Into Blair's Gates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A car smashed into the gates protecting Prime Minister Tony
Blair's official Downing Street residence Saturday, injuring a U.S. tourist and
narrowly missing her three sons.
</P>
<P>
	   Police were questioning the driver to determine whether he deliberately
attempted to smash the barrier or whether he lost control of the car. He was
held on suspicion of causing criminal damage, but his name was not released.
</P>
<P>
	   Eyewitnesses said a tourist pushed her children to safety just before she
was hit and flung fifteen feet. The woman was hospitalized with a broken leg.
Her sons, ages three, six and eight, were not harmed.
</P>
<P>
	   Scotland Yard described the woman as a U.S. tourist but would not release
her name or hometown.
</P>
<P>
	   The black wrought iron gates block access to Downing Street, a short street
at the end of which sits No. 10, the prime minister's office and home. The gates
were damaged, but the car did not break through, police said. They said the
prime minister and his family were not at home at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   Bus driver Peter Saacs, 55, witnessed the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The driver pulled up as if to show someone Downing Street,'' he said.
``Then he was wheel-spinning in front of me and pulled out and went round the
back of our bus and into the gates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
