<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan for underwater cables could affect clamming industry  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) - The state's ocean-clamming industry could be in
trouble if AT&AMP;T receives permission to install a $1.5 billion cable link to
Europe.
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T, one of several telecommunications companies involved in the battle,
asked the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection on Friday not to
grant a hearing to fishermen and to allow fiber optic cable to be installed
underwater.
</P>
<P>
	   The cable, which would carry Internet traffic and is expected to handle
about 8.2 million phone calls simultaneously, would run through some of the
world's richest clam beds.
</P>
<P>
	   "The fisherman don't own the sea bed," Paul Shorb, an attorney for AT&AMP;T,
told The Press of Atlantic City for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Shorb said fisherman "had their shot" to contest the permits in meetings,
and had won several concessions. But the necessary permits were later issued by
the DEP and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
	   Although AT&AMP;T owns just 6 percent of the project, the company estimated that
a delay in laying the cable
</P>
<P>
	   would cost as much as $20 million per month.
</P>
<P>
	   Shorb noted that Internet consumers would absorb the cost of delays, adding
that fisherman should take the battle to court instead of seeking relief from
the state.
</P>
<P>
	   Fisherman say they don't want to delay the project, but rather want to make
certain their safety and liability issues are addressed, such as burying cables
deeper, and removing old, unused cables to prevent fishermen from hitting them.
</P>
<P>
	   "All we're asking for is for them to be responsible for the cables," said
Daniel Cohen, a clam boat owner in the Port of Cape May. "If a fisherman hits a
cable, they (the companies) should be responsible."
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen said the companies have agreed to bury the cables 1 meter deep in some
areas, and 1.2 meters in other areas.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our fishing should not be constrained by a permanent structure," said
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
	   Shorb, however, noted that cables on the land, underground cables in that
they are protected and marked for the public's safety.
</P>
<P>
	   "In a land situation, we get a right-of-way, it's marked and people are not
supposed to dig there," said Shorb.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T and Sprint are in charge of installing the trans-Atlantic cable, which
would provide a link from Tuckerton to Widemouth, England, and an additional
link from Manasquan to Blaabjerg, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
	   The new cable, called a TAT-14, would have two lines to Europe and one line
connecting the two about 25 miles offshore.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of the project's enormous cost, 53 companies are involved in its
progress.
</P>
<P>
	   "After we jointly fund the project, we compete in reselling capacity," said
Shorb.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T's request to the DEP was sent on Friday, following a similar one made
by Sprint. Both companies argue that once a permit has been issued, a public
hearing regarding the permit is too late.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the Trenton-based Garden State Seafood Association previously asked
for a hearing and requested that the installation of cables be halted until a
hearing took place.
</P>
<P>
	   The DEP has said the state Office of Administrative Law would have had to
grant such a hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
