<HEADLINE> Snow Falls in Great Lakes Region  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Rain spread into parts of the West on Saturday and light snow fell around
parts of the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
	   A strong jet stream carried moist air inland from a storm system approaching
the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Steady rain fell over parts of northern and central California, with some
locally heavy rain in the state's northwest corner and along the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
	   About an inch of rain had fallen by midday at Redding and Blue Canyon.
</P>
<P>
	   Winter storm warnings and watches were issued for Saturday night in parts of
northern and central California.
</P>
<P>
	   The area of rain also expanded northward into southwestern Oregon and
eastward into northern Nevada, with a few light showers reaching southern Idaho
and western Utah.
</P>
<P>
	   A few snow showers were scattered at higher elevations of California's
Sierra, south-central Oregon, northern Nevada and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
	   Showers also were scattered around Washington's Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
	   Farther east, light snow fell from northeastern Minnesota into northern
Wisconsin and both Upper and Lower Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   A chance of snow showers or flurries was forecast during the night in
northern Pennsylvania, New York state and New England.
</P>
<P>
	   On the northern Plains, a few isolated, light snow showers moved eastward
across Montana and North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
	   Snow also was possible in western South Dakota and parts of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
	   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a morning low
of 17 below zero at Saranac Lake, N.Y., to a midday reading of 76 at Harlingen,
Texas. The lowest wind chill was 62 below zero at Frenchville, Maine, and the
highest heat index was 78 at Harlingen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
