<HEADLINE> Jackson Rallies for Ill. Students  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson used the birthday of slain civil
rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. as a rallying point Saturday in his crusade
for six black students expelled from the Decatur school system.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We seek to honor his memory by fighting from Decatur to Wall Street,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to supporters at the Rainbow-PUSH Coalition's weekly meeting,
Jackson reaffirmed plans to appeal a judge's decision upholding the expulsions
and geared up for a rally Saturday night in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
	   He contended U.S. District Judge Michael McCuskey put ``politics over
principle'' in his ruling and said, ``This is not the first time we've had to
fight unjust judges.''
</P>
<P>
	   The teens originally were expelled for up to two years as the result of a
bleacher-clearing fight at a football game last September. After intervention by
Jackson and the governor, the city's school board cut the time to one year and
let the six teens attend alternative schools.
</P>
<P>
	   But Jackson said the punishment was still too harsh for a fight that
involved no weapons or drugs and that hurt no one seriously. He said he would
ask the school board on Tuesday to reinstate a seventh student who withdrew from
school rather than face expulsion. Jackson says the teen-ager was being hit and
was not fighting.
</P>
<P>
	   During protests in Decatur late last year, Jackson said the expulsions were
not a racial issue. But in the lawsuit, the students argued the school district
disproportionately expelled black students and disciplined them more harshly
than white students.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge said there was no evidence race was an issue. He also said the
students' actions threatened community safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
