<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Lawmakers Address Sprawl  </HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER COLEMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- For 50 years, Natomas Air Field and the pilots
who used it had few neighbors.
</P>
<P>
	   The airport was built in a flood plain in the fields north of Sacramento.
Then came the levee improvements, and in 1997, city officials lifted a building
moratorium in the plain, letting loose a flood of shopping centers, movie
theaters and homes.
</P>
<P>
	   Overnight, it seemed, Russ Kilmer saw Sacramento grow toward him and his
27-acre airport.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, in what anti-urban sprawl activists say is a perfect illustration of
their concerns, Kilmer and his 40 crop dusters and private planes are being
pushed off the land to make way for more houses and stores. City officials
changed the area's zoning from agriculture to residential and retail and gave
Kilmer until the end of this month to shut the airport down.
</P>
<P>
	   Development is coming even though the airport's land was contaminated by
decades of farm chemicals from the crop dusters, Kilmer said. He doesn't believe
anyone would pay to clean it up for housing, but the rules are more lenient for
commercial use, and commercial businesses are taking advantage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's what's happening all over,'' Kilmer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cities are sprawling over farm land and into unsuitable areas at an alarming
rate, even with the environmental hazards that could pose, said Brett Hulsey,
director of the Sierra Club's anti-sprawl project.
</P>
<P>
	   ``California has been dealing with growth issues overall, but of the 11
states that have growth-management acts, California ranks ninth,'' Hulsey said.
``That basically means the laws aren't working.''
</P>
<P>
	   There are state laws that require land-use plans for forest, agricultural
and coastal land, but the laws don't tell counties and cities how to implement
those plans, said Peter Detwiler, a consultant for the Senate Committee on Local
Government.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, California's laws have been described as ``Jell-O without a
mold,'' Detwiler said. With the absence of policy comes urban sprawl, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sprawl, as defined by the California Futures Network, is poorly planned
residential developments that devour farmland and open space and spawn traffic
congestion, pollution and a diminished quality of life.
</P>
<P>
	   It occurs mostly on the edges of cities where there are few neighbors to
cry: ``Not in my backyard,'' Detwiler said.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue of urban sprawl surfaces for discussion every few years, then
disappears, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   This appears to be a year when legislators are willing to talk about it,
especially in light of projections that the state's population is expected to
grow by 12 million over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Groups such as the California Futures Network are promoting smart growth --
urban building that doesn't mean long commutes. The California Building Industry
Association is advancing a ``job-centered'' housing policy that would remove
obstacles to building higher-density urban housing near jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Overly restrictive policies would push California into a housing crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Frankly, I think we're already at a crisis stage,'' said spokesman Tim
Coyle.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department of Finance estimates 250,000 new homes should be built
each year to keep up with population growth, but only about half that number are
built.
</P>
<P>
	   A group of legislators will meet informally next week for the first time to
address the issue in a caucus on responsible growth, said Assemblywoman Pat
Wiggins.
</P>
<P>
	   The caucus will look at recommendations from a panel that studied the issue
last year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of all the things the Legislature did last year, the one true failing
grade we give them is this area,'' said Gerald Meral, executive director of the
Planning and Conservation League. ``There's not a hint, not a ripple, not a
whisper that indicates they will do anything.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kilmer, meanwhile, has contacted every member of the Sacramento City Council
in an effort to keep his airport operating, at least for a few more years until
he retires.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't blame the developers. Housing, shopping, transportation -- they're
just responding to a need,'' he said. ``But you just can't relocate an
airport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1717 </TRAILER>
