<HEADLINE> Germans March For Communist Heroes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- An estimated 100,000 people marched in commemoration of two
heroes of German communism in eastern Berlin on Saturday, guarded by police
after a threat against the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
	   No violence was reported during the march to a memorial for Rosa Luxemburg
and Karl Liebknecht, who were killed by soldiers in Berlin during a failed 1919
uprising.
</P>
<P>
	   The Party of Democratic Socialism, the former East German Communist Party,
organized the event. Leaders of the party laid wreaths at the memorial.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the former East German regime, the deaths of Liebknecht and Luxemburg
were marked with annual commemorations. The party revived the marches in 1992,
two years after Germany was officially reunified.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 2,000 police, including rooftop snipers and bomb experts, protected
marchers after the party received a letter from a man wanted on arson charges
who threatened to use a machine gun and hand grenades on the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
	   Police distributed leaflets to residents along the route, warning them to
look out for suspicious people or packages.
</P>
<P>
	   The party had called off the originally planned march the previous Sunday
because of the threat, citing police pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
