<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinelands Commission gives OK to reopen landfill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SOUTHAMPTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Despite the objections of
environmentalists and many residents, the New Jersey Pinelands Commission voted
to reopen a landfill in Ocean Township and build half a dozen communications
towers in the forest preserve.
<P>
	   The 9-4 vote on Friday to reopen the landfill came after the commission's
newly appointed chairman, Jerrold L. Jacobs, took his seat for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   The landfill and tower issues had been under debate for months, with a
majority of public comment aimed at the landfill, which was closed 11 years ago
because its contaminants posed a threat to people living nearby. The landfill
has never been properly cleaned and capped.
</P>
<P>
	   The communications towers also drew concern from people who said the
structures are not in the best interests of the Pine Barrens.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacobs, who voted for the landfill plan, said the plan wasn't perfect but
would prevent legal delays and improve the landfill.
</P>
<P>
	   "I voted for it on the basis that it was the best solution to a not-perfect
situation," Jacobs told The Press of Atlantic City for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists said the vote sets a bad precedent, and worried that new
waste to the landfill could add lead, mercury and other pollutants to the dump.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Department of Environmental Protection has wanted to hire owner
United Environmental Services Inc. to reopen the landfill. The company has a
plan to take in about 435,000 cubic yards of broken glass and demolition and
construction debris.
</P>
<P>
	   The waste would cover contaminates already there and level a part of the
site that is lined to prevent leachates from entering soil or groundwater. The
company would be paid about $7 million to accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The money would also be used to pay for a permanent cap to the lined section
of the landfill. Right now, rainwater percolates through the open portion of the
landfill and leaches about 30,000 gallons a day of contaminated water into the
Kirkwood-Cohansey aquifer.
</P>
<P>
	   But to launch the plan, the DEP needed the commission to waive strict rules
concerning Pinelands waste.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert W. McIntosh Jr., who sits on the panel on behalf of the U.S.
Secretary of the Interior, voted against the plan. McIntosh said he wanted to
know if there were any financial assurances the company would be able to
complete the work. Residents said they had the same concern.
</P>
<P>
	   Meantime, Jeff Tittle, director of the New Jersey chapter of the Sierra
Club, said United Environmental Services should have to pay for the capping as
required by state law, rather than reopening the dump.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on Friday, the commission unanimously approved a plan to allow Sprint
and Omnipoint to erect communications towers as high as 200 feet in the heart of
the Pinelands. The vote came a year after the commission allowed cellular phone
service providers to build as many as 23 towers in the region.
</P>
<P>
	   That plan calls for using 29 existing or previously approved towers, plus
six new ones, to be built to support Personal Communications Systems, or PCS.
The exact locations of the towers will depend on property negotiations and local
approvals.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacobs said an expert determined the PCS plan uses the fewest towers to
deliver service. He also said the commission would have been forced to accept
the plan anyway because Federal Communications Commission rules say certain
levels of service can't be denied to providers who carry a license for it.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just think it's a sellout to the (Pinelands) Comprehensive Management
Plan to allow all those towers in some of the most environmentally sensitive
sections of the pines just so someone speeding to Atlantic City can talk on his
phone," Tittle said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sally Dudley, Whitman's other appointment to the commission and considered a
strong environmentalist, was unable to vote because the state Senate last week
failed to approve her nomination before adjourning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1734 </TRAILER>
