<HEADLINE> DEBATE NOTEBOOK: Pink pigs protest Pentagon pork  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) - Two men in pink pig costumes and carrying a
briefcase of play money emerged from a stretch limousine outside the site of
Saturday's Republican presidential debate.
<P>
	   "I'm a Pentagon contractor," one said, a plastic cigar clenched between his
teeth.
</P>
<P>
	   The pigs, representatives of the anti-defense spending group Iowans for
Sensible Priorities, said they were in town to protest Pentagon pork.
</P>
<P>
	   "We get money from the Pentagon and we give money back to the candidates,"
said one pig, who declined to identify himself.
</P>
<P>
	   Someone from the group, planted in the crowd, then began singing "Hail to
the Pork," a parody set to the tune of the "Hail to the Chief."
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   More than an hour before debate began, supporters of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and publisher Steve Forbes took their respective spots opposite each other
on the lawn of Iowa Public Television studios.
</P>
<P>
	   With campaign signs stacked on top of each other, Bush supporters
antagonized their Republican counterparts with screams of "We want Bush. We love
Bush."
</P>
<P>
	   The Forbes crowd, not to be outdone, grabbed megaphones and began screaming:
"Where's your tax plan?"
</P>
<P>
	   Decked out in a neon orange Forbes T-shirt and ski cap, 81-year-old Paul
Sandhorst said the 2000 campaign was his first foray into political activism.
</P>
<P>
	   "Lee Iacocca was my choice a few years ago - a businessman who knows how to
do things," Sandhorst said.
</P>
<P>
	   As for Forbes, Sandhorst said, "he doesn't have any debts. No one's done him
any favors."
</P>
<P>
	   ---
</P>
<P>
	   Decked out in a straw hat and carrying a sign that read "Grandmas for Bush,"
Rosanne Freeburg was on a mission - to obtain kiss No. 27 from George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   The 72-year-old Cedar Rapids woman has kissed the Texas governor 26 times
during the past year as he campaigned in Iowa for the Republican president
nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've had 26 kisses for him," she said gleefully.
</P>
<P>
	   Freeburg said she supports Bush because of his stance on charter schools and
she plans to follow him to New Hampshire next week.
</P>
<P>
	   With scores of Bush supporters behind her, Freeburg stepped forward and sang
her theme song, "Should all the Grandmas Vote for Bush," to the tune of "Auld
Lang Syne."
</P>
</TEXT>
