<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York GOP boss says McCain guilty of hypocrisy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The head of New York's Republican Party on Saturday
blasted Sen. John McCain's complaints about challenges to his qualifying
petitions for the state's presidential primary as "the height of hypocrisy."
<P>
	   Citing McCain's successful use of petition requirements in Arizona to knock
a potential challenger off the GOP Senate primary ballot in that state in 1998,
New York GOP boss William Powers said, "Senator McCain has demonstrated he is
just another politician who will say one thing and do another when it benefits
him."
</P>
<P>
	   Powers, a supporter of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's presidential candidacy,
has mounted challenges to McCain's petitions to qualify for New York's March 7
primary ballot. That effort has been denounced by McCain as "Stalinist
politics."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's campaign chairman in New York on Saturday said the challenge is
Bush's "last defense against a surging John McCain."
</P>
<P>
	   "What you are seeing is an advertisement of the state party's insecurity,"
said Guy Molinari, McCain state chairman and Staten Island borough president.
"John McCain is poised to upset George W. Bush's parade to the coronation. Bill
Powers and the Bush campaign are anxious to avoid a fair fight, and they are
using authoritarian tactics to do it."
</P>
<P>
	   Powers said McCain should be subject to the same political rules as other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is clear that Senator McCain believes one special set of rules applies
to him, and another set of rules applies to everyone else," Powers said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Republican Party is attempting to ensure that the people who signed
Senator McCain's petitions are registered Republicans who live in the right
congressional districts," the New York GOP leader said. "Sound familiar, Senator
McCain? That is almost exactly what you did in Arizona."
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, when reports circulated of McCain's own use of petition
challenges against potential opponents in Arizona, McCain spokesman Howard
Opinsky insisted the two situations are quite different. The challenges to
McCain in New York include alleged violations of "highly technical things
including the color of the paper on which the petitions were signed," Opinsky
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We followed rules that are very open in Arizona," Opinsky said Friday. "The
rules in New York are written to keep people off the ballot, legitimate
candidates, so that the establishment can control the process."
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Powers' lead attorney in the case, Jeffrey Buley, has said the New
York review of McCain's petitions only involves checking to see if those who
signed McCain petitions are enrolled Republicans and live in the congressional
districts where the petitions were circulated. Buley said hypertechnical
petition requirements will not be used against McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, the McCain camp has objected because Bush supporters in New
York had originally said they planned no challenges to the McCain petitions. The
challenges were filed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain and his New York campaign director, Staten Island Borough President
Guy Molinari, have called on Bush to use his influence with Powers and Gov.
George Pataki, also a Bush supporter, to get the challenges withdrawn. Bush has
refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has also filed a federal lawsuit in an attempt to open up the ballot
in New York. That lawsuit will be heard at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, GOP candidates must circulate petitions to qualify separate
convention delegate slates in each of the state's 31 congressional districts in
which they wish to compete. In effect, there are 31 separate GOP primaries in
New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Molinari has conceded the McCain petitions have probably come up short on
the required number of signatures in at least five of the 31 districts, and
possibly in a sixth. Buley is examining all of McCain's petitions.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and millionaire publisher Steve Forbes have both filed petitions they
claim qualify them for the primary ballot in all 31 congressional districts.
Only McCain, among the other GOP presidential contenders, also attempted to
qualify for the New York ballot through the petition process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1747 </TRAILER>
