<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Troops Stay in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
   By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KOIDU, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Nigeria has halted the pullout of intervention
troops from Sierra Leone to help keep the fragile peace in the country until a
U.N. force is fully deployed, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, officials reported that a U.N. peacekeeper drowned in the West
African country, becoming the first casualty suffered by a member of the U.N.
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
	   Maj. Gen. Gabriel Pamba, a commander of the Nigerian-led West African
intervention force known as ECOMOG, said the troops would remain in place to
prevent a dangerous power vacuum in Sierra Leone, where the rebel group
Revolutionary United Front and government forces signed a peace accord in July.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the accord, the rebels continue to terrorize civilians in the dense
jungle interior, according to the United Nations and human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
	   ECOMOG was the main fighting force backing Sierra Leone's government during
the war and now provides security alongside U.N. peacekeepers, who began
arriving in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet Nigeria maintained that it could not afford its ECOMOG commitment and
late last year withdrew more than a third of the 10,000-member force.
</P>
<P>
	   ``ECOMOG was not meant to stay in Sierra Leone forever. But we will continue
until the U.N. peacekeepers are fully deployed,'' Pamba said.
</P>
<P>
	   Since November, the U.N. has begun deploying 6,000 peacekeepers -- mainly
Indians, Nigerians and Kenyans. On Wednesday, the Security Council began
considering a British proposal to nearly double the force's strength to 11,100
troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Col. J.S. Sandhu, a U.N. military officer, said Saturday that Yusuf
Birik, a Kenyan soldier, drowned while participating in a water obstacle course
during training exercises in Magburaka, 120 miles north of Freetown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
