	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New polling suggests Vice President Al Gore has slipped
past former Sen. Bill Bradley to retake a solid lead in their campaign for New
Hampshire's Democratic primary election, Newsweek reported today. The
newsmagazine said 50 percent of people who plan to vote in the Feb. 1 Democratic
primary favored Gore, while 36 percent preferred Bradley. The other 14 percent
were undecided. Newsweek said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., moved in the Republican
campaign from a statistical dead heat to a slight lead over the national
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
