plans to appeal a judge's decision upholding the expulsions and geared up for a
rally tonight in Decatur. He contended the judge put "politics over principle"
in his ruling and said, "This is not the first time we've had to fight unjust
judges."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mystery of Nixon Tape May Be Solved
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Archives is exploring whether new technology
could solve an enduring mystery of Watergate: What was said during the infamous
18 1/2-minute gap on one of President Nixon's tapes recorded three days after
the break-in. It is part of a recording made June 20, 1972 as Nixon chatted with
his chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman. Public disclosure of the erasure eroded
Nixon's credibility at a time when his presidency was unraveling. Steve
St.Croix, an audio expert, said technology developed in the past three years
might make it possible to recover conversation, even from tapes repeatedly
erased on older machines.
</P>
