<HEADLINE> Report Says Pinochet Outlook Grim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The independent medical team examining Gen. Augusto Pinochet
concluded he would die ``long before'' the expected 18 months needed to complete
his extradition to Spain on torture charges, The Sunday Telegraph reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Home Secretary Jack Straw said he was inclined to stop
extradition proceedings against Pinochet after four specialists unanimously
found the 84-year-old general unfit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet requires a pacemaker and has reportedly suffered from two mild
strokes, diabetes, heart disease and depression.
</P>
<P>
	   The key conclusion in the confidential medical report was that the former
dictator would not live to stand trial in Spain, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pinochet has been under house arrest in Britain for 15 months during legal
battles over a Spanish attempt to extradite him for trial on human rights abuses
during his 1973-90 rule.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Jack Straw has made a very big mistake in this case'' in neglecting
Pinochet's deteriorating health,'' Fernando Barros, Pinochet's spokesman, told
the newspaper. ``The general deserves an apology.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Home Office has said it would accept arguments on Pinochet's fate from
Spain, as well as France, Switzerland and Belgium -- which also have extradition
requests -- before making a final decision on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Amnesty International said it was considering asking for a
judicial review of the way the medical examination was carried out.
</P>
<P>
	   At Pinochet's rented home in Wentworth, about 40 protesters gathered
Saturday to reiterate demands that Pinochet face trial for his alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said the campaigners were ``noisy but peaceful.'' There were no
arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
