<HEADLINE> Finland To Choose New President  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTI HUUHTANEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- With the major presidential aspirants agreeing on
the big issues, Finnish voters are turning to the candidates' personalities to
make up their minds for Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
	   Voters are choosing between, among others, a legislator who has publicly
described having sex in a waterbed, a government minister who refuses to marry
her longtime boyfriend and a suave politician who has been called the ``Kennedy
of Finland.''
</P>
<P>
	   It was considered unlikely that any of the seven candidates -- four of them
women -- would win the required 50 percent of the vote. A runoff between the two
top vote-getters is expected on Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
	   No matter who is elected, no major changes are expected in foreign and
security policy, the president's traditional domain, because of a consensus
among leading Finnish politicians. The main candidates approve of membership in
the European Union, which Finland joined in 1995, and say they will continue the
country's post-World War II policy of neutrality.
</P>
<P>
	   The election is only the second time Finns have voted directly for a
president since gaining independence from Russia in 1917. Before, voters cast
their ballot for an electoral college that chose the president -- a process
often marred by political deals.
</P>
<P>
	   The lack of issues in the election has meant low-key campaigns, with
candidates refusing to criticize each other or even argue.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, people have been drawn to campaign rallies this year by the
personalities, and a high turnout was expected at the polls. Thirty-two percent
of the country's 4.2 million voters already cast ballots in a week of advance
voting at post offices.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the two leading candidates is former Prime Minister Esko Aho, 45.
Local media have dubbed Aho the ``Kennedy of Finland'' because of his dapper and
youthful appearance and the inclusion of his family in his campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
	   His main opponent, 56-year-old foreign minister Tarja Halonen, is a former
unionist who has said she will not marry her longtime boyfriend. She also has
declined to join the Evangelical Lutheran Church in a country where 85 percent
of the people are members. Finland has never had a female president.
</P>
<P>
	   Three recent major polls have shown Aho, of the opposition Center Party, and
Halonen, a Social Democrat, ahead of the other candidates and in a close race.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those trailing in the polls were 54-year-old Parliament speaker Riitta
Uosukainen and 64-year-old former U.N. peace envoy Elisabeth Rehn.
</P>
<P>
	   The flamboyant Uosukainen shocked the nation with candid descriptions of
lovemaking on a waterbed. She led earlier surveys, but her support has fallen,
according to recent polls.
</P>
<P>
	   Rehn was the first female defense minister of a Western country. She was
narrowly defeated by President Martti Ahtisaari in a runoff in 1994, but she was
far behind in the polls this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Other candidates include Risto Kuisma, a former hard-drinking union boss who
is now a leading member of the temperance movement; Ilkka Hakalehto, a historian
who opposes Finland's EU membership; and Green Party member Heidi Hautala, who
sits in the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   President Ahtisaari, 62, is not seeking a second term after six years in
office. He has said he will take a job in an international organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1806 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0184 </DOCNO>
