<HEADLINE> Israel Jets Strike Southern Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes attacked suspected guerrilla
hideouts in southern Lebanon on Saturday in the fifth such strike in a week.
</P>
<P>
	   The airstrikes came after two guerrilla groups claimed to have attacked
Israeli troops and their militia allies, Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Two Israeli jets fired four missiles at targets in Iqlim al-Tuffah, a
stronghold of Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas that faces an Israeli-occupied
border zone, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Black smoke billowed from the area, but there was no word on casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   The district is a frequent target of Israeli warplanes. It is used by
Hezbollah guerrillas to attack Israeli troops and allied militiamen in the
occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
	   Lebanese guerrillas are fighting to oust 1,500 Israeli soldiers and 2,500
South Lebanon Army militiamen from the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
	   The jets returned 2 1/2 hours later to strike near the village of Maidoun,
just outside the zone. In Jerusalem, the Israeli military confirmed the
airstrikes and said all planes returned safely.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, the Hezbollah group and the Syrian-backed Amal movement said their
forces had fired rockets and mortars at Israeli and allied positions. No
casualties were reported in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   The fighting in south Lebanon has continued despite hopes of peace between
Lebanon and Israel now that the Jewish state has resumed negotiations with
Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel contends that the occupied zone, set up in 1985, is necessary to
protect its northern towns from cross-border guerrilla attacks. Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak has promised to withdraw Israeli troops from south Lebanon
by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
