<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Frustrated With Elian's Delay  </HEADLINE>
   By ANITA SNOW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Increasingly frustrated by 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez's
extended stay in the United States, tens of thousands of protesters rallied to
demand the child's return in the angriest gathering so far in six weeks of
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How long? How long do we have to wait?'' shouted actor Julio Casanova, one
among a group of speakers who addressed the crowd. He referred to the Miami
relatives sheltering Elian as ``the torturers of his innocence.''
</P>
<P>
	   While a march of tens of thousands of mothers on Friday appealed to familial
sentiment, Saturday's gathering at the spot where Fidel Castro declared the
socialist character of his government almost four decades ago was a strident
political meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Because of the historical significance of the site -- a street corner in the
heart of Havana's Vedado neighborhood -- and because of the political nature of
the gathering, many demonstrators had thought the Cuban leader would attend.
Ultimately Castro did not show.
</P>
<P>
	   The gathering came one day after the deadline the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service had set for Elian to be returned to his father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, who lives in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   But last week, Attorney General Janet Reno lifted the deadline to give
Elian's relatives in Miami a chance to fight in federal court to keep the boy
with them in the United States. Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, says he
can give the child a better life off the communist island.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuban authorities are becoming increasingly impatient with the delays, which
they say only increases the psychological suffering of a small boy who lost his
mother at sea and is now separated from his father and grandparents in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian was found clinging to an inner tube Nov. 25 off the coast of Florida
after his mother, stepfather and others died in a failed attempt to reach U.S.
shores.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuba insists Elian was ``kidnapped'' and is being ``held hostage'' by
enemies of Castro's communist government in Miami. Elian's Miami relatives and
the anti-Castro exile leaders who constantly visit the family there are
typically referred to here as ``criminals,'' ``mafia members,'' ``terrorists''
and ``wolves.''
</P>
<P>
	   Like most other such demonstrations, Saturday's rally was broadcast live on
government television.
</P>
<P>
	   The broadcast included black and white film clips of the day Castro stood on
the same site in April 1961 and defined the Cuban revolution as socialist.
During that same speech, Castro announced that a U.S.-backed invasion force was
headed toward the island. The following day, CIA-sponsored troops launched the
disastrous Bay of Pigs invasion.
</P>
<P>
	   The angry political tone of Saturday's rally seemed aimed at letting
Washington know that Cuba was getting fed up.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricardo Alarcon, president of the National Assembly and Castro's point man
on U.S.-Cuban relations, told The Associated Press on Friday that Cuban
authorities are frustrated by Reno's failure to set a new deadline and the INS's
failure to enforce its decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1831 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinelands Commission gives OK to reopen landfill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SOUTHAMPTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Despite the objections of
environmentalists and many residents, the New Jersey Pinelands Commission voted
to reopen a landfill in Ocean Township and build half a dozen communications
towers in the forest preserve.
<P>
	   The 9-4 vote on Friday to reopen the landfill came after the commission's
newly appointed chairman, Jerrold L. Jacobs, took his seat for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   The landfill and tower issues had been under debate for months, with a
majority of public comment aimed at the landfill, which was closed 11 years ago
because its contaminants posed a threat to people living nearby. The landfill
has never been properly cleaned and capped.
</P>
<P>
	   The communications towers also drew concern from people who said the
structures are not in the best interests of the Pine Barrens.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacobs, who voted for the landfill plan, said the plan wasn't perfect but
would prevent legal delays and improve the landfill.
</P>
<P>
	   "I voted for it on the basis that it was the best solution to a not-perfect
situation," Jacobs told The Press of Atlantic City for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists said the vote sets a bad precedent, and worried that new
waste to the landfill could add lead, mercury and other pollutants to the dump.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Department of Environmental Protection has wanted to hire owner
United Environmental Services Inc. to reopen the landfill. The company has a
plan to take in about 435,000 cubic yards of broken glass and demolition and
construction debris.
</P>
<P>
	   The waste would cover contaminates already there and level a part of the
site that is lined to prevent leachates from entering soil or groundwater. The
company would be paid about $7 million to accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The money would also be used to pay for a permanent cap to the lined section
of the landfill. Right now, rainwater percolates through the open portion of the
landfill and leaches about 30,000 gallons a day of contaminated water into the
Kirkwood-Cohansey aquifer.
</P>
<P>
	   But to launch the plan, the DEP needed the commission to waive strict rules
concerning Pinelands waste.
</P>
<P>
	   Robert W. McIntosh Jr., who sits on the panel on behalf of the U.S.
Secretary of the Interior, voted against the plan. McIntosh said he wanted to
know if there were any financial assurances the company would be able to
complete the work. Residents said they had the same concern.
</P>
<P>
	   Meantime, Jeff Tittle, director of the New Jersey chapter of the Sierra
Club, said United Environmental Services should have to pay for the capping as
required by state law, rather than reopening the dump.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on Friday, the commission unanimously approved a plan to allow Sprint
and Omnipoint to erect communications towers as high as 200 feet in the heart of
the Pinelands. The vote came a year after the commission allowed cellular phone
service providers to build as many as 23 towers in the region.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan approved Friday calls for using 29 existing or previously approved
towers, plus six new ones, to be built to support Personal Communications
Systems, or PCS. The exact locations of the towers will depend on property
negotiations and local approvals.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacobs said an expert determined the PCS plan uses the fewest towers to
deliver service. He also said the commission would have been forced to accept
the plan anyway because Federal Communications Commission rules say certain
levels of service can't be denied to providers who carry a license for it.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just think it's a sellout to the (Pinelands) Comprehensive Management
Plan to allow all those towers in some of the most environmentally sensitive
sections of the pines just so someone speeding to Atlantic City can talk on his
phone," Tittle said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sally Dudley, Whitman's other appointment to the commission and considered a
strong environmentalist, was unable to vote because the state Senate last week
failed to approve her nomination before adjourning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-15-00 1838 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadorean Indian Protest Flops  </HEADLINE>
   By MONTE HAYES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Nationwide demonstrations planned by organizations
representing Ecuador's 4 million Indians failed to materialize Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Protest leaders, who are calling for the resignation of President Jamil
Mahuad, announced without explanation that the marches were being postponed
until Monday, or perhaps later.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Mahuad, under growing calls to step down for his failure to stop
Ecuador's economic decline, urged citizens to reject violence and ``political
cannibalism'' to resolve the Andean nation's economic and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We ask Ecuadoreans not to resort to violent actions and instead to make
use of dialogue and rationality to resolve problems,'' he said during his
state-of-the-union address to Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   The Indians may have been persuaded not to demonstrate by a toughly worded
warning from the armed forces against violent protests.
</P>
<P>
	   There also were reports of disputes among groups that belong to the umbrella
Indian organization on when and how to carry out the protest.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the planned protest, Indians had threatened to blockade highways
to paralyze traffic and keep farm produce from reaching the cities.
</P>
<P>
	   The army took control of Ecuador's highways on Saturday. Troop carriers
patrolled the major routes and threw up checkpoints, searching car and bus
passengers for weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1842 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Received Subsidy Payments  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- A partnership that includes Bill Bradley received
$2,150 in farm subsidy payments in 1997 and 1998, campaign aides said Saturday.
As a Democratic senator from New Jersey, Bradley had opposed such payments.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley got $700 from the payments to the 250-acre farm in Missouri he owns
with a high school friend, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign spokeswoman Anita Dunn said the farm also received relief payments
after floods in 1993. Bradley donated his share to charity, added Dunn, who did
not immediately know the amount.
</P>
<P>
	   During last week's debate, Vice President Al Gore accused Bradley of voting
against flood relief that year. Bradley said Gore distorted his record and he
insisted he eventually voted for the relief package.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said Gore's record was tainted because he accepted federal subsidy
payments for growing tobacco on the Gore family's Tennessee tobacco farm.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Bradley aides said, the Democratic National Committee had
accepted soft money from the tobacco industry to put on the 1996 convention that
nominated Gore and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator Bradley continues to stoop to new lows every day,'' said Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley has come under fire in the campaign for Iowa's precinct caucuses on
Jan. 24 for not being sympathetic to farm assistance programs. While he insists
he was only representing his state, he has continued to maintain the Missouri
farm operation.
</P>
<P>
	   Dunn, who was questioned about the subsidies by a reporter, argued that
subsidies Bradley received were minor and said his opposition to those programs
showed he was not influenced by personal gain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If you want to see the difference between the two candidates, nothing
better illustrates it than the fact that Bill Bradley voted against a program
from which his partnership received a small subsidy,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Lehane said the latest exchange underscores the importance of Gore's
challenge to step up the number of campaign debates.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We reiterate our challenge that he debate us weekly,'' Lehane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Plans Parliament Referendum  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Ukraine will hold a nationwide referendum on April 16
that could lead to dissolving the parliament and forming a new bicameral
legislature, President Leonid Kuchma said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Kuchma has long been at odds with the leftist-dominated parliament, or
Verkhovna Rada, which he accuses of blocking economic reforms in the
impoverished former Soviet republic. He has been threatening such a referendum
for months.
</P>
<P>
	   The Central Election Committee collected about 4 million signatures in
support of the referendum, the Interfax news agency reported. At least 3 million
signatures representing at least two-thirds of Ukraine's regions are required to
declare a referendum.
</P>
<P>
	   The referendum is to consist of six questions. One is a confidence vote in
the parliament. If a majority of voters choose no-confidence, the parliament
could be disbanded.
</P>
<P>
	   Another question asks whether to give Kuchma the right to dismiss the Rada
if it fails to adopt a budget in three months.
</P>
<P>
	   Voters would be asked to choose whether to abolish lawmakers' immunity from
prosecution. They also would choose whether to reduce the 450-seat parliament to
a 300-seat body and split it into two houses, one composed of nationally elected
candidates and the other made up of municipal officials and regional governors
appointed by the president.
</P>
<P>
	   Leftist factions in parliament oppose the proposed referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 1849 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000115.0191 </DOCNO>
