<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Demand Cuban Boy's Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Increasingly frustrated by 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez's
extended stay in the United States, tens of thousands of Cuban protesters
rallied today to demand the child's return in the angriest gathering so far in
six weeks of demonstrations. The gathering came one day after the deadline the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service had set for Elian to be returned to
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who lives in Cuba. But last week, Attorney
General Janet Reno lifted the deadline to give Elian's relatives in Miami a
chance to fight in federal court to keep the boy with them in the United States.
Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, says he can give the child a better life
off the communist island.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Delays West Bank Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel decided Saturday to postpone a withdrawal from the
West Bank for at least two weeks over a dispute with the Palestinians on the
land to be included in the pullout. The Palestinians have accused Israel of
neglecting the peace talks with them in favor of the Syrian negotiations, which
reopened in December and will continue Wednesday in the United States.
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Cabinet warned in a meeting Friday that
Israeli sluggishness in the negotiations will prevent the sides from working out
a framework on a final peace agreement by a Feb. 13 deadline.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accused Serb War Criminal Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A notorious Serb paramilitary leader accused of
war crimes was shot and killed by masked gunmen on Saturday in a Belgrade hotel.
The official Tanjug news agency confirmed that Zeljko Raznatovic, better known
as Arkan, had died and that two others with him had been shot. Arkan was
indicted for war crimes in Bosnia in September 1997. He was a longtime ally of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, McCain Spar on Taxes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush accused John McCain today of seeking a
$40 billion tax increase on the job benefits of American workers. The senator
retorted that the governor was trying a "Texas two-step" around his own failure
to plan for the future financing of Social Security. McCain is debating but not
campaigning for the Jan. 24 Iowa caucuses. Steve Forbes, Bush's closest
challenger in Iowa because of McCain's bypass strategy, also challenged Bush on
taxes. "In Texas, George, your tax cuts are more apparent than real," Forbes
said. "Most Texans have never seen those tax cuts."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Gore Leading in N.H.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New polling suggests Vice President Al Gore has slipped
past former Sen. Bill Bradley to retake a solid lead in their campaign for New
Hampshire's Democratic primary election, Newsweek reported today. The
newsmagazine said 50 percent of people who plan to vote in the Feb. 1 Democratic
primary favored Gore, while 36 percent preferred Bradley. The other 14 percent
were undecided. Newsweek said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., moved in the Republican
campaign from a statistical dead heat to a slight lead over the national
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rev. Jackson Rallies in Ill.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson used the birthday of slain civil
rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. as a rallying point today in his crusade
for six black students expelled from the Decatur school system. Speaking to
supporters at the Rainbow-PUSH Coalition's weekly meeting, Jackson reaffirmed
plans to appeal a judge's decision upholding the expulsions and geared up for a
rally tonight in Decatur. He contended the judge put "politics over principle"
in his ruling and said, "This is not the first time we've had to fight unjust
judges."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Marino's Season Ends With Thud
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Instead of the Super Bowl, Dan Marino may be
headed for retirement, thanks to the Jacksonville Jaguars, who buried the Miami
Dolphins 62-7 today in the second round of the AFC playoffs. Marino's final
statistics: 11 completions in 25 attempts for 95 yards, one fumble lost and two
interceptions. Was it his last game? "Don't ask me that question now," he said.
Coach Jimmy Johnson, who feuded frequently with Marino this season, is also
considering retirement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UCLA 71, No. 13 North Carolina 68
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Ryan Bailey connected on two free throws with 14.9
seconds left today as UCLA beat No. 13 North Carolina 71-68. Jerome Moiso led
UCLA (10-4) with 19 points. Jason Capel led the Tar Heels (11-6) with 21 points,
including his team's first 10 points of the second half. The Tarheels' Ed Cota's
eight assists gave him 891, moving him into 10th place on the NCAA's career
list.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY
</P>
