<HEADLINE> Congressman Pease Retiring  </HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES HOSKINSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rep. Ed Pease announced Saturday he will not seek
re-election to the congressional seat he has held since 1996, saying he wants to
devote more time to community service.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Events of the last two years have helped me focus on the things I want to
do most -- spend more time in the fields and forests of Indiana, with family and
friends, and actively engage in the volunteer life of the communities I love so
much,'' the Republican said at a news conference in Terre Haute.
</P>
<P>
	   Being hospitalized last year with an arterial blockage in his heart, the
impeachment of President Clinton that year and having recently been robbed on a
Washington street caused him to rethink his priorities and decide not to seek a
third term, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pease is the second Indiana Republican planning to leave Congress after this
year's election. U.S. Rep. David McIntosh, R-Muncie, is seeking the Republican
gubernatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The departure of two of the GOP's rising stars could make it even harder for
the party to keep its slim 222-212 majority in Congress, with one independent
who usually votes with the Democrats. More than 20 Republicans have announced
they are retiring at the end of this session, against a half-dozen Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
