<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans Demand Return of Elian Gonzalez
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Increasingly frustrated by 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez's
extended stay in the United States, an estimated 150,000 Cubans rallied to
demand the child's return. Cuban authorities say the delays only increase the
psychological suffering of a boy who lost his mother at sea and is now separated
from his father and grandparents in Cuba. Elian was found clinging to an inner
tube Nov. 25 off the Florida coast after his mother, stepfather and others died
in a failed attempt to reach U.S. shores.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Environmentalists Issue Annual Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The rise of the Internet and soaring stock markets
threaten to obscure "real-world" troubles such as crises in water supplies and
other resources, the Worldwatch Institute said in its State of the World 2000
report today. The report noted that the 20th century brought spectacular
technological achievements, boosted employment and helped fuel America's longest
peacetime economic expansion. But, it said, the expanding global economy is
outgrowing Earth's ecosystems. Since Worldwatch started its annual assessments
in 1984, its list of troublesome trends has lengthened to include rising
temperatures, melting glaciers, more destructive storms, and dying coral reefs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Wants More Money for Veterans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans a $1.5 billion increase in
spending for the nation's veterans, much of it aimed at improving health care
services, a senior congressional Democrat said today. Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill.,
the senior Democrat on the House Veterans Affairs Committee, said the
administration will request $46 billion for veterans' benefits and services.
That includes a request for a $1.5 billion increase in spending authority, much
of it targeted at expanding health care services, Evans said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chile Vote Too Close To Call
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Sunday's presidential election in Chile is so close
that not even pollsters will hazard a guess who will win: socialist Ricardo
Lagos or his rightist rival, Joaquin Lavin. Some 8 million Chileans are eligible
to cast ballots in a run-off vote for a new leader in this country, where the
economy is emerging from its deepest recession in 16 years. Lavin and Lagos
battled to a virtual draw in an initial ballot on Dec. 12. Lagos received 47.9
percent of the vote and Lavin received 47.5 percent. A simple majority was
needed to win outright.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russian Contenders Prepare for Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- With little more than two months until Russia's presidential
election, Communists and other Russian groups sketched out strategies Saturday
for their race against heavily favored acting President Vladimir Putin.
Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said he has a "good chance" of winning
the election. The reform-oriented Yabloko party formally nominated lawmaker
Grigory Yavlinsky as its candidate. All the candidates will be hard pressed to
beat Putin, who assumed power after Boris Yeltsin resigned Dec. 31 and called
early elections.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Delays West Bank Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel decided Saturday to postpone a withdrawal from the
West Bank for at least two weeks over a dispute with the Palestinians on the
land to be included in the pullout. The Palestinians have accused Israel of
neglecting the peace talks with them in favor of the Syrian negotiations, which
reopened in December and will continue Wednesday in the United States.
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Cabinet warned in a meeting Friday that
Israeli sluggishness in the negotiations will prevent the sides from working out
a framework on a final peace agreement by a Feb. 13 deadline.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bucs Advance to NFC Title Game
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Bucaneers beat the Washington Redskins
14-13 today to earn a spot in the NFC championship game. The victory sent the
Bucs into the title game for the first time since 1979. They will either travel
to St. Louis or play at home against Minnesota, depending on the outcome of
tomorrow's game. Earlier today, the Jacksonville Jaguars routed the Miami
Dolphins 62-7. The Jaguars will play host to the winner of tomorrow's game
between Indianapolis and Tennessee next week for the AFC championship.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rocker Booed, Cheered at Fla. Event
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) -- Shunned by some of his teammates, Atlanta Braves
reliever John Rocker received a mix of boos and cheers today in his first public
appearance since making inflammatory comments toward minorities, homosexuals and
foreigners. Rocker, playing in Dennis Martinez's second annual charity baseball
game at the University of Miami, signed autographs for fans. Later, he stood by
himself during warmups. "He spoke bad of everybody except for white people and
that's not right," New York Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez said.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY
</P>
