<HEADLINE> Mo. House Explodes, Kills One  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Explosions destroyed a home and scattered debris
over a wide area of a south Kansas City neighborhood Saturday. At least one
person was killed.
</P>
<P>
	   The blasts at a home set an adjacent house on fire.
</P>
<P>
	   The body of the victim was found in the house that exploded, said Fire
Department spokesman Pat Gilchrist. One person from that house was missing.
</P>
<P>
	   A large amount of explosive chemicals were found. Gilchrist said the type of
chemicals was unknown but they appeared to be powerful pyrotechnics that would
be used in making fireworks.
</P>
<P>
	   Fire officials said they did not know the cause of the explosions, but
speculated that it could have been a ruptured natural gas line or a
methamphetamine laboratory.
</P>
<P>
	   Wood, glass and other debris littered the streets in the area. Some
businesses close to the house that exploded had their windows blown out.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses in the area reported hearing a series of explosions.	   ``We
thought at first someone was shooting at the house, but then there was just a
real loud boom,'' said Dave Ross, who lives in the house on the other side of
the exploded house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
