<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Killed in Costa Rican Plan Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A plane carrying 20 people crashed into a house
in Costa Rica's capital Saturday, killing four people and injuring 15, including
one person in the house, emergency officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The twin-engine plane had just taken off from Tobia Bolanos Airport in San
Jose when it crashed at 1:10 p.m., Red Cross spokesman Guillermo Arroyo said.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane, a Czech-built LED 410 leased by Taxi Aero Centro Americano, was
bound for the Tortuguero national park on the Atlantic Coast of northern Costa
Rica. The plane carried 17 passengers and three crew members.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities did not release the nationalities or identities of the four
people who died.
</P>
<P>
	   The injured included six Spaniards, two Swiss, one American and one El
Salvadoran. Their identities were not immediately released. The others injured
were Costa Rican, Red Cross officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The injuries ranged from bruises to more serious trauma.
</P>
<P>
	   The pilot survived. There was no word on the other crew members.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane crashed into a home in San Jose's upscale Rohrmoser neighborhood,
injuring a housekeeper. Two other people in the house were not injured.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of the crash was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Similar accidents have occurred in recent years in the area near the
airport. In September 1998, a small plane crashed into a house, killing two
people aboard the aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
