<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serb Paramilitary Leader Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Masked gunmen opened fire in a hotel lobby
Saturday, killing a feared Serb paramilitary leader indicted by the U.N. war
crimes tribunal for alleged atrocities in Bosnia and Croatia. There was no word
of arrests, suspects or a motive. Zeljko Raznatovic, better known as Arkan, was
reputedly one of Serbia's wealthiest individuals, and a longtime ally of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. Arkan was indicted for war crimes in
Bosnia in September 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tax Arguments Dominate GOP Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Tax arguments dominated a 90-minute debate among the
six GOP candidates for the 2000 nomination today, the last Iowa confrontation
before the first votes of the year are cast in the Jan. 24 precinct caucuses.
George W. Bush accused John McCain of seeking a $40 billion tax increase on the
job benefits of American workers. The senator retorted that the governor was
trying a "Texas two-step" around his own failure to plan for the future
financing of Social Security. Steve Forbes called both Bush and McCain "the
timid tax cutters" of the Republican presidential campaign.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans Demand Return of Elian Gonzalez
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Increasingly frustrated by 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez's
extended stay in the United States, an estimated 150,000 Cubans rallied to
demand the child's return. Cuban authorities say the delays only increase the
psychological suffering of a boy who lost his mother at sea and is now separated
from his father and grandparents in Cuba. Elian was found clinging to an inner
tube Nov. 25 off the Florida coast after his mother, stepfather and others died
in a failed attempt to reach U.S. shores.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Black Activists Protest Immigration
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Black activists at a rally honoring Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
today called for an end to what they see as a double standard in U.S.
immigration policy that favors Cubans over Haitians. The group of about 150
people denounced Miami officials for going to Washington on behalf of 6-year-old
Cuban Elian Gonzalez while "not saying a word" about more than 400 would-be
immigrants shipped back to Haiti after their boat ran aground New Year's Day.
Under the 1966 Cuban Readjustment Act, Cubans who reach U.S. soil can stay. But
there is no such law for Haitians and others who arrive here illegally.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuadorean Indian Protest Flops
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Nationwide demonstrations planned by organizations
representing Ecuador's 4 million Indians failed to materialize Saturday. Protest
leaders, who are calling for the resignation of President Jamil Mahuad,
announced without explanation that the marches were being postponed until
Monday, or perhaps later. Meanwhile, Mahuad, under growing calls to step down
for his failure to stop Ecuador's economic decline, urged citizens to reject
violence and "political cannibalism" to resolve the Andean nation's economic and
political crisis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Environmentalists Issue Annual Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The rise of the Internet and soaring stock markets
threaten to obscure "real-world" troubles such as crises in water supplies and
other resources, the Worldwatch Institute said in its State of the World 2000
report today. The report noted that the 20th century brought spectacular
technological achievements, boosted employment and helped fuel America's longest
peacetime economic expansion. But, it said, the expanding global economy is
outgrowing Earth's ecosystems. Worldwatch started its annual assessments in
1984.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chile Vote Too Close To Call
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Sunday's presidential election in Chile is so close
that not even pollsters will hazard a prediction as to who will win: socialist
Ricardo Lagos or his rightist rival, Joaquin Lavin. Some 8 million Chileans are
eligible to cast ballots in a run-off vote for a new leader in this country,
where the economy is emerging from its deepest recession in 16 years. Lavin and
Lagos battled to a virtual draw in an initial ballot on Dec. 12. Lagos received
47.9 percent of the vote and Lavin received 47.5 percent. A simple majority was
needed to win outright.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bucs, Jags Win PLayoff Games
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Bucaneers beat the Washington Redskins
14-13 today to earn a spot in the NFC championship game. The victory sent the
Bucs into the title game for the first time since 1979. They will either travel
to St. Louis or play at home against Minnesota, depending on the outcome of
tomorrow's game. Earlier today, the Jacksonville Jaguars routed the Miami
Dolphins 62-7. The Jaguars will play host to the winner of tomorrow's game
between Indianapolis and Tennessee next week for the AFC championship.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY
</P>
</TEXT>
