<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal feted on 80th birthday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Cardinal John O'Connor's birthday party Saturday turned
into a major fund-raiser for donors eager to express their gratitude for his
contribution not only to the city but to the nation.
<P>
	   Praising his strength and wisdom, speakers honored O'Connor on his 80th
birthday, which raised $5.2 million for Catholic charities, including support
for parochial schools in the New York Archdiocese and funding for a seminary
position named for the cardinal.
</P>
<P>
	   But with speculation that O'Connor is in the twilight of his career as one
of the most powerful Catholics in the nation, the party at the Waldorf-Astoria
also served as a gathering for some of his possible successors.
</P>
<P>
	   Included among the 1,500 people attending were several men whose names have
been mentioned as O'Connor's possible successors: Archbishop Justin Rigali of
St. Louis; Archbishop Edwin O'Brien, who heads the archdiocese for the U.S.
Military; and Bishop Henry Mansell of Buffalo, a former top aide to O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor said he anticipates being relieved of his post in the near future,
and while saying he would like to stay until he dies, he still found humor in
the situation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I will soon be evicted. I don't know when it will be," said O'Connor,
speaking eloquently for about 15 minutes while drawing several standing ovations
and even more laughs. "I will have the distinction of bring the first living
cardinal to be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
	   He promised not to disappear from the public's view and will assist his
successor in any way that he can.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor turned the party's focus away from him and instead celebrated the
city he loves. He spoke fondly of New York and its many giving people,
especially those he said who do so quietly.
</P>
<P>
	   The dinner featured tributes to the cardinal, a speech by O'Connor, and a
video about his legacy.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor, who grew up in Philadelphia, was a military chaplain who served
briefly as the bishop of Scranton, Pa., before being named to head the New York
Archdiocese in 1984. He succeeded Cardinal Terence Cooke.
</P>
<P>
	   He is the oldest active bishop in the United States. The pope is expected to
replace him now that he has turned 80, the age at which cardinals lose their
power to vote for a new pope.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor also had a brain tumor removed in September and has missed a number
of public appearances, including Masses, since then. He stumbled twice in
November when mounting the steps to the pulpit, and has taken to sitting in a
chair near the high altar to avoid the stairs.
</P>
<P>
	   The guest list for his birthday dinner read like a Who's Who of Catholics in
America. In addition to Rigali, O'Brien and Mansell, the attendees were expected
to include Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark; Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua
of Philadelphia; Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston; Cardinal Adam Maida of Detroit;
Cardinal James Hickey of Washington; Cardinal Francis George of Chicago;
Archbishop Harry Flynn of St. Paul-Minneapolis; and the Papal Nuncio in
Washington D.C., Gabriel Montalvo.
</P>
<P>
	   Auxiliary Bishop James F. McCarthy, who once served as O'Connor's secretary
for 12 years, referred to the six cardinals attending the celebration.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's a measure of the respect of which he has had by the leaders of the
United States," McCarthy said. "This may be the last chance that everyone can
singularly point the spotlight on him and say, 'Way to go, John."'
</P>
<P>
	   Former Mayor Ed Koch, a close friend of the cardinal's, and Gov. George
Pataki, also attended.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the clergy are also expected to attend Sunday morning Mass at St.
Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
	   The dinner was chaired by three Wall Street investment bankers: Ted
Forstmann, senior partner of Forstmann Little &AMP; Co., and a well-known advocate
of school vouchers; David Komansky, CEO of Merrill Lynch; and Les Quick of Quick
&AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
	   Tickets were $1,000 a head but many guests made additional contributions.
The seminary position being funded by some of the proceeds is the John Cardinal
O'Connor Distinguished Chair in Hebrew Studies at St. Joseph's Seminary in
Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
	   It is designed to educate priests about the shared scriptural heritage of
Jews and Christians. Fostering better relations between Catholics and Jews has
been one of the cardinal's priorities.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor is also known for being a stalwart defender of the pope's hard line
on abortion and homosexuality. During his 16 years in New York, he has chastised
politicians who support abortion and ousted gay worshippers from parish
churches. But he's also sided with striking unions and gone into AIDS wards
anonymously to wash the hair of patients too sick to know who he was.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York Archdiocese serves 2.4 million Catholics in Manhattan, the
Bronx, Staten Island, Westchester, Rockland and five upstate counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
