<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans Rally for Return of Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Thousands of Cubans rallied angrily today expressing their
frustration over the delay of Elian Gonzalez's return. The government, which
organized the event and brought in the protesters, estimated the crowd at
150,000. A march of tens of thousands of mothers yesterday was also held for the
young boy, but today's gathering was more of a strident political meeting, held
at the street corner where Fidel Castro declared that his government was
socialist almost four decades ago.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serb Paramilitary Leader Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Masked gunmen opened fire in a hotel lobby
Saturday, killing a feared Serb paramilitary leader indicted by the U.N. war
crimes tribunal for alleged atrocities in Bosnia and Croatia. Zeljko Raznatovic,
better known as Arkan, was shot in the Belgrade Intercontinental Hotel and
rushed to a hospital for emergency surgery, police said. Arkan, 47, and his
paramilitary forces have been accused of involvement in atrocities during
Serbia's war with Croatia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Wants Confederate Flag Removed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NASHUA, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore said today the Confederate flag
should come down from public buildings because it divides Americans. Gore, in a
CNN interview with Jesse Jackson, said the flag represents "for many Americans a
hurtful message that recalls the pain of slavery" and it should not be flown
from the South Carolina Statehouse or other public buildings. Republican
candidates competing in the Feb. 19 South Carolina primary are asked about the
issue nearly every time they visit the state. Texas Gov. Bush says the question
is for people in South Carolina to decide, a point reinforced by his campaign
after Gore's criticisms.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fighting in Colombia Leaves 50 Dead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In some of the worst fighting in months, clashes
between leftist rebels and security forces near Bogota killed 50 people
Saturday, the same day Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited northern
Colombia. Rebels from the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC,
staged an early morning attack on Guayabetal, 30 miles southeast of Bogota,
Colombia's capital. The Colombian government and FARC also held peace talks
Saturday in a southern jungle. It was not clear if the rebel attack was meant as
a show of force to coincide with the peace talks or Albright's visit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Black Activists Protest Immigration Policy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Black activists at a rally honoring Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
today called for an end to what they see as a double standard in U.S.
immigration policy that favors Cubans over Haitians. The group of about 150
people denounced Miami officials for going to Washington on behalf of 6-year-old
Cuban Elian Gonzalez while "not saying a word" about more than 400 would-be
immigrants shipped back to Haiti after their boat ran aground New Year's Day.
Under the 1966 Cuban Readjustment Act, Cubans who reach U.S. soil can stay. But
there is no such law for Haitians and others who arrive here illegally.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuadorean Indian Protest Fails
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Nationwide demonstrations planned by organizations
representing Ecuador's 4 million Indians failed to materialize Saturday. Protest
leaders, who are calling for the resignation of President Jamil Mahuad,
announced without explanation that the marches were being postponed until
Monday, or perhaps later. Meanwhile, Mahuad, under growing calls to step down
for his failure to stop Ecuador's economic decline, urged citizens to reject
violence and "political cannibalism" to resolve the Andean nation's economic and
political crisis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ga. Tech Beats No. 18 Maryland 69-68
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- Georgia Tech's Shaun Fein knocked down two critical free
throws with 53 seconds remaining, and No. 18 Maryland couldn't get off a shot at
the end, falling to the Yellow Jackets 69-68 tonight. Juan Dixon scored a
career-high 31 points and blocked a shot by Fein with about 15 seconds left.
Maryland got the ball back to Dixon, who drove in the lane but had the ball
knocked away by a horde of defenders as the clock ran out. Maryland (11-5)
dropped to 0-3 in the Atlantic Coast Conference for the first time since
1995-96, which also was the last season the Terrapins lost to Tech (8-7, 1-2).
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Celtics Beat Nets 99-96
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Antoine Walker scored 14 of his season-high 39
points in the fourth quarter to lead the Boston Celtics to a 99-96 victory over
New Jersey tonight. He had a steal and the game-clinching dunk on a New Jersey
inbounds play with 16 seconds to go. Walker, who had not scored more than 19
points in the last five games, also got the rebound of Stephon Marbury's drive
in the closing seconds, and later added a free throw in ending the Nets'
three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
