<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 8 Kansas 97, Nebraska 82  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG TUCKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Luke Axtell scored 15 points and No. 8 Kansas
remained unbeaten at home with a 97-82 victory over Nebraska on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Axtell, a 6-foot-10 transfer from Texas, made three 3-pointers and hit a
pair of free throws that kept the Jayhawks (14-2 overall, 3-0 Big 12) in charge
with a 66-46 lead with 12:43 remaining. It was the first time Axtell had led his
new team in scoring.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cornhuskers (7-9, 0-3), trying to avert their first 0-3 start in the
conference in seven years, trailed by only two until Kansas went on a 17-2 run
at the end of the first half. The Jayhawks then scored the first four points of
the second half to open a 53-32 lead.
</P>
<P>
	   Until then, the biggest lead Kansas could manage was eight when Axtell made
a 3-pointer for a 32-24 lead. The Huskers then scored the next six points and
trimmed the lead to 32-30 before Kenny Gregory's bucket and Kirk Hinrich's
3-pointer ignited the 17-2 run in the last three minutes of the half.
</P>
<P>
	   Nebraska, 1-16 in its last 17 trips to Allen Fieldhouse, was led by Kimani
Ffriend's 23 points and 14 rebounds. Gary Cochran had 17 points, including five
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
	   Louis Truscott's free throw sliced Kansas' lead to 60-45 before Drew Gooden
hit a pair of free throws and Axtell followed with two more. Gooden, a 6-foot-9
freshman, brought the sellout crowd of more than 16,000 to its feet with a
follow shot at the 11:47 mark that gave the Jayhawks a 69-48 lead.
</P>
<P>
	   A few minutes later, reserve Ashante Johnson scored six of Kansas' next
eight points as the Jayhawks improved to 8-0 at home.
</P>
<P>
	   Gooden and Gregory had 14 points for Kansas, while Nick Collison had 13.
</P>
<P>
	   The Huskers outrebounded Kansas 55-48.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
