<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Rallies for Ill. Students  </HEADLINE>
   By SARA BAKER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DECATUR, Ill. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson used the birthday of slain
civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. Saturday as a rallying point in his
crusade for six black students expelled from the Decatur school system.
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson has said the expulsions were not a racial issue. But while speaking
to hundreds of people packed in the Church of the Living God on Saturday night,
he called the expulsions a black and white issue.
</P>
<P>
	   He pointed to recent studies that show ``zero tolerance'' discipline
policies imposed in schools amid fears of mass shootings and riots are having a
disproportionate impact on black students.
</P>
<P>
	   He also pointed to figures showing that 82 percent of students the Decatur
school district has expelled are black, even though black students comprise only
about 46 percent of Decatur's public school population.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Decatur is symbolic of a national crisis,'' Jackson said. ``Youth are
being expelled disproportionately and jailed disproportionately without a plan
to educate them.''
</P>
<P>
	   Jackson added that what is happening in Decatur is the biggest civil rights
movement in America today.
</P>
<P>
	   The six Decatur teens were expelled for up to two years as the result of a
bleacher-clearing fight at a football game in September. After intervention by
Jackson and the governor, the city's school board cut the time to one year and
let the six teens attend alternative schools.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to supporters at a Rainbow-PUSH Coalition weekly meeting in Chicago
earlier in the day, Jackson reaffirmed plans to appeal a judge's decision
upholding the expulsions.
</P>
<P>
	   But Jackson said the punishment was still too harsh for a fight that
involved no weapons or drugs and that hurt no one seriously. He said he would
ask the school board on Tuesday to reinstate a seventh student who withdrew from
school rather than face expulsion. Jackson says the teen-ager was being hit and
was not fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-15-00 2354 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
