<DOCNO> APW20000115.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Saturday, Jan. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Delay Sparks Angry Rally
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- In the same the street corner where Fidel Castro declared
that his government was socialist, thousands of Cubans angrily protested Friday
the delay of Elian Gonzalez's return. The government, which organized the event
and brought in the protesters, estimated the crowd at 150,000. The gathering
came one day after a deadline the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
had set for Elian to be returned to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who lives
in Cuba. Because of the historical significance of the site and the political
nature of the gathering, many demonstrators had thought Castro would attend, but
he did not.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Marine Accused of Rape in Japan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- A U.S. Marine has been arrested and accused of trying to rape
a Japanese woman at a disco on the Japanese island of Okinawa, police said.
Lance Cpl. Oswald McDonald, 29, dragged the woman into a corner of the disco
Friday and attempted to sexually assault her, a spokesman for the Okinawa
Prefectural police said. The arrest in Okinawa city came just months after the
U.S. military lifted a four-year curfew barring service members from the city
center. The ban, lifted in October, was meant to curtail fights and drunkenness.
The curfew was imposed in October 1995, a month after three U.S. servicemen
raped a 12-year-old Okinawan schoolgirl on another part of the island. The crime
triggered protests against the U.S. military presence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nigeria Troops Stay in Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KOIDU, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Nigeria has halted the pullout of intervention
troops from Sierra Leone to help keep the fragile peace in the country until a
U.N. force is fully deployed, officials said Saturday. Maj. Gen. Gabriel Pamba,
a commander of the Nigerian-led West African intervention force known as ECOMOG,
said the troops would remain in place to prevent a dangerous power vacuum in
Sierra Leone, where the rebel group Revolutionary United Front and government
forces signed a peace accord in July. Despite the accord, the rebels continue to
terrorize civilians in the dense jungle interior.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Says Pinochet's Outlook Grim
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- The independent medical team examining Gen. Augusto Pinochet
concluded he would die "long before" the expected 18 months needed to complete
his extradition to Spain on torture charges, The Sunday Telegraph reported. Last
week, Home Secretary Jack Straw said he was inclined to stop extradition
proceedings against Pinochet after four specialists unanimously found the
84-year-old general unfit to stand trial. Pinochet requires a pacemaker and has
reportedly suffered from two mild strokes, diabetes, heart disease and
depression.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serb Paramilitary Leader Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Masked gunmen opened fire in a hotel lobby
Saturday, killing a feared Serb paramilitary leader indicted by the U.N. war
crimes tribunal for alleged atrocities in Bosnia and Croatia. Zeljko Raznatovic,
better known as Arkan, was shot in the Belgrade Intercontinental Hotel and
rushed to a hospital for emergency surgery, police said. Arkan, 47, and his
paramilitary forces have been accused of involvement in atrocities during
Serbia's war with Croatia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jackson Rallies for Ill. Students
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DECATUR, Ill. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson used the birthday of slain
civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. Saturday as a rallying point in his
crusade for six black students expelled from the Decatur school system. The six
Decatur teens were expelled for up to two years as the result of a
bleacher-clearing fight at a football game in September. After intervention by
Jackson and the governor, the city's school board cut the time to one year and
let the six teens attend alternative schools.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils Beats Flyers 4-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Patrik Elias had a goal and an assist and Martin
Brodeur made 30 saves Saturday night as the New Jersey Devils beat Philadelphia
4-1, snapping the Flyers' 15-game home-unbeaten streak. Philadelphia, which had
gone 12-0-3 during its run, the longest in the NHL this season, played without
captain Eric Lindros, who sustained the third concussion of his career at
Atlanta on Friday night. Both teams had unbeaten streaks snapped by losses on
Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockets Beat Bulls 93-90
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Steve Francis matched a career high with 27 points -- 23 in
the first half-- and had 11 assists as the Rockets held on to beat the Bulls
93-90. Toni Kukoc scored 29 points for the Bulls, who have lost three straight
following a three-game winning streak. Brand did OK, too, adding 15 points to go
with 11 rebounds. Francis didn't score as much in the second half because the
Bulls had to double team him after he erupted for 19 first-quarter points,
including a spectacular 10-point spurt in the final 69 seconds as the Rockets
built a 17-point lead they never lost.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
</TEXT>
